00:00:36.910 --> 00:00:40.890
[Matt]: What's really interesting is if you
look at sort of sleep, and we've done some

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:45.200
of this work, and I maybe will speak about
it on sleep and motor skill learning, and

00:00:45.200 --> 00:00:50.340
that seems to be more dependent on this sort
of lighter form of non-REM sleep Stage 2 and

00:00:50.340 --> 00:00:55.399
particularly the burst of electrical activity
the sleep spindles, there's a really bizarre

00:00:55.399 --> 00:01:01.850
bump in Stage 2 and sleep spindles during
development, it happens right around the 12-month

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:08.370
period, which is where, all of a sudden, you
start to see considerable limb or multi-limb

00:01:08.370 --> 00:01:13.270
coordination. In other words, you start to
perambulate, you start to learn how to walk.

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:18.159
It's almost as though there's like a homeostatic
response, which is that with the drive for

00:01:18.159 --> 00:01:23.979
motor plasticity and learning comes a response
from sleep to say, "Oh, now we're into motor

00:01:23.979 --> 00:01:28.640
skill learning? We need to consolidate." And
you get this...it's a really strange bump,

00:01:28.640 --> 00:01:29.700
and it dies away again after the...

00:01:29.700 --> 00:01:33.509
[Rhonda]: What's the sleep, the spindles,
sleep two spindles, what stage is that?

00:01:33.509 --> 00:01:37.950
[Matt]: Well, you see sleep spindles throughout
almost all of non-REM. So once you get past

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:43.250
the lightest sort of Stage 1 on REM, then
you get spindles throughout all of non-REM,

00:01:43.250 --> 00:01:49.860
but they are a prototypical feature of Stage
2 non-REM as well. Then Stage 3 and 4, which

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:55.820
is sort of like the deep sleep stuff, you
also get spindles there, too. But in our hands,

00:01:55.820 --> 00:02:01.880
at least, the strongest sleep stage and the
strongest electrical signature in your EEG

00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:06.990
that is predictive of your motor skill learning
is Stage 2 and sleep spindles, both of which

00:02:06.990 --> 00:02:13.209
seem to have this bizarre sort of, you know,
coincidental spike right around this developmental

00:02:13.209 --> 00:02:15.549
phase of crawling, standing, walking.

00:02:15.549 --> 00:02:20.499
[Rhonda]: Yeah. So many things going on during
the development. I mean, it's so fascinating

00:02:20.499 --> 00:02:21.599
to observe for sure.

00:02:21.599 --> 00:02:26.659
[Matt]: And language, too. I mean, when we've
looked at this as well with teaching adults

00:02:26.659 --> 00:02:34.099
foreign languages, or even actually just mathematical
languages or artificial grammar, sleep is

00:02:34.099 --> 00:02:39.590
a huge component in that. But they also saw
this fascinating thing with development, which

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:46.370
was about not just concrete learning of individual
facts but the generalization of knowledge.

00:02:46.370 --> 00:02:51.790
So this is sort of the thing that I think
separates us from computers, at least for

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:57.029
now, which is that computers are very good
at storing individual bytes of information

00:02:57.029 --> 00:03:02.139
in a vertical way very clearly. And we can
do that, too, storing individual facts. But

00:03:02.139 --> 00:03:06.819
what computers don't do, which is what we
do, is intelligently integrate and associate

00:03:06.819 --> 00:03:13.339
them together so that we can extract overarching
patterns and schemas and statistical rules

00:03:13.339 --> 00:03:16.329
about this thing called the world in which
we live.

00:03:16.329 --> 00:03:23.209
And, yeah, sorry, I was just gonna say that
you can, with infants, you can teach them

00:03:23.209 --> 00:03:30.079
just these novel sounds, and each one of these
strings of sounds is unique and different.

00:03:30.079 --> 00:03:35.420
But there's something common about the grammar
that is binding and overarching across all

00:03:35.420 --> 00:03:39.819
of them. There is an overarching schema that
you could learn in addition to each one of

00:03:39.819 --> 00:03:41.030
the individual facts.

00:03:41.030 --> 00:03:49.459
After they've had a nap versus an infant that
has not had a nap, post-nap, the infants have

00:03:49.459 --> 00:03:54.370
extracted and understood the generalized rules
of what they've been learning, not just the

00:03:54.370 --> 00:04:00.489
individual facts. Whereas infants that have
learned but haven't napped have not sort of

00:04:00.489 --> 00:04:01.489
made the abstraction.

00:04:01.489 --> 00:04:05.019
[Rhonda]: So my being on nap nazzi, I should
be rewarded for that, right?

00:04:05.019 --> 00:04:06.019
[Matt]: Absolutely.

00:04:06.019 --> 00:04:07.029
[Rhonda]: It's absolutely like...

00:04:07.029 --> 00:04:11.060
[Matt]: And it stays from the, you know, infancy
all the way through to adulthood. So if you're

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:14.999
napping, I'm not gonna...well, there's a few
double-edged sword aspects of napping.

00:04:14.999 --> 00:04:18.820
[Rhonda]: So I wanted to ask you a question,
you're talking about basically being able

00:04:18.820 --> 00:04:25.319
to connect the dots, you know, how would that
sort of differentiates us from what a computer

00:04:25.319 --> 00:04:30.420
can do, I mean, one of the things. But is
there a certain...I remember reading in your

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:36.509
book, and this is probably the part of the
book that I was more skimming, you know, like...and

00:04:36.509 --> 00:04:43.700
that was the importance of REM sleep and dreaming
and creativity. So is that, connecting...because

00:04:43.700 --> 00:04:49.560
I feel like connecting the dots, you know,
requires some creative thought to be able

00:04:49.560 --> 00:04:53.650
to kind of, like, put things together and
come up with a big-picture idea and figure

00:04:53.650 --> 00:04:57.379
things out. So is it known? Is REM sleep important
for that?

00:04:57.379 --> 00:05:01.950
[Matt]: Yeah, it does seem to be. So if there
is...So, I mean, we could take a step back

00:05:01.950 --> 00:05:08.849
and think about how does sleep achieve memory
processing, learning, information processing.

00:05:08.849 --> 00:05:15.490
And sleep seems to be important in at least
three ways. First, you need sleep before learning

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:20.120
to actually get your brain ready to initially
soak up new information, to initially lay

00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:23.180
down new memory traces.

00:05:23.180 --> 00:05:29.540
But you also then need to sleep after learning
to take those freshly-minted memories in the

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:33.610
brain, particularly in a region that we call
the hippocampus, which you could think of

00:05:33.610 --> 00:05:37.939
almost like the informational inbox of your
brain, but it's very good at receiving those

00:05:37.939 --> 00:05:43.939
sort of new memory files. But you need sleep
after learning to take those new memories

00:05:43.939 --> 00:05:49.479
and then essentially hit the save button on
them so that you don't forget those informational

00:05:49.479 --> 00:05:56.100
pieces of the puzzle. So sleep before learning
to get your brain ready, to acquire information.

00:05:56.100 --> 00:05:59.240
Sleep after learning to hold on to those individual
facts.

00:05:59.240 --> 00:06:04.560
[Rhonda]: So let me get this straight. So
if you want, for example, short-term memory,

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:09.819
right, because if you're sort of wanting to
store things in the hippocampus, even short-term,

00:06:09.819 --> 00:06:10.930
that would be sleep before.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:11.930
[Matt]: That's right.

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:16.190
[Rhonda]: And then if you want to then consolidate
it and have a long-term memory, that would

00:06:16.190 --> 00:06:17.340
be your sleep after?

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:18.340
[Matt]: Sleep after.

00:06:18.340 --> 00:06:19.340
[Rhonda]: Okay.

00:06:19.340 --> 00:06:23.909
[Matt]: So you can't cheat sleep on either
side of the memory equation. You've got to...You

00:06:23.909 --> 00:06:28.180
can't pull the all-nighter and hope to be
able to continue to learn. And we did this

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:32.570
study. We said sort of, you know, "Is it wise
to pull the all-nighter before the exam?"

00:06:32.570 --> 00:06:37.229
So we took a group of individuals, assign
them to one of two groups, a sleep group and

00:06:37.229 --> 00:06:41.900
a sleep deprivation group. A sleep group,
they get a full eight hours of shut-eye that

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:48.590
we measure here at the sleep center. The deprivation
group we keep awake all night under full supervision.

00:06:48.590 --> 00:06:53.460
And they don't get any naps. There's no caffeine.
It's miserable for everyone involved.

00:06:53.460 --> 00:06:55.069
[Rhonda]: Wow. No caffeine.

00:06:55.069 --> 00:06:59.492
[Matt]: No caffeine at all. And then the next
day, we place them inside an MRI scanner,

00:06:59.492 --> 00:07:04.990
and we had them try and learn, and cram, essentially,
a whole list of new facts into the brain,

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:11.030
into the hippocampus. And the first result
was that the sleep deprivation group was about

00:07:11.030 --> 00:07:18.939
40% more deficient in their learning ability.
So they learned 40% less, four zero, which

00:07:18.939 --> 00:07:19.939
is...

00:07:19.939 --> 00:07:20.939
[Rhonda]: That's astronomical. That's a huge...

00:07:20.939 --> 00:07:23.900
[Matt]: Non-trivial. I mean, if you want to
put that in context, I guess it's the difference

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:29.330
between acing an exam and failing at miserably
40%. What was interesting, though, is what

00:07:29.330 --> 00:07:34.560
was going on in the hippocampus, this informational
inbox of the brain. When we looked at that

00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:39.400
in those people who'd had a full night of
sleep, you saw lots of healthy learning-related

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:42.030
activity. It was beautiful.

00:07:42.030 --> 00:07:47.940
In the sleep deprivation group, we actually
couldn't find any significant signal whatsoever.

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:55.249
And so it was almost as though sleep deprivation
had sort of shut-down-your-memory inbox and

00:07:55.249 --> 00:08:00.090
any new incoming files were being bounced.
And we put forward a theory as to why that

00:08:00.090 --> 00:08:05.900
was. Perhaps that the hippocampus being a
short-term reservoir of memory has a limited

00:08:05.900 --> 00:08:11.099
storage capacity, perhaps a little bit like
a USB stick.

00:08:11.099 --> 00:08:18.760
And you have maybe, in humans, a 16-hour recording
capacity for information acquisition before

00:08:18.760 --> 00:08:26.270
you have to sleep. Because it's during sleep,
then after learning. So that's sort of the

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:30.550
story before learning. It's not great. We
can show it. We know in the brain what part

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:33.039
of the brain is failing to produce those impairments.

00:08:33.039 --> 00:08:36.089
[Rhonda]: In that study, you were testing
the ability to acquire new information.

00:08:36.089 --> 00:08:41.419
[Matt]: Exactly, to sort of lay down those
fresh memories and just to grab hold of them.

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:47.470
And you can't do that well without sufficient
sleep. And that seems to be in part related

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:52.519
to your non-rapid-eye-movement sleep or your
non-REM sleep.

00:08:52.519 --> 00:08:57.040
But then, what we've also done in lots of
these, and we and lots of other people have

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:03.560
now replicated this finding, sleep after learning
then takes those memories and it sort of it

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:08.000
hits the save button on them. It's a little
bit crass. Actually, what really happens is

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:14.029
that during sleep, there is a file transfer
mechanism that takes place at night, that

00:09:14.029 --> 00:09:19.220
we shift memories from that short-term vulnerable
storage reservoir, the hippocampus, and we

00:09:19.220 --> 00:09:24.180
move them out to the long-term storage site
within the brain, which is the cortex, which

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:26.820
essentially acts like a hard drive.

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:32.899
And that means that when you wake up the next
day, there are two delightful benefits. First,

00:09:32.899 --> 00:09:37.579
having shifted those memories from the short-term
vulnerable reservoir to that more permanent

00:09:37.579 --> 00:09:42.890
sort of safe storage haven in the brain. They're
protected, and they're safe, so that you're

00:09:42.890 --> 00:09:44.130
going to remember rather than forget.

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:50.650
The second benefit, however, is that sort
of having cleared off those files from the

00:09:50.650 --> 00:09:56.300
hippocampus, almost like shifting files from
the USB stick, you've cleared out all of that

00:09:56.300 --> 00:10:01.190
fresh memory encoding reservoir, so that when
you wake up the next morning, you can start

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:07.480
acquiring new files all over again. So it's
this sort of elegant, symbiotic system of

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:09.269
memory that happens.

00:10:09.269 --> 00:10:10.680
[Rhonda]: Yeah, beautiful.

00:10:10.680 --> 00:10:12.570
[Matt]: Yeah, absolutely. Sorry.

00:10:12.570 --> 00:10:15.389
[Rhonda]: We'll, of course, use all this.

00:10:15.389 --> 00:10:19.779
[Matt]: I'm ethically sealed[sp]. It's bizarre.

00:10:19.779 --> 00:10:26.070
[Rhonda]: I remember reading somewhere that
when you sleep, and this is related to what

00:10:26.070 --> 00:10:31.450
you were just talking about, that your brain
sort of replays, like, electrical-activity-wise,

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:36.510
it looks like you're literally, like, reliving
the same thing you just learned or something.

00:10:36.510 --> 00:10:37.510
Is that...

00:10:37.510 --> 00:10:41.470
[Matt]: That's absolutely correct. So these
studies firstly happened in animals, and we've

00:10:41.470 --> 00:10:46.970
now been replicating some of them with brain
imaging, with MRI scans in humans. Hard to

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:51.820
believe, but we can do it. But the original
findings were fascinating. They would place

00:10:51.820 --> 00:10:57.139
electrodes into that structure that we spoke
about, the hippocampus, which also rats have

00:10:57.139 --> 00:11:01.910
as well, and it helps rats learn spatial navigation.

00:11:01.910 --> 00:11:05.529
And they would place lots of electrodes into
this part of the brain. And as the rat would

00:11:05.529 --> 00:11:11.440
run around the maze and learn the maze, individual
cells would fire, and they would spatially

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:17.170
code which part of the maze the rat was in.
So different cells are mapping different parts.

00:11:17.170 --> 00:11:22.079
It's like sort of navigating a route from
your home to work. Different sort of cells

00:11:22.079 --> 00:11:24.250
are coding the journey along the way.

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:26.880
[Rhonda]: Yeah. I'd probably would suck at
doing that, but...

00:11:26.880 --> 00:11:30.839
[Matt]: I think, yeah, yeah. I lost that.
Yeah, some people say it's a male aspect of

00:11:30.839 --> 00:11:35.160
the gene, but I definitely lost it. Anyway,
but what is delightful was that you could

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:40.590
sort of hang, you know, a sound tone on each
one of these electrodes. And what you would

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:47.501
hear, and this is just, you know, for audio,
you would hear sort of "buh buh buh bump,

00:11:47.501 --> 00:11:50.720
buh buh buh bump, buh buh buh bump," as the
rat was running around the maze, as these

00:11:50.720 --> 00:11:55.490
cells were learning, encoding, and creating
this kind of memory circuit essentially.

00:11:55.490 --> 00:12:01.440
And, yeah, you know, "buh buh buh bump," off
it goes. But what was genius is that they

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:09.350
kept recording. And as the rat fell asleep,
what did they hear? And it wasn't just static

00:12:09.350 --> 00:12:16.209
random firing, which is what we thought typically
happens during sleep. In that static of electrical

00:12:16.209 --> 00:12:22.700
impulses at night, in a sea of electrical
noise, came out a very clear, predictive,

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:29.160
message, which was "brrrmp, brrrmp, brrrmp."
It was exactly the same temporal sequence

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:33.910
"buh buh buh bump, buh buh buh bump, buh buh
buh bump," but it was sped up. And we now

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:40.130
know that it's during sleep that we replay,
but we replay at somewhere between 10 to 20

00:12:40.130 --> 00:12:42.110
times the speed.

00:12:42.110 --> 00:12:45.860
So it's as though you're kind of, you know,
you've done the, you know, recording of whatever

00:12:45.860 --> 00:12:51.310
happened during the day, but then it gets
replayed but at times 20 or times 10. "Brrrp,

00:12:51.310 --> 00:12:52.310
brrrp, brrrp, brrrp, brrrp."

00:12:52.310 --> 00:12:55.550
[Rhonda]: Wow. So is this is a long-term potentiation
part? Is this where it's solidifying?

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:56.550
[Matt]: Yeah.

00:12:56.550 --> 00:12:57.870
[Rhonda]: Now what stage of sleep is that?
I know you mentioned...

00:12:57.870 --> 00:13:00.149
[Matt]: So that's during deep non-REM sleep.

00:13:00.149 --> 00:13:01.149
[Rhonda]: Deep.

00:13:01.149 --> 00:13:02.149
[Matt]: Yup, that we see that.

00:13:02.149 --> 00:13:05.209
[Rhonda]: It's the sleep I'm always trying
to optimize for, and it's just so difficult.

00:13:05.209 --> 00:13:09.610
[Matt]: And it's difficult, you know, I think...Well,
sleep in general is difficult for so many

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:14.589
people, and we can speak why. So this starts
to come back to your original question about

00:13:14.589 --> 00:13:20.899
REM sleep, though. So we get this memory replay.
It's absolutely fascinating. We can now see

00:13:20.899 --> 00:13:25.370
it in humans. We can even manipulate it, which
is amazing.

00:13:25.370 --> 00:13:30.860
So if I teach you some information on a screen.
Let's say it's about a particular object,

00:13:30.860 --> 00:13:37.290
like a fire engine, and you have to try and
learn both the object and the spatial location

00:13:37.290 --> 00:13:43.529
of that on a screen. And then tomorrow, we're
going to sort of come back. And I'm just going

00:13:43.529 --> 00:13:48.819
to show you the image and say, "Do you remember
seeing it or not, yes or no?" And if you do

00:13:48.819 --> 00:13:53.259
remember seeing it, you've got to place where
you thought it was on the screen. So you have

00:13:53.259 --> 00:13:56.360
to learn the item, and you have to learn the
associated location.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:14:01.380
But here's the great part. During the initial
learning session, before you slept, not only

00:14:01.380 --> 00:14:06.440
do you see the fire engine but we play the
sound of the fire engine, like a fire engine

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:12.040
ring. And then we show you a kettle. It's
whistling. We show you a cat. It's meowing.

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:18.680
So each of these items that you're making
has a contextual cue associated with it, a

00:14:18.680 --> 00:14:24.139
sound. And it's a congruent sound, fire engine
sound, fire engine, kettle sound.

00:14:24.139 --> 00:14:29.930
And here's the fun part. I can teach you a
hundred of these items, and then during sleep,

00:14:29.930 --> 00:14:35.940
I'm going to replay those sounds that you
heard as if I'm trying to get into your brain

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:41.019
and I'm selectively reactivating each one
of those individual memories. But I'm only

00:14:41.019 --> 00:14:48.250
going to reactivate and replay half of those
memories. I'm gonna go to replay 50 of 100

00:14:48.250 --> 00:14:49.759
things that you've learned.

00:14:49.759 --> 00:14:54.360
And then the next day, we wake you up, and
we test you. And firstly, your memory is better

00:14:54.360 --> 00:14:58.769
after sleep. And that's what we found. What's
interesting is that for those items that I

00:14:58.769 --> 00:15:06.279
replayed during sleep, they are almost twice
as superior in terms of your memory retention.

00:15:06.279 --> 00:15:08.980
[Rhonda]: So the playing of them doesn't disrupt
the sleep at all or...?

00:15:08.980 --> 00:15:14.930
[Matt]: Well, that's the key. You have to
play at a sub-threshold-awakening sound. So

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:20.320
we will test your auditory threshold, and
we will then play the sound at a level that

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:26.420
we know is below your awakening threshold.
So it's still just enough to get in to penetrate

00:15:26.420 --> 00:15:29.820
into the brain and tickle the memory and reactivate
it...

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:30.820
[Rhonda]: That's fascinating.

00:15:30.820 --> 00:15:33.949
[Matt]: ...but it's not enough to wake you
up. So now, you know, you could imagine, you

00:15:33.949 --> 00:15:38.820
know, I've got these science fiction ideas
of thinking, well, I learned all of this information,

00:15:38.820 --> 00:15:44.000
and maybe I can just put my favorite playlist
on, you know, at night at low sound and, you

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.259
know, stimulate these memories. Or could it
be a study aid where you, you know, help students,

00:15:48.259 --> 00:15:49.329
like, sci-fi stuff?

00:15:49.329 --> 00:15:53.810
[Rhonda]: So you think coupling different
sounds maybe with, you know, learning facts,

00:15:53.810 --> 00:15:55.089
it may actually help...

00:15:55.089 --> 00:15:56.089
[Matt]: Yeah.

00:15:56.089 --> 00:15:59.660
[Rhonda]: Like irrespective of replaying them,
like, during sleep, do you think just even

00:15:59.660 --> 00:16:02.730
the coupling of the sound somehow can help,
can remember your...?

00:16:02.730 --> 00:16:07.639
[Matt]: As long as those sounds have been
coupled and bounced to specific information.

00:16:07.639 --> 00:16:11.950
And this is what we call context-dependent
or key-dependent memory. This is well known

00:16:11.950 --> 00:16:16.839
in psychology over about 100 years. If you
study in the room that you're going to take

00:16:16.839 --> 00:16:22.140
the exam, you do better, because you actually
use cues, contextual cues from around the

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:25.000
room that are triggers to help you better
remember.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.000
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.000
[Matt]: We're just doing that with sleep.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:32.470
[Rhonda]: What about caffeine? So if you study
caffeinated and you don't take your exam caffeinated.

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:34.180
Is this kind of the same concept?

00:16:34.180 --> 00:16:38.700
[Matt]: We don't know about caffeine. It's
an interesting thing. Caffeine may be a...it's

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:45.139
a nonspecific stimulant, whether it works
with ingested substances. We know, however,

00:16:45.139 --> 00:16:49.920
this works also with odors. So have you ever
had that experience where you're sort of in

00:16:49.920 --> 00:16:54.430
an airport and you're sort of tying your shoelaces
at the security, someone walks past with that

00:16:54.430 --> 00:17:00.520
cologne or a perfume of a person you knew,
and it instantly unlocks that memory, as if

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:04.810
the sound has triggered the reactivation of
the memory, and it comes flooding back.

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:09.340
Well, you can do the same thing with this
memory and sleep trick, where I teach you

00:17:09.340 --> 00:17:15.540
stuff during the day, and we can puff certain
odors up your nose and associate the smell

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:20.870
with the learning material. And then during
sleep, you reperfuse the odor up the nose...

00:17:20.870 --> 00:17:21.870
[Rhonda]: Oh, really?

00:17:21.870 --> 00:17:25.430
[Matt]: ...and you can get the same benefit
as well, the same doubling of the benefit.

00:17:25.430 --> 00:17:29.650
[Rhonda]: Wow, that's fascinating. I remember
this study that was done, that was coupling

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:35.730
an odor, it was like a cherry blossom odor,
with an electrical shock. So those, you know,

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:42.790
classical fear studies that they do in mice,
it was in rodents. And there was some sort

00:17:42.790 --> 00:17:49.090
of epigenetic change that the breathing of
the odor, or the cherry blossom, was inducing.

00:17:49.090 --> 00:17:54.140
That was like changing some receptor on the
glucocorticoid receptors. So it was getting

00:17:54.140 --> 00:17:58.120
passed on to, like, the next generation. And
so even though the next generation didn't

00:17:58.120 --> 00:18:03.480
have the shock and the coupling of the smell,
you know, if they were exposed to the smell,

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:04.480
they have the fear.

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:07.380
[Matt]: The critical memory was translated
from one generation to the next.

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:10.690
[Rhonda]: Yeah. So, anyways, it'd be fascinating.
You don't know what role sleep plays in the

00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:11.800
epigenetic transfer.

00:18:11.800 --> 00:18:15.430
[Matt]: Right. So if we all start doing this,
you know, are our children going to be incredible

00:18:15.430 --> 00:18:20.010
memory replayers, you know, by the way of...But
to come back to your...I'm sorry I've taken

00:18:20.010 --> 00:18:24.810
a desperately long time to answer your original
question, which was what about REM sleep.

00:18:24.810 --> 00:18:29.900
So what we've spoken about is the first two
of the three stages of memory processing with

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:34.060
sleep, sleep before to get the brain ready
to lay down memories, sleep after to grab

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:38.950
a hold of those individual memories and cement
them into the neural architecture of the brain.

00:18:38.950 --> 00:18:44.540
Once you've done that, though, there's a final
step. And that seemed to not depend on deep

00:18:44.540 --> 00:18:48.930
non-REM sleep but instead depend on rapid
eye movement sleep or REM sleep, which is

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:52.060
what most of us know as dream sleep.

00:18:52.060 --> 00:18:58.060
And it's during dream sleep that your brain
essentially performs informational alchemy,

00:18:58.060 --> 00:19:03.680
is what I would describe it as. It's a little
bit like group therapy for memories that sleep

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:08.670
has gathered in all of the information during
the day. And during non-REM sleep, which always

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:13.370
comes first, by the way, in our sleep cycle.
We always have non-REM sleep first, then REM

00:19:13.370 --> 00:19:17.280
sleep second, then non-REM sleep again, then
REM sleep second.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:24.470
And we don't know why there is no good explanatory
data suggesting why non-REM sleep always comes

00:19:24.470 --> 00:19:30.320
first and REM sleep comes second. But I've
put forward the theory that, for information

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:35.280
processing, it makes sense. Which is that
non-REM sleep first to just get what you've

00:19:35.280 --> 00:19:41.290
learned and lock it into the brain. REM sleep
then comes along, and REM sleep starts to

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:48.030
fuse all of the information that you've recently
learned with the entire back catalog of information

00:19:48.030 --> 00:19:52.250
that you've got stored up across a lifetime
of experience.

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:58.890
And it's this sort of...Essentially, REM sleep
is creating a revised mind wide web of associations.

00:19:58.890 --> 00:20:03.000
And I'd like to sort of think of what's going
on with REM sleep. And we've done lots of

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:08.090
these studies to look at this and these clever
ways that you can look at sleep and associative

00:20:08.090 --> 00:20:15.970
memory processing and building new novel connections.
And it's almost like memory pinball, where

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:20.830
you take these new memories and you sort of
launch them up, and you start bouncing them

00:20:20.830 --> 00:20:26.250
around into the architecture of information
within the brain. And you're starting to test

00:20:26.250 --> 00:20:29.460
associations. You're starting to say, you
know, "Should this new information be connected

00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:33.160
to this? Maybe not. Should it be connected
to this? Maybe not."

00:20:33.160 --> 00:20:39.720
Now some of that happens whilst were awake
during the day. We make obvious connections.

00:20:39.720 --> 00:20:44.540
But what's strange is that we make connections
during REM sleep but they're not of the same

00:20:44.540 --> 00:20:50.750
kind. The connections that we're making during
REM sleep are the longshots. This is the bizarre...

00:20:50.750 --> 00:20:51.790
[Rhonda]: The bizarre, right.

00:20:51.790 --> 00:20:55.010
[Matt]: ...strange. You know, it's sort of...it
would be the equivalent of saying, during

00:20:55.010 --> 00:20:59.770
the day, we take this information, and the
connections we make are like a Google search

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:05.310
gone right, which is the first page is all
of the things that are most related. And it's

00:21:05.310 --> 00:21:10.940
very obvious. Page 1, that's directly related
to what I inputted.

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:15.200
During REM sleep, it's almost as though you
input the search term and you're immediately

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:21.100
taken to page 20 of the Google search, which
is about some field hockey game in Utah. And

00:21:21.100 --> 00:21:28.340
you think, I don't understand. Oh, that's
interesting. I see what you're talking about.

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:35.400
So we make these bizarre leaps of associative
memory processing faith during REM sleep.

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:40.990
And that's why we now understand that it's
REM sleep that helps us divine remarkable

00:21:40.990 --> 00:21:45.790
creative insights into previously impenetrable
problems.

00:21:45.790 --> 00:21:52.140
And you can see this throughout the history
of human beings, this dream-inspired insight,

00:21:52.140 --> 00:21:58.120
scientific demonstrations. You know, August
KekulÃ© divined the idea of a benzene ring,

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:03.810
these double carbon rings by dreaming of a
serpent that swallowed its tail. Dmitri Mendeleev,

00:22:03.810 --> 00:22:11.160
you know, came up with the Periodic Table
of Elements by way of dream inspiration. And,

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:16.400
you know, people have won Nobel Prizes, Otto
Loewi won the Nobel Prize for the demonstration

00:22:16.400 --> 00:22:21.850
of chemical transmission across nerve cells.
And he dreamt of the experiment that helped

00:22:21.850 --> 00:22:25.590
improve that. He didn't dream of the concept
itself, but he dreamt of the experiment to

00:22:25.590 --> 00:22:27.520
prove it.

00:22:27.520 --> 00:22:32.930
Wonderful, artistic demonstrations of this,
too. You know, Paul McCartney has written

00:22:32.930 --> 00:22:38.610
innumerable songs, it turns out, by way of
his dreams. Keith Richards came up with the

00:22:38.610 --> 00:22:42.810
opening chords of Satisfaction by way of dream-inspired
insight.

00:22:42.810 --> 00:22:49.590
So REM sleep takes that third component of
information processing. And I think it's what

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:57.690
defines us differentially from computers in
part, which is that deep sleep is about knowledge,

00:22:57.690 --> 00:23:02.240
which is gathering all of the information
and holding on to it. REM sleep, I would argue,

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:08.310
is about wisdom, which is knowing what it
all means when you fit it together, you know.

00:23:08.310 --> 00:23:12.260
That's what I want from a good student. Don't
just give me dry-book learning. Do you really

00:23:12.260 --> 00:23:16.230
understand it? Can you apply it? Are you creative?
That's dream sleep.

00:23:16.230 --> 00:23:20.700
[Rhonda]: Right, a deep thinker. Why do you
sometimes not remember your dreams and sometimes

00:23:20.700 --> 00:23:23.370
you do remember your dreams? Do you have any
idea?

00:23:23.370 --> 00:23:29.480
[Matt]: Yeah. So some of it seems to be about,
if you wake up out of that dream sleep period

00:23:29.480 --> 00:23:34.530
and then you go back into sleep, the awakening
can sometimes help you commit that experience

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:35.530
to memory.

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:36.750
[Rhonda]: Oh, okay.

00:23:36.750 --> 00:23:41.111
[Matt]: But there are people who say that
I never remember my dreams, you know. We can

00:23:41.111 --> 00:23:44.420
bring those people into my sleep center, and
we can, you know, wake them up in the middle

00:23:44.420 --> 00:23:48.141
of dream sleep, and they'll say, "It's remarkable.
For the first time, I was dreaming." And the

00:23:48.141 --> 00:23:51.920
answer is no. It's not the first time that
you are dreaming. It's just the first time

00:23:51.920 --> 00:23:56.130
that you've actually remembered a dream, because
it's the first time you've typically woken

00:23:56.130 --> 00:23:57.130
up.

00:23:57.130 --> 00:24:01.170
[Rhonda]: Okay. My mother-in-law, you know,
claims that she doesn't dream. And, of course,

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:02.450
I'm like, "No, you have to dream."

00:24:02.450 --> 00:24:03.450
[Matt]: Yeah.

00:24:03.450 --> 00:24:04.450
[Rhonda]: That must be...

00:24:04.450 --> 00:24:07.640
[Matt]: There are a selection of patients
that have a lesion in a part of the prefrontal

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:12.460
cortex, in their white matter, which are these
big sort of informational fiber tracts that

00:24:12.460 --> 00:24:17.930
communicate impulses. If you get a lesion
deep down there, we do seem to genuinely see

00:24:17.930 --> 00:24:21.370
a cessation of dreaming in those patients.

00:24:21.370 --> 00:24:26.570
By the way, I would...I didn't even feel confident
to write this in the book, and it's still

00:24:26.570 --> 00:24:33.680
a theory that I've never really heard in public,
but go with me on this. Which is, I think

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:40.120
that we may actually remember all of our dreams,
or it's possible that there's a tenable theory.

00:24:40.120 --> 00:24:46.170
The problem is we don't have access to those
dreams. Those dreams are memorized, and they

00:24:46.170 --> 00:24:50.870
are available. They're just not accessible.
I think what happens as we wake up is that

00:24:50.870 --> 00:24:56.170
we lose the IP address to those memories.
And the reason I believe this to be potentially

00:24:56.170 --> 00:24:59.990
true is have you ever had the experience where
you wake up and you think, I was dreaming,

00:24:59.990 --> 00:25:04.330
and I know I was dreaming. And you try as
hard as you can. The harder you try, the...

00:25:04.330 --> 00:25:05.330
[Rhonda]: Yeah.

00:25:05.330 --> 00:25:09.800
[Matt]: ...worse the memory-recall goes? And
then you think, forget it. Two days later,

00:25:09.800 --> 00:25:13.720
you're walking along, and you see a street
sign, and all of a sudden, it triggers the

00:25:13.720 --> 00:25:17.710
unlocking of that dream memory. You think,
oh, that's what the dream was about.

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:23.690
As a neuroscientist, that tells me that the
memory was present. The memory was available.

00:25:23.690 --> 00:25:30.210
The problem was accessibility. You couldn't
gain recall access. So the information is

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:32.950
there. It's just not accessible. If that's
true...

00:25:32.950 --> 00:25:37.850
[Rhonda]: It's happened to me just even after
I've, you know, when I go to bed. You know,

00:25:37.850 --> 00:25:40.910
later that night, I hit the pillow, and all
of a sudden, I remember the dream right as

00:25:40.910 --> 00:25:41.910
I'm hitting the pillow.

00:25:41.910 --> 00:25:42.910
[Matt]: Right.

00:25:42.910 --> 00:25:43.910
[Rhonda]: That's happened to me more than
once. But you're right.

00:25:43.910 --> 00:25:49.220
[Matt]: Right. It sort of tells you that there
is...it's almost a scary prospect, which is

00:25:49.220 --> 00:25:55.230
that maybe every single one of our dreams
throughout life are stored and are present

00:25:55.230 --> 00:26:00.570
and determine our behavior to some degree,
because we know that there is an enormous

00:26:00.570 --> 00:26:05.720
amount of information that changes our behavior
or decisions that goes on below the radar

00:26:05.720 --> 00:26:10.200
of consciousness, implicit memory. That could
be true for dreaming, too.

00:26:10.200 --> 00:26:15.370
And I think I've got an experiment that we
may be able to design to actually get at this.

00:26:15.370 --> 00:26:19.830
And if that's true, it should, hopefully,
radically change our view of dreaming, that

00:26:19.830 --> 00:26:24.280
dreams are ephemeral, that they dissolve quickly,
they're forgotten, and they don't influence

00:26:24.280 --> 00:26:25.740
us as human species.

00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:26.960
[Rhonda]: That would be pretty groundbreaking.

00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:27.960
[Matt]: Yeah, we'll see.

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:34.350
[Rhonda]: You just had a study that I just
read, I think, yesterday on sleep and it affecting

00:26:34.350 --> 00:26:35.990
behavior, loneliness, or...

00:26:35.990 --> 00:26:41.820
[Matt]: Yeah, so we just published a sleep
study demonstrating that sleep loss will trigger

00:26:41.820 --> 00:26:48.030
viral loneliness. And it was a three-part
study. I mean, firstly, the reason that I

00:26:48.030 --> 00:26:54.260
got into this was loneliness is a killer.
We know that there is a massive epidemic of

00:26:54.260 --> 00:27:01.050
loneliness now in industrialized nations.
Being lonely increases your mortality risk

00:27:01.050 --> 00:27:07.810
by about 45%. In other words, being lonely
is twice as risky for your death concern than

00:27:07.810 --> 00:27:08.810
obesity...

00:27:08.810 --> 00:27:09.810
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:27:09.810 --> 00:27:10.810
[Matt]: ...which is striking.

00:27:10.810 --> 00:27:16.980
[Rhonda]: Yeah. There was actually a study
showing loneliness changes, like, a massive

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:23.370
amount of gene expression and, like, up-regulates
NF-kappaB, cortisol, like all these pro-inflammatory

00:27:23.370 --> 00:27:25.170
genes. So it makes sense that it'd be associated
with...

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:28.230
[Matt]: And what's bizarre about loneliness...By
the way, I'm taking a complete...this has

00:27:28.230 --> 00:27:34.350
got nothing to do with sleep. But if you look
at the profile of your gene expression and

00:27:34.350 --> 00:27:40.830
your immune system, you've got some immune
components that will go after viruses. And

00:27:40.830 --> 00:27:46.120
viruses can only be transmitted from one human
being to another by way of touch. They can't

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:50.390
live outside of our bodies. Bacteria, so if
you scrape yourself on a fence, like, you

00:27:50.390 --> 00:27:55.200
know, walking past it, you can get a bacterial
infection because bacteria can live outside

00:27:55.200 --> 00:27:57.260
of the body.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:05.340
When you become lonely, your gene expression
shifts you away from a profile of immunity

00:28:05.340 --> 00:28:11.570
that normally deals with viruses and pushes
you to more towards a bacterial defense profile.

00:28:11.570 --> 00:28:12.570
[Rhonda]: Really?

00:28:12.570 --> 00:28:13.570
[Matt]: Isn't that incredible?

00:28:13.570 --> 00:28:15.600
[Rhonda]: Yeah, you should send me that study.

00:28:15.600 --> 00:28:16.600
[Matt]: That your psychology...

00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:17.600
[Rhonda]: Yeah, that's fascinating.

00:28:17.600 --> 00:28:22.080
[Matt]: And there's a couple of folks at UCLA,
who, if you ever have interest in this area

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:24.810
of how loneliness, the mind, the mood...

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:25.810
[Rhonda]: Oh, totally. Yeah.

00:28:25.810 --> 00:28:29.640
[Matt]: Okay, I've got to give you these people.
I'm a complete fan of...

00:28:29.640 --> 00:28:30.640
[Rhonda]: Please do.

00:28:30.640 --> 00:28:35.420
[Matt]: ...their work. And they did this study.
And it just blew my mind. How could a concept

00:28:35.420 --> 00:28:40.570
that is so sort of, you know, out there, and
some people almost don't, you know, believe

00:28:40.570 --> 00:28:45.090
in loneliness. Toughen up. What's wrong with
you? Go out make some...How could that change

00:28:45.090 --> 00:28:51.800
the expression of your genes and even alter
how you, the organism, fend for yourself from

00:28:51.800 --> 00:28:57.190
an immunological perspective shifting you
from viral to bacterial defense. But, anyway...

00:28:57.190 --> 00:28:58.190
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:28:58.190 --> 00:29:02.490
[Matt]: So coming back, I was desperately
concerned about the state of loneliness. What's

00:29:02.490 --> 00:29:06.620
interesting, I was reading a lot at the time,
because we do a lot of work with sleep and

00:29:06.620 --> 00:29:11.110
psychiatric disorders including anxiety, and
when I was reading the studies where they

00:29:11.110 --> 00:29:16.110
would take animals and they would deprive
them of sleep, you've got this anxiogenic

00:29:16.110 --> 00:29:23.040
profile where you got cortisol increasing,
you got shift in insulin and glucose regulation,

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:27.940
all of the bad things that you would not wish
to happen, an anxiety increase, they had fear-like

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:31.020
behavior all by way of just sleep restriction.

00:29:31.020 --> 00:29:36.100
But what was also interesting is that sometimes
the researchers would know, despite not measuring

00:29:36.100 --> 00:29:42.360
it systematically, that the animals, who would
often be secluded by themselves in the cage,

00:29:42.360 --> 00:29:49.850
even when they were with other conspecifics,
and other conspecifics would not approach

00:29:49.850 --> 00:29:50.850
them either.

00:29:50.850 --> 00:29:51.850
[Rhonda]: Okay.

00:29:51.850 --> 00:29:57.020
[Matt]: And so it seemed to me just from reading
this, I thought, well, this seems like an

00:29:57.020 --> 00:30:03.230
animal phenotype of human loneliness. And
it seems to be caused by a lack of sleep.

00:30:03.230 --> 00:30:06.080
So we decided we had to do the study.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:09.290
So the first part of the study, we took a
group of individuals, and they went through

00:30:09.290 --> 00:30:12.530
the study twice. They were either deprived
of sleep for an entire night, or they got

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:19.640
a full eight hours of sleep. The first test
was do you have a social repulsion boundary,

00:30:19.640 --> 00:30:24.270
and that boundary is increased when you are
sleep-deprived. So I think everyone has that

00:30:24.270 --> 00:30:28.370
sense that if I start moving closer to you,
you think, okay, do you know what, at some

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:31.840
point, that's kind of enough. That's about
my close distance.

00:30:31.840 --> 00:30:35.920
What's interesting is that if I ask a sleep-deprived
an individual to stay put, and I ask you,

00:30:35.920 --> 00:30:40.580
as an experimenter, to walk towards the sleep
deprived individual, and the individual says,

00:30:40.580 --> 00:30:45.490
"Stop," when they feel comfortable relative
to when that very same individual has had

00:30:45.490 --> 00:30:49.870
a full eight-hour night of sleep. When you're
sleep-deprived, you decide to push people

00:30:49.870 --> 00:30:57.600
a further distance away from you. So you have
a lower desire for social proximity and social

00:30:57.600 --> 00:30:58.600
interaction.

00:30:58.600 --> 00:31:05.280
Second, we then replicated that finding, but
now we had them inside the MRI scanner. Because

00:31:05.280 --> 00:31:08.861
we wanted to see what was changing the brain
to produce this social repulsion. What we

00:31:08.861 --> 00:31:13.270
found was that the regions of the brain that
are essentially an alarm network, which is

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:17.040
a sort of a stay-away-from-me network that
is sort of in the parietal cortex and the

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:22.920
premotor cortex, it's sort of what we call
the near space network. So it creates your

00:31:22.920 --> 00:31:28.240
comfort of boundary. And when objects start
to approach you, it alarms to say, "Incoming.

00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:33.910
Be cautious. Be wary." That part of the brain
became hyperactive when people were sleep-deprived...

00:31:33.910 --> 00:31:34.910
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:31:34.910 --> 00:31:39.850
[Matt]: as if you were getting this repulsion
signal from the brain. If that wasn't bad

00:31:39.850 --> 00:31:45.320
enough, the other parts of the brain that
have been called the theory-of-mind network,

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:49.880
which sort of helps you understand the intent
of other people, it's a pro-social network

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:54.840
in the brain, it cooperates pro-social interaction,
that part of the brain was shut down by sleep

00:31:54.840 --> 00:31:59.490
deprivation. So it's a double-edged sort of
sword.

00:31:59.490 --> 00:32:07.110
So we weren't satisfied with that. Next, we
wanted to say, "Could someone who just looked

00:32:07.110 --> 00:32:13.000
at these sleep-deprived individuals, could
they actually judge them as being lonelier

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:17.580
and looking lonelier and beaten, sort of perceived
as lonely, even though they knew nothing about

00:32:17.580 --> 00:32:18.780
the experiment?"

00:32:18.780 --> 00:32:22.770
So in the experiment with the sleep-deprived
individuals, we also did videotaped interviews

00:32:22.770 --> 00:32:26.071
with them. And we just asked them general
questions. Tell us about a movie that you

00:32:26.071 --> 00:32:31.420
watched? Or what was happening in the news
this week? Just bland stuff. And then we got

00:32:31.420 --> 00:32:39.390
1,000, I think was it was over 1,000 people,
1,083 people online. And they knew nothing

00:32:39.390 --> 00:32:43.020
about the experiment. They didn't know it's
about sleep, sleep deprivation, knew nothing.

00:32:43.020 --> 00:32:47.250
And we showed them just a 60-second clip of
these people when they'd have a good night

00:32:47.250 --> 00:32:50.790
of sleep and when they were sleep-deprived.
And we just asked them, "How lonely does this

00:32:50.790 --> 00:32:55.660
person appear to you?" And they knew nothing.
But despite knowing nothing, they consistently

00:32:55.660 --> 00:33:01.570
and reliably rated the sleep-deprived version
of the individual as seeming lonelier.

00:33:01.570 --> 00:33:04.870
We also asked them, "Would you socially interact
with this person? Would you friend them on

00:33:04.870 --> 00:33:10.320
Facebook? Would you work with them in a business
environment?" And they consistently rated

00:33:10.320 --> 00:33:13.330
that they would prefer not to engage and interact
with them.

00:33:13.330 --> 00:33:16.310
[Rhonda]: Is that because they just looked
unhappy or looked...?

00:33:16.310 --> 00:33:20.210
[Matt]: Well, we actually think it's a collection
of things. It's that their appearance, but

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:24.770
also their vocal tone, is very different.
We think there's a lot of...This is now one

00:33:24.770 --> 00:33:27.440
of the key things. What's communicating this
asocial profile?

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:30.070
[Rhonda]: Oh, so they are listening to them
speak?

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:33.520
[Matt]: So they watched them, and they listen
to them speak. So they could hear them as

00:33:33.520 --> 00:33:41.200
well. So we demonstrated that. There was,
unfortunately, the social repulsion on both

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:45.750
sides of the equation. When you're sleep-deprived,
you yourself don't want to have anything to

00:33:45.750 --> 00:33:50.070
do with other people. And that perhaps wouldn't
be so bad if people would only at least come

00:33:50.070 --> 00:33:54.650
to your rescue, because they would see you
in need. The opposite is true. People find

00:33:54.650 --> 00:34:01.480
you socially repulsive as a consequence. So
there's a push from both sides of the social

00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:03.820
dyad.

00:34:03.820 --> 00:34:08.379
The next thing, we asked those people who
were rating the sleep-deprived individuals,

00:34:08.379 --> 00:34:14.389
we also said, "Look, how lonely do you feel
after just the 60-second clip?" And they themselves

00:34:14.389 --> 00:34:20.099
felt lonelier after interacting with sleep-deprived
individuals. In other words, this contagion

00:34:20.099 --> 00:34:21.690
of sleep-deprivation-induced loneliness.

00:34:21.690 --> 00:34:26.389
[Rhonda]: So I wonder how much of this can
be translated to, like, someone that, say,

00:34:26.389 --> 00:34:31.409
for example, gets only five or six hours of
sleep versus, of course, not getting a full

00:34:31.409 --> 00:34:35.029
night sleep. You know, maybe there's, like,
a little, just a little bit of this penetrating...

00:34:35.029 --> 00:34:38.470
[Matt]: We then ask that question. That was
the final part of the study, which is that

00:34:38.470 --> 00:34:43.510
we said, "Okay, this is extreme sleep deprivation,
and most of the population does not undergo

00:34:43.510 --> 00:34:49.220
this. What about a more ecological version?"
So we tracked hundreds of people across two

00:34:49.220 --> 00:34:56.520
nights of sleep. And we asked, just by a subtle
variation of nature, our small perturbations

00:34:56.520 --> 00:35:02.329
of sleep from one night to the next, do they
predict how lonely you experience yourself

00:35:02.329 --> 00:35:07.589
to be from one day to the next? And these
are small minute changes in sleep efficiency,

00:35:07.589 --> 00:35:10.670
just small reductions in sleep of tens of
minutes.

00:35:10.670 --> 00:35:15.819
Lo and behold, even just that small change
in your sleep from one night to the next,

00:35:15.819 --> 00:35:21.940
we could measure, predicted how lonely you
would experience life the next day from one

00:35:21.940 --> 00:35:26.010
day to the next. So it doesn't even take,
you know, two hours of sleep reduction.

00:35:26.010 --> 00:35:27.010
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:28.010
[Matt]: Small minutes.

00:35:28.010 --> 00:35:34.240
[Rhonda]: I remember reading somewhere, too,
that isn't the, like, amygdala, like hyperactive

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:37.710
or something happens, there's not an inhibitory
signal that occurs if you're sleep-deprived

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:38.710
or...?

00:35:38.710 --> 00:35:39.710
[Matt]: That's right.

00:35:39.710 --> 00:35:40.710
[Rhonda]: Is that correct?

00:35:40.710 --> 00:35:41.710
[Matt]: Yes.

00:35:41.710 --> 00:35:44.559
[Rhonda]: So then you're feeling more...you're,
like, alarmed and, you know, just anxious

00:35:44.559 --> 00:35:47.650
and feeling that in a, say, threat...

00:35:47.650 --> 00:35:48.650
[Matt]: That's right.

00:35:48.650 --> 00:35:50.789
[Rhonda]: ...that ongoing threat that really
isn't there.

00:35:50.789 --> 00:35:56.849
[Matt]: Exactly, yeah. So we published the
study in 2007 where we, again, sort of sleep-deprived

00:35:56.849 --> 00:36:02.079
people, put them inside an MRI scanner, and
we showed them increasingly negative and aversive

00:36:02.079 --> 00:36:06.950
and unpleasant images. And what we saw is
that, relative to people who'd got a full

00:36:06.950 --> 00:36:13.310
night of sleep, the amygdala, this sort of
emotional epicenter for the generation of

00:36:13.310 --> 00:36:18.910
strong, emotional, impulsive reactions, that
deep emotional center was 60% more reactive

00:36:18.910 --> 00:36:21.769
under conditions of a lack of sleep.

00:36:21.769 --> 00:36:28.359
And then we asked why. Why is your emotional
brain so sort of sensitive and erupting with

00:36:28.359 --> 00:36:34.680
such extraordinary activity? And what we then
went to find, or went on to find out in later

00:36:34.680 --> 00:36:38.500
work, was that another part of your brain
called the prefrontal cortex that sits directly

00:36:38.500 --> 00:36:43.470
above your eyes here, and particularly the
middle part right between your eyes, that

00:36:43.470 --> 00:36:49.760
part of the brain acts almost like the CEO
of the brain, of your emotions, and your hedonic

00:36:49.760 --> 00:36:55.420
impulses. And it sends sort of an inhibitory
top-down regulatory control. It's sort of,

00:36:55.420 --> 00:36:59.010
like, the brakes on the gas pedal of your
emotions.

00:36:59.010 --> 00:37:03.720
That part of the brain was shut down by sleep
deprivation, and you'd lost that communication

00:37:03.720 --> 00:37:09.589
to the amygdala. So now you, from an emotional
standpoint, you were all emotional gas pedal

00:37:09.589 --> 00:37:13.210
and too little regulatory control brake as
it were.

00:37:13.210 --> 00:37:19.020
[Rhonda]: It's really interesting. This work
kind of reminds me of...I'm not sure if you're

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:23.440
aware of any of this research. A lot of it
has been done by Dr. Molly Crockett, who,

00:37:23.440 --> 00:37:30.390
I believe, now she's at Harvard. But she has
done a lot of studies looking at serotonin

00:37:30.390 --> 00:37:36.089
depletion in the brain. And basically, you
can induce that by giving acute tryptophan

00:37:36.089 --> 00:37:41.710
depletion, giving someone like branched-chain
amino acids to compete with transport for

00:37:41.710 --> 00:37:45.829
tryptophan in the brain, which then basically
drops serotonin levels. I mean, you can drop

00:37:45.829 --> 00:37:48.430
your serotonin levels down to, like, 10%.

00:37:48.430 --> 00:37:49.569
[Matt]: And mood is...

00:37:49.569 --> 00:37:54.839
[Rhonda]: And the same thing happens where,
exactly what you were describing, the inhibitory

00:37:54.839 --> 00:38:01.000
signal that happens from the prefrontal cortex
onto the amygdala is, like, stops. And so

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:08.070
people become extremely impulsive. Terrible
moods, a little more aggressive, their long-term

00:38:08.070 --> 00:38:12.470
planning shuts down, and they just, like,
going for the short-term gratification. Very

00:38:12.470 --> 00:38:17.319
similar. So it'd be kind of interesting...I
don't know how serotonin would be related

00:38:17.319 --> 00:38:20.119
to all that, but there must be some sort of
connection.

00:38:20.119 --> 00:38:23.470
[Matt]: Yeah. I mean, and I think there's
a number of different, I think, neuro chemicals

00:38:23.470 --> 00:38:27.710
that can produce that same kind of neural
phenotype and as it were. But what struck

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:33.920
me was that when I looked at that neural signature
of sleep deprivation for the emotional brain,

00:38:33.920 --> 00:38:39.671
it was not dissimilar to numerous psychiatric
conditions. And that then now, gosh, 11 years

00:38:39.671 --> 00:38:45.660
ago, I'm showing my age, but that set sort
of, you know, the sleep center off on a completely

00:38:45.660 --> 00:38:49.890
new trajectory of work. And we're doing a
lot of this work in sleep and psychiatric

00:38:49.890 --> 00:38:50.890
disorders.

00:38:50.890 --> 00:38:55.500
And I think one of the most fundamental things
that I can say at this point is that we have

00:38:55.500 --> 00:39:01.020
not been able to discover a single psychiatric
condition in which sleep is normal. And so

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:07.940
I think sleep has a profound story to tell
in our understanding, maybe our treatment,

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:13.400
I don't know about prevention, but possibly,
of grave mental illness. And psychiatry has

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:18.049
known this, by the way, for, you know, 40
or 50 years. It's always been documented that

00:39:18.049 --> 00:39:21.079
sleep disturbance goes hand-in-hand with psychiatric
disturbance.

00:39:21.079 --> 00:39:24.650
[Rhonda]: Maybe there's some sort of complex
gene environment interaction. A few people

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:27.760
that are more genetically susceptible and
are getting...losing the sleep, or, like,

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:30.380
the ones that are kind of pushed into a disease
state.

00:39:30.380 --> 00:39:34.130
[Matt]: And we've seen this, too, that if
you look at that emotional brain reaction

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:40.210
signature that I just sort of described, and
you repeat that, but with people who are high-anxious

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:43.799
and low-anxious, and we know some of the genes
that are associated with being high-anxious

00:39:43.799 --> 00:39:50.309
and low-anxious. So we're using anxiety as
a sort of a proxy for perhaps a particular

00:39:50.309 --> 00:39:56.690
genotype here. What you see is that it's those
high-anxious people who are the most vulnerable

00:39:56.690 --> 00:40:01.769
to this impact of a lack of sleep. Those who
are low-anxious still have a bad outcome,

00:40:01.769 --> 00:40:07.339
but it's nowhere near as bad. So there seems
to be sort of interactions here between sleep

00:40:07.339 --> 00:40:13.170
loss and your basic trait levels of being
sort of a nervous, anxious type to begin with.

00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:14.170
[Rhonda]: That makes sense.

00:40:14.170 --> 00:40:17.710
[Matt]: And those are the people who are,
sadly, the people who typically don't get

00:40:17.710 --> 00:40:18.760
a good night of sleep anyway.

00:40:18.760 --> 00:40:22.220
[Rhonda]: Right. So you're saying anxiety
is, like, one of the things that stops me

00:40:22.220 --> 00:40:23.220
from sleeping.

00:40:23.220 --> 00:40:24.339
[Matt]: It's the principal trigger of insomnia.

00:40:24.339 --> 00:40:25.339
[Rhonda]: Yeah, really, true.

00:40:25.339 --> 00:40:28.690
[Matt]: It's the model of insomnia right now,
is that you get...And if you look at the nervous

00:40:28.690 --> 00:40:32.940
system, that's how we understand insomnia
right now, is that its principle is...I think

00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:38.970
ultimately we'll find that there are multiple
flavors of insomnia, different forms. We already

00:40:38.970 --> 00:40:43.900
categorized two of them. We've got what we
call sleep onset insomnia and sleep maintenance

00:40:43.900 --> 00:40:49.460
insomnia, difficulty falling asleep, difficulty
staying asleep. They're not mutually exclusive.

00:40:49.460 --> 00:40:52.769
You can have both, or you can just have one
or the other.

00:40:52.769 --> 00:41:00.779
But coming back to it, I think the overarching
biological red thread narrative of insomnia

00:41:00.779 --> 00:41:05.720
is an amplified fight-or-flight nervous system,
that your nervous system is split into these

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:10.759
two branches, what we call sort of the sympathetic
and parasympathetic parts of your autonomic

00:41:10.759 --> 00:41:16.210
nervous system. The sympathetic is anything
but sympathetic. It's poorly named. It's the

00:41:16.210 --> 00:41:21.549
fight-or-flight branch of your nervous system.
It ramps you up, charges you up, releases

00:41:21.549 --> 00:41:23.119
cortisol, adrenaline.

00:41:23.119 --> 00:41:29.950
You constantly see an overactive, sympathetic
nervous system in people with insomnia. And

00:41:29.950 --> 00:41:34.200
when you measure their cortisol across the
24-hour period, in most of us, just as we're

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:39.400
getting to our natural bedtime, cortisol just
starts to now drop down. We start to see that

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:44.940
cycling down of cortisol. The opposite happens
in people with insomnia. You get a continued

00:41:44.940 --> 00:41:51.030
rise right around that bedroom period. And
it seems to be very predictive of sleep onset

00:41:51.030 --> 00:41:52.599
problems.

00:41:52.599 --> 00:41:56.579
If you look throughout the night, cortisol
then starts to plummet, and it drops beautifully

00:41:56.579 --> 00:42:00.730
down. It's part of the reason why deep sleep
is the best form of natural blood pressure

00:42:00.730 --> 00:42:07.529
medication that you could ever wish for. Your
heart rate drops down, your vessels relax,

00:42:07.529 --> 00:42:12.500
cortisol drops down. But in other insomnia
patients, we see this bizarre spike in cortisol

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:17.839
in the middle of the night. And it predicts
nighttime awakenings. It predicts sleep maintenance

00:42:17.839 --> 00:42:18.839
insomnia.

00:42:18.839 --> 00:42:24.519
[Rhonda]: I have experienced...So that's one
of the problems that I actually have. It's

00:42:24.519 --> 00:42:30.279
much, much better now that my stress level
is, like, maintained. At graduate school,

00:42:30.279 --> 00:42:34.309
I would get nighttime awakenings where my
heart would start racing. And I would wake

00:42:34.309 --> 00:42:39.569
up thinking that there was a spider or some
kind of threat. And I would scream, and sometimes

00:42:39.569 --> 00:42:44.849
fly out the bed. I mean, you know, and just...it
would scare my husband, you know. At the time,

00:42:44.849 --> 00:42:50.240
we weren't married. But, I mean, you know,
these nighttime awakenings, it was something

00:42:50.240 --> 00:42:56.470
that's dated back for quite some time. But
really, it manifested during a very stressful

00:42:56.470 --> 00:42:57.760
period, and that was graduate school.

00:42:57.760 --> 00:42:58.760
[Matt]: We see that...

00:42:58.760 --> 00:42:59.760
[Rhonda]: Got much better.

00:42:59.760 --> 00:43:00.760
[Matt]: ...so frequently.

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:01.760
[Rhonda]: Yeah.

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:06.999
[Matt]: But if you can think about that as
sort of, you know, a stress management component

00:43:06.999 --> 00:43:11.880
to insomnia, you know, it's part of what we
call cognitive behavioral therapy for insomnia,

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:16.499
which is sort of dealing with that stress,
you know, meditation. There's great apps out

00:43:16.499 --> 00:43:19.279
there, like Headspace, for example.

00:43:19.279 --> 00:43:24.710
And the data on meditation and insomnia is
very very powerful. You know, I'd known about

00:43:24.710 --> 00:43:30.109
it a little bit, but I hadn't read really
all of the studies until I started researching

00:43:30.109 --> 00:43:35.130
it for the book. And I was so convinced that
I started meditating. And I haven't stopped

00:43:35.130 --> 00:43:39.390
since. Because it was, you know...Typically,
I'm not a bad sleeper. I'm a light sleeper.

00:43:39.390 --> 00:43:45.650
I'm a pretty good sleeper. I found it hugely
useful for times when I was under stress,

00:43:45.650 --> 00:43:49.249
or when I was traveling and jetlag. It's very
beneficial, too.

00:43:49.249 --> 00:43:55.180
But that underlying theme, I think, as a message
for insomnia, it's not the only cause of insomnia,

00:43:55.180 --> 00:44:01.400
but it seems to be if there's one common sort
of rule that binds many of the patients with

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:06.190
insomnia together, it's this overactive fight-or-flight
branch of the nervous system. And if you can

00:44:06.190 --> 00:44:09.839
settle that down, you are certainly on the
path towards better sleep.

00:44:09.839 --> 00:44:14.220
[Rhonda]: Right. And to kind of just...Another
point that you made talking about, you know,

00:44:14.220 --> 00:44:17.970
the hormonal response and the cortisol rising
typically when it's supposed to be falling,

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:22.890
that kind of prevents you from falling asleep,
there is some interesting research that I've

00:44:22.890 --> 00:44:28.400
read where, and I know you and I have talked
about how the importance of bright light exposure...Bright

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:33.990
light exposure for six hours a day...I mean,
no one does that nowadays. We're always inside.

00:44:33.990 --> 00:44:37.529
So it's rare unless you're, like, working
out in a nature park or something.

00:44:37.529 --> 00:44:38.980
[Matt]: The irony of these things...

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:39.980
[Rhonda]: Right, you know.

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:42.089
[Matt]: Yeah. It's for the camera. I promise.

00:44:42.089 --> 00:44:46.779
[Rhonda]: Right. But, actually, it was shown
to lower cortisol by 25%.

00:44:46.779 --> 00:44:47.799
[Matt]: Yup.

00:44:47.799 --> 00:44:53.849
[Rhonda]: So this is, like, you know, another
kind of I don't know if that would even help

00:44:53.849 --> 00:44:56.079
someone with the anxiety or, you know...

00:44:56.079 --> 00:45:01.560
[Matt]: No, I think it's...there's no studies
testing it yet, but there are studies...So

00:45:01.560 --> 00:45:05.800
just sort of to go back to make this point,
we normally have a circadian rhythm, this

00:45:05.800 --> 00:45:09.911
beautiful sort of 24-hour rhythm. And we human
beings were diurnal, and we like to sleep

00:45:09.911 --> 00:45:15.999
at night, be awake during the day. We have
this awesome upswing of our circadian rhythm

00:45:15.999 --> 00:45:21.279
sort of once we wake up sort of 7, 8, 9, 10,
11. It starts to peak during the day. It drops

00:45:21.279 --> 00:45:25.119
down a little bit in the mid-afternoon. And
that's why you sort of get around meeting

00:45:25.119 --> 00:45:28.920
tables in the middle of the afternoon these
sort of, you know, head nods. It's not people

00:45:28.920 --> 00:45:33.799
listening to a good music. It's like, actually,
it's a pre-programmed dip in your alertness.

00:45:33.799 --> 00:45:37.849
And then it rises back up, and then it drops
down at night.

00:45:37.849 --> 00:45:42.470
And one of the ways that you can get this
sort of what you would want, which is a nice

00:45:42.470 --> 00:45:47.599
sinusoidal wave, you want a nice strong peak
of the circadian rhythm during the day so

00:45:47.599 --> 00:45:51.420
that you're awake and you're active during
the day and you're productive, and then you

00:45:51.420 --> 00:45:56.990
want an awesome sort of trough throughout
the night so that you sleep soundly, deeply,

00:45:56.990 --> 00:46:00.020
and in a stable fashion.

00:46:00.020 --> 00:46:04.450
And the way that you can sort of help your
circadian rhythm have that wonderful peak

00:46:04.450 --> 00:46:11.569
and delightful trough is by getting lots of
daylight during the day but lots of darkness

00:46:11.569 --> 00:46:17.520
during the night. And we are a dark-deprived
society in this modern era. And it is a huge

00:46:17.520 --> 00:46:19.430
problem in the evening.

00:46:19.430 --> 00:46:25.270
But I think people have underestimated that
we are a light-deprived society during the

00:46:25.270 --> 00:46:31.940
day. So what happens is that your brain goes
through life in this kind of almost stupor

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:36.930
state where it's not getting enough daylight
to really keep it ramped up throughout the

00:46:36.930 --> 00:46:41.769
day so you're sleepy throughout the day and
you're tired, but then we've got too much

00:46:41.769 --> 00:46:48.000
light in the evening so you end up being awake
at night, and then you're sleepy during the

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:49.569
day, you're awake at night.

00:46:49.569 --> 00:46:54.499
And so, you know, almost like, I'm gonna call
it a seesaw. I think we call it teeter-totter

00:46:54.499 --> 00:46:59.660
here. You know, during the day, you want daylight
to come in and force you all the way on to

00:46:59.660 --> 00:47:03.680
the on switch and you're active and awake.
And then at night, you want the signal of

00:47:03.680 --> 00:47:08.210
darkness to come in to trigger the release
of a hormone called melatonin to shift you

00:47:08.210 --> 00:47:13.319
all the way into the off position so you go
into deep sleep and a sound sleep.

00:47:13.319 --> 00:47:18.220
But now, with artificial light and staying
out of bright light, so the teeter-totter

00:47:18.220 --> 00:47:22.609
has just pushed a little bit to one side,
and then sort of with not enough darkness

00:47:22.609 --> 00:47:26.640
at night, it's only pushed a little bit down
on the other side. So you kind of have this

00:47:26.640 --> 00:47:31.859
flip-flop switch that...it's like a dimmer
switch that is basically just on dim for 24

00:47:31.859 --> 00:47:36.470
hours rather than light and complete darkness,
if that makes some sense.

00:47:36.470 --> 00:47:37.470
[Rhonda]: Yes.

00:47:37.470 --> 00:47:38.470
[Matt]: It's terrible analogy, but...

00:47:38.470 --> 00:47:42.660
[Rhonda]: Do you have any idea, like, how
much bright light exposure, like, you know...Let's

00:47:42.660 --> 00:47:46.180
say, you know, a lot of people work in, like,
a little cubicle where they could don't even

00:47:46.180 --> 00:47:51.049
have windows. I mean, they're just like in
the middle of this, like, little rooms with

00:47:51.049 --> 00:47:56.160
no actual sunlight coming in, you know, is
something like if you wake up in the morning

00:47:56.160 --> 00:48:00.339
and you go outside for 30 minutes or an hour
first thing in the morning, like...Most people

00:48:00.339 --> 00:48:04.099
are drinking their coffee. Well, maybe what
you need is bright light exposure instead

00:48:04.099 --> 00:48:05.650
of your coffee, or drink your coffee outside.

00:48:05.650 --> 00:48:07.990
[Matt]: Right, yeah. Take the coffee on...

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:11.380
[Rhonda]: Yeah. Do you know how much light
you need? And if you don't have light outside,

00:48:11.380 --> 00:48:16.180
let's say you live in London, and you're in
the winter, and there's no...It's just gray.

00:48:16.180 --> 00:48:23.630
[Matt]: Even that, even on a cloudy day, the
lux intensity of light far exceeds that that

00:48:23.630 --> 00:48:28.529
you would have from incandescent light or
at sort of typical lights inside of a building.

00:48:28.529 --> 00:48:31.410
[Rhonda]: Okay. So now my second question,
the lux amount, so do you know?

00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:36.279
[Matt]: Yeah. So I think, I mean, if you look
at the studies, once you get over a sort of,

00:48:36.279 --> 00:48:42.510
you know, about 5,000 to 10,000 lux, you can
have a pretty powerful effect. I don't believe

00:48:42.510 --> 00:48:47.250
there's...and I could be wrong. And Satchin
Panda, our good friend, who is just A plus...In

00:48:47.250 --> 00:48:50.819
fact, yeah, if you're watching this, like,
stop watching this now. Just go and watch

00:48:50.819 --> 00:48:57.910
the Satchin Panda podcast. He's much more
powerful and eloquent than I am. But they

00:48:57.910 --> 00:49:04.059
have looked at the degree of exposure to outside
light, not necessarily the intensity of light

00:49:04.059 --> 00:49:06.890
during that outside exposure time.

00:49:06.890 --> 00:49:12.440
So I don't think we yet understand exactly
what the dose response is in terms of lux

00:49:12.440 --> 00:49:19.319
intensity. What we do know is that getting
30 to 40 minutes of outside morning light

00:49:19.319 --> 00:49:24.559
is critical. But here's the trick. Here, in
California a lot of people make this mistake,

00:49:24.559 --> 00:49:29.200
but even in London, it happens despite cloudy
day, people put shades on in the morning.

00:49:29.200 --> 00:49:37.039
Don't do that. I know it looks good. But don't.
Let that natural light penetrate your eye.

00:49:37.039 --> 00:49:42.339
There's a retinal mechanism that goes through
to your thalamus that then goes through the

00:49:42.339 --> 00:49:47.660
hypothalamus that regulates your circadian
clock. You need that light penetration. You're

00:49:47.660 --> 00:49:51.390
losing all of that good stuff if, or some
of it, if you put shades on.

00:49:51.390 --> 00:49:57.239
Wear some protection, that's fine. Just nix
the shades in the morning. In the afternoon,

00:49:57.239 --> 00:50:02.499
reverse the trick. And this is actually a
very good tip for jet lag. Jet lag is essentially

00:50:02.499 --> 00:50:07.980
an extreme form of what most of us have, which
what we've been describing this diluted amount

00:50:07.980 --> 00:50:13.599
of light during the day and then too much
light at night. Jet lag, you really should

00:50:13.599 --> 00:50:18.190
get out in the morning, 40 minutes of daylight,
no shades. And in the afternoon, it's fine

00:50:18.190 --> 00:50:23.230
to go out. But when you go out, now is the
time to put shades on, because you can start

00:50:23.230 --> 00:50:29.309
to encourage even then the release of melatonin,
which is that hormone of darkness, which signals

00:50:29.309 --> 00:50:30.900
the timing of healthy sleep.

00:50:30.900 --> 00:50:33.190
[Rhonda]: So about what time in the afternoon
would you say shades are...?

00:50:33.190 --> 00:50:37.150
[Matt]: So I would say, you know, probably...it
depends on your bedtime, if you're a morning

00:50:37.150 --> 00:50:41.230
owl or an evening lark, and we can speak about
chronotypes. So it really depends on when

00:50:41.230 --> 00:50:44.369
you're planning on going to bed. But let's
say that you're planning on going to bed at

00:50:44.369 --> 00:50:50.039
about 10 p.m., I would say, if you're sort
of going out after about to 4:30-ish, now

00:50:50.039 --> 00:50:54.390
is a good time to maybe start to help dilute
down some of that light.

00:50:54.390 --> 00:51:00.749
But then, you know, in the evenings, you know,
we are so bathed and saturated in light. And

00:51:00.749 --> 00:51:06.089
yes, we can speak a lot about LED screens,
and they are impactful, and there's been lots

00:51:06.089 --> 00:51:11.970
of work on that, some of which haven't replicated
but many of which have. I think the bigger

00:51:11.970 --> 00:51:17.090
problem is just overhead lighting in general.
We're just infused by, in every room that

00:51:17.090 --> 00:51:18.090
we go.

00:51:18.090 --> 00:51:23.539
And my recommendation has now been, in the
last hour before bed, just turn off half of

00:51:23.539 --> 00:51:28.579
the lights in your house, you know. We don't
necessarily need all of them blazing in the

00:51:28.579 --> 00:51:35.359
last hour before bed. And when you do that,
it's quite surprising how soporific and somnogenic

00:51:35.359 --> 00:51:39.960
it actually is, you know. And I want to do
the experiment, although someone beat me to

00:51:39.960 --> 00:51:42.980
the experiment, and they did it...you know,
it's one of those studies when I read it,

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:49.130
I just thought, my first reaction, I'm not
a big person. My first reaction was, oh, I'm

00:51:49.130 --> 00:51:50.130
so jealous.

00:51:50.130 --> 00:51:51.130
[Rhonda]: Oh, yeah.

00:51:51.130 --> 00:51:53.849
[Matt]: I was like, oh, I wish I've done...And
then I just thought, this is a brilliant paper.

00:51:53.849 --> 00:51:58.119
I can't wait to teach it. They took a group
of people. They looked at their habitual amount

00:51:58.119 --> 00:52:02.430
of sleep that they would typically get. And
these people are getting sort of seven and

00:52:02.430 --> 00:52:06.349
a half to eight hours. And they would ask,
you know, "When are you gointo sleep?" And

00:52:06.349 --> 00:52:11.299
sort of most of them would go to bed like
11 and sleep through till 7.

00:52:11.299 --> 00:52:15.339
And then they took them out of that typical,
you know, modernity environment, and they

00:52:15.339 --> 00:52:18.619
took them out to the Rockies. And they had
sleep tracking equipment on them. They took

00:52:18.619 --> 00:52:23.720
them there for several weeks. And there was
no electricity whatsoever, not even a torch,

00:52:23.720 --> 00:52:29.240
not even a headlamp from a car, nothing. And
then they look to see what changed.

00:52:29.240 --> 00:52:33.210
The first thing was that these people went
from sleeping, you know, an acclaimed seven

00:52:33.210 --> 00:52:37.210
and a half or seven hours of sleep that was
their norm. It was actually just below seven,

00:52:37.210 --> 00:52:41.200
saying, "That was fine. That's all I needed."
To then, actually, when they had no watch,

00:52:41.200 --> 00:52:45.339
they didn't know when to wake up, no alarm
clocks, they ended up sleeping closer to nine

00:52:45.339 --> 00:52:49.470
hours a night, which is what we typically
see when you saturate sort of people away

00:52:49.470 --> 00:52:52.010
from or dislocate them from modernity.

00:52:52.010 --> 00:52:54.760
[Rhonda]: So would you say that's a good sleep
duration?

00:52:54.760 --> 00:52:59.059
[Matt]: Well, I think somewhere between seven
to nine is what we recommend. But I think

00:52:59.059 --> 00:53:02.890
when you do this in a healthy, young people,
and these were healthy, young people, they

00:53:02.890 --> 00:53:06.609
seemed to acclimate to a sleep amount that
was somewhere between sort of eight to nine

00:53:06.609 --> 00:53:12.230
hours of sleep. So I think it's good evidence
that, you know...You can look at how hunter-gatherer

00:53:12.230 --> 00:53:16.829
tribes were sleeping. And we've studied, you
know, these people. And they actually sleep

00:53:16.829 --> 00:53:22.779
in a strange manner. We can get back to that.
And people have tried to use them as the gold

00:53:22.779 --> 00:53:24.589
standard as to how we should be sleeping.

00:53:24.589 --> 00:53:27.000
[Rhonda]: They're a lot more active and...I
mean, they're so different, right?

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:30.739
[Matt]: I don't think it's a good control.
I think we should say, "Let's take modern

00:53:30.739 --> 00:53:36.309
human beings and let's just take them out
of all context of modernity. And let's see

00:53:36.309 --> 00:53:43.170
how they're sleeping. Let's just sort of put
them on an ad-lib buffet of sleep. And they

00:53:43.170 --> 00:53:47.940
can just sleep as much as they want. They're
not told when to wake up and sort of when

00:53:47.940 --> 00:53:53.450
to go to bed." And they seem to sleep what
we now think of as a natural amount, which

00:53:53.450 --> 00:53:56.891
is somewhere between, if you look at the distribution,
seven to nine hours.

00:53:56.891 --> 00:53:58.210
[Rhonda]: And these are younger individuals?
Sure.

00:53:58.210 --> 00:54:02.559
[Matt]: Yup. And we can speak about, and I
hope we speak about sleep and aging. But what

00:54:02.559 --> 00:54:06.960
was also interesting is when they slept, not
just how much they slept. They started to

00:54:06.960 --> 00:54:12.759
go to bed earlier and earlier and earlier,
and they started to wake up a little bit earlier

00:54:12.759 --> 00:54:18.760
and earlier. And the total duration of sleep
expended. But where that expanded amount of

00:54:18.760 --> 00:54:23.849
sleep was positioned on the 24-hour clock
was dragged back because they weren't influenced

00:54:23.849 --> 00:54:28.599
by these cues of, you know, too much daylight
at night. Temperature is another one that

00:54:28.599 --> 00:54:30.980
I'd love to speak about, too.

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:36.440
But what's fascinating is that when you look
at hunter-gatherer tribes, all these experiments

00:54:36.440 --> 00:54:44.609
of sort of true nature, the natural point
of middle point of sleep, the middle phase

00:54:44.609 --> 00:54:49.099
sort of time of that eight to nine hours sleep
phase, came somewhere between midnight and

00:54:49.099 --> 00:54:53.529
1:00 p.m. And I often ask people this question,
you know, "Have you ever thought about what

00:54:53.529 --> 00:55:00.890
the term midnight actually means?" You know,
it means the middle of the solar night, which

00:55:00.890 --> 00:55:04.500
is the time when most of us should be in the
middle of our sleep phase.

00:55:04.500 --> 00:55:09.819
But now, in the 21st century, we've gone through
the, you know, the agrarian sort of, you know,

00:55:09.819 --> 00:55:15.590
pushed into the industrial era, and now into
the digital era. Now midnight is the time

00:55:15.590 --> 00:55:19.769
when we maybe check Facebook for the last
time or think about sending that last email.

00:55:19.769 --> 00:55:27.359
So not only has the duration of our sleep
decreased through the influence of the modern

00:55:27.359 --> 00:55:31.770
times but also when we're sleeping has been
dramatically shifted, too.

00:55:31.770 --> 00:55:38.619
[Rhonda]: Right. I know I've made some changes
a few years ago to my place, where now, I

00:55:38.619 --> 00:55:42.960
was telling you, I have Philips hue lights
that turn on red light. And they come on actually

00:55:42.960 --> 00:55:47.299
quite early. They come on around 5 p.m. In
fact, when we have visitors, they start to

00:55:47.299 --> 00:55:51.059
go crazy when sunset, and it's like red, and
they're like getting sleepy, you know. It's

00:55:51.059 --> 00:55:55.410
like, "Why is it so dark in here? Can we turn
the lights on?" And it's like, "No, because

00:55:55.410 --> 00:55:57.960
that's what you should...You're supposed to
be getting the sleepy right now. You're supposed

00:55:57.960 --> 00:56:03.809
to be...It's 6:00, 6:30." Well, depending
on what time of year it is, you know, "The

00:56:03.809 --> 00:56:06.420
sun is setting. You should be getting sleepy."
It's phenomenal.

00:56:06.420 --> 00:56:08.579
[Matt]: Yeah. It's one of the few triggers.

00:56:08.579 --> 00:56:10.220
[Rhonda]: Yeah, it really works.

00:56:10.220 --> 00:56:12.940
[Matt]: Temperature is the other key trigger
that...I think that's probably, you know,

00:56:12.940 --> 00:56:18.019
in the past three years, that's what we've
really understood, is that temperature is

00:56:18.019 --> 00:56:24.769
as powerful a trigger of sleep organization
and sleep depth as light is.

00:56:24.769 --> 00:56:25.859
[Rhonda]: And sleep depth.

00:56:25.859 --> 00:56:32.650
[Matt]: And sleep depth as well. So what typically
happens is that, for you to fall asleep and

00:56:32.650 --> 00:56:38.140
stay asleep, your body needs to drop its core
temperature by about 1 degree Celsius or about

00:56:38.140 --> 00:56:43.250
sort of 2 to 3 degrees Fahrenheit. And that's
the reason that you will always find it easier

00:56:43.250 --> 00:56:47.990
to fall asleep in a room that's too cold than
too hot, because the room that's too cold

00:56:47.990 --> 00:56:52.599
is at least taking you in the right thermal
direction for good sleep. It's dragging your

00:56:52.599 --> 00:56:55.640
body down into a cooler realm.

00:56:55.640 --> 00:57:01.269
And when you look at these hunter-gatherer
tribes, you know, the San in Namibia, you

00:57:01.269 --> 00:57:05.630
can look at them, whose way of life hasn't
changed for thousands of years, they don't

00:57:05.630 --> 00:57:11.039
go to bed and necessarily as immediately as
the sun goes down. They usually go to bed

00:57:11.039 --> 00:57:16.339
maybe sort of 8 or 9 in the evening, several
hours after sundown.

00:57:16.339 --> 00:57:22.099
But when they do start to go to bed is when
the temperature drops. As the sun drops, the

00:57:22.099 --> 00:57:26.500
ambient temperature remains for a little while,
and then it starts to drop, too, as the land

00:57:26.500 --> 00:57:31.089
cools, and the ambient temperature cools with
the land because darkness has ensued. That

00:57:31.089 --> 00:57:35.510
seems to be a thermal trigger for them getting
sleepy and falling asleep.

00:57:35.510 --> 00:57:41.839
Then, when you look at when they wake up,
they typically wake up 15 to 20 minutes before

00:57:41.839 --> 00:57:49.170
dawn. So it's not light that seems to be necessarily
the trigger instigating the awakening. It's

00:57:49.170 --> 00:57:51.690
actually the rise of temperature.

00:57:51.690 --> 00:57:53.349
[Rhonda]: And that's on a circadian rhythm,
right?

00:57:53.349 --> 00:57:58.229
[Matt]: And that's on a circadian...So what
is training us to our natural sleep rhythms

00:57:58.229 --> 00:58:04.869
is both temperature and light. So this comes
back to our modern homes, where we go into

00:58:04.869 --> 00:58:10.569
offices, and we don't necessarily have the
rising warmth of the day to activate us because

00:58:10.569 --> 00:58:15.380
we're set at 70 degrees, and then we go home,
and our thermostats are set at 70 degrees

00:58:15.380 --> 00:58:21.470
again or whatever your standard temperature
is. And we don't get the thermal cue through

00:58:21.470 --> 00:58:26.740
our bodies to say, "It's time for sleep."
So no wonder our sleep is worse.

00:58:26.740 --> 00:58:33.109
And if you manipulate people's core temperature,
and you can do this through showers, hot baths,

00:58:33.109 --> 00:58:39.499
you can do it through saunas, but there's
a great experiment where they essentially

00:58:39.499 --> 00:58:44.819
designed what it looked like a kind of a wetsuit.
And throughout the wetsuit were all of these

00:58:44.819 --> 00:58:51.359
plastic veins running through them. And the
researchers were able to exquisitely control,

00:58:51.359 --> 00:58:56.769
through water at different temperatures, the
temperature of any part of your body. So would

00:58:56.769 --> 00:59:01.489
I want to warm your hands and your feet? Or
would I want to warm your core?

00:59:01.489 --> 00:59:07.249
And so what they were able to do is...These
people I mean talk about being stripped of

00:59:07.249 --> 00:59:10.309
your dignity, you know. You get into this
like wetsuit, you zip it up, and you say,

00:59:10.309 --> 00:59:15.240
"Right, I'm off to bed." In you go. And then
they would manipulate core body temperature

00:59:15.240 --> 00:59:19.759
exquisitely. And lo and behold, when they
dropped the core body temperature, they were

00:59:19.759 --> 00:59:26.029
able to induce sleep quicker, and the amount
of deep sleep, what we call slow-wave sleep,

00:59:26.029 --> 00:59:30.940
which is deep non-REM sleep or Stages 3 &amp; 4,
also called slow-wave sleep because of these

00:59:30.940 --> 00:59:38.190
big powerful slow brainwaves, that deep, rich
non-REM sleep was increased somewhere between

00:59:38.190 --> 00:59:40.829
about 10% to 20%, which is non-trivial.

00:59:40.829 --> 00:59:41.829
[Rhonda]: Wow.

00:59:41.829 --> 00:59:46.380
[Matt]: Then they said, "Well," this is in
sort of, you know, young healthy people, "what

00:59:46.380 --> 00:59:50.539
about people with insomnia, and people who
are older." Because older people struggle

00:59:50.539 --> 00:59:55.190
with sleep and, of course, insomnia. And they
were able to get even greater of mileage out

00:59:55.190 --> 01:00:01.220
of the thermal manipulation with those cohorts,
too. So I think it's a very interesting intervention

01:00:01.220 --> 01:00:05.710
possibility to try and augment and manipulate
human sleep.

01:00:05.710 --> 01:00:08.779
[Rhonda]: So do you think those things, like
the chili pads that are out there, you think

01:00:08.779 --> 01:00:10.839
those can potentially help deep sleep?

01:00:10.839 --> 01:00:15.140
[Matt]: Yeah. I don't know of any data from
them yet. All I know is the experimental data

01:00:15.140 --> 01:00:20.489
that we've looked at, you know, with manipulation
of body temperature. They did this in rats

01:00:20.489 --> 01:00:26.599
awhile back, by the way, which is they would
warm their paws. And when they warm their

01:00:26.599 --> 01:00:29.339
paws, the rats fell asleep quicker and stayed
asleep.

01:00:29.339 --> 01:00:33.299
And you think, hang on a second, you just
told me that you need to cool the body, but

01:00:33.299 --> 01:00:38.039
you're talking about warming them up. And
this is the reason why probably saunas work,

01:00:38.039 --> 01:00:42.380
hot baths work, and showers work for the opposite
reason that most people believe them to work.

01:00:42.380 --> 01:00:46.960
You think, you know, I get out of a hot bath,
and I'm nice and toasty, I get into bed, and

01:00:46.960 --> 01:00:48.230
I fall asleep faster.

01:00:48.230 --> 01:00:53.580
That's not true. What happens is that you
get into the bath, you get massive vasodilation.

01:00:53.580 --> 01:01:00.009
All of the vessels open up on the surface
of your skin. That draws, it almost charms,

01:01:00.009 --> 01:01:06.220
the blood out from the core of your body to
the surface. And your skin and your hands

01:01:06.220 --> 01:01:11.230
and your feet especially act like these wonderful
thermal radiators. And they dissipate the

01:01:11.230 --> 01:01:17.000
heat. So you get out of the bath, and your
core body temperature actually plummets, and

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:18.130
that's what you need for good sleep.

01:01:18.130 --> 01:01:22.480
And I suspect this the reason that saunas...I
mean, I think you've had experience it too.

01:01:22.480 --> 01:01:26.810
[Rhonda]: Yeah, definitely. It definitely
affects my sleep. And going from a sauna into,

01:01:26.810 --> 01:01:32.460
like, an ice cold shower and then doing kind
of like going back and forth really really

01:01:32.460 --> 01:01:38.339
helps sleep. And I've used that also going
to other countries. Getting in the sauna and

01:01:38.339 --> 01:01:42.119
going the cold shower and then back in the
sauna.

01:01:42.119 --> 01:01:43.119
[Matt]: And triggering it back.

01:01:43.119 --> 01:01:44.119
[Rhonda]: It helps with my jet lag.

01:01:44.119 --> 01:01:45.119
[Matt]: Yeah.

01:01:45.119 --> 01:01:47.319
[Rhonda]: I mean, it's an end of too, because
my husband experience the same thing. But,

01:01:47.319 --> 01:01:49.940
you know, there's definitely something...there's
something there. And what you're saying absolutely

01:01:49.940 --> 01:01:54.769
happens. The sauna increases vasodilation,
blood flow goes to the skin, and so dissipation

01:01:54.769 --> 01:01:56.869
of heat. That all makes perfect sense. So
hot bath...

01:01:56.869 --> 01:02:00.719
[Matt]: I'm just gonna, very quickly, just
grab a quick mouthful of water.

01:02:00.719 --> 01:02:08.180
[Rhonda]: The hot baths and hot showers are
good before bed.

01:02:08.180 --> 01:02:15.450
[Matt]: Yeah. And I'll just mention, I think
one thing that's I think fascinated me, though,

01:02:15.450 --> 01:02:22.849
about the benefit of exercise...so exercise
also has a really nice, powerful benefit on

01:02:22.849 --> 01:02:28.299
sleep, although it's a two-way street, and
remind me to talk about that, in a good way.

01:02:28.299 --> 01:02:33.319
But something else has occurred to me with
saunas, too. And I was thinking about this,

01:02:33.319 --> 01:02:38.750
because I think I know that you're a fan.
I think you've mentioned this before. One

01:02:38.750 --> 01:02:44.910
of the ways that you can induce sleep is that
you can increase a lot of the immune factors,

01:02:44.910 --> 01:02:50.989
things like cytokines, you know, things also
like TNF-alpha, or...

01:02:50.989 --> 01:02:52.819
[Rhonda]: IL-6.

01:02:52.819 --> 01:03:00.319
[Matt]: IL-6. IL-1 even more so, but IL-6
is part of that equation, too. We've known

01:03:00.319 --> 01:03:06.989
this for some time that if you infect an animal,
it will create an immune antibody response,

01:03:06.989 --> 01:03:13.779
a cytokine cascade. Those cytokines have a
direct communication pathway into brain structures,

01:03:13.779 --> 01:03:20.960
including things like the hypothalamus, which
regulates sleep. And it's that immune cascade

01:03:20.960 --> 01:03:27.260
that is actually a trigger in dialing up the
amount of sleep. So when animals get sick,

01:03:27.260 --> 01:03:30.489
just like when humans get sick, the thing
that you want to do is just curl up in bed

01:03:30.489 --> 01:03:31.489
and go to sleep.

01:03:31.489 --> 01:03:36.920
And in fact, you get sleepier as a consequence
of being infected. Why is that? The reason

01:03:36.920 --> 01:03:41.799
is because there is nothing better...Sleep
is the Swiss Army knife of health, that no

01:03:41.799 --> 01:03:43.339
matter what the ailment...

01:03:43.339 --> 01:03:44.339
[Rhonda]: That's so cool. I don't know...

01:03:44.339 --> 01:03:48.440
[Matt]: You know, there is something more
than likely in the armament of sleep toolbox,

01:03:48.440 --> 01:03:53.900
sort of as it were, that will deal with that,
and so, and I promise I'm not going off an

01:03:53.900 --> 01:03:57.839
attention here, so the idea is that these
immune factors are sleep-instigating.

01:03:57.839 --> 01:04:00.619
[Rhonda]: This is awesome. Wow.

01:04:00.619 --> 01:04:05.040
[Matt]: They are sleep, sort of, you know,
they're somnogenic, you know. Somno-sleep-genic

01:04:05.040 --> 01:04:11.749
increased genesis improvement. So what I've
