01:05:21.710 --> 01:05:27.530
pro-inflammatory cytokines that sort of get
released to perhaps deal with some of, you

01:05:27.530 --> 01:05:32.670
know, the essential distress. And, you know,
I think we've both spoken about this that...

01:05:32.670 --> 01:05:36.849
[Rhonda]: So that way, like if you're exercising
a lot, you do seem to require more sleep,

01:05:36.849 --> 01:05:37.849
or you sleep more?

01:05:37.849 --> 01:05:39.640
[Matt]: Well, we don't know that, but that's
my current theory...

01:05:39.640 --> 01:05:40.640
[Rhonda]: Yeah, it's a great hypothesis.

01:05:40.640 --> 01:05:42.310
[Matt]: ...which is that, you know, you possibly...

01:05:42.310 --> 01:05:43.950
[Rhonda]: Are you gonna test that? That's
awesome.

01:05:43.950 --> 01:05:47.609
[Matt]: Yeah, we're going to test. So we've
just actually been looking at studying not

01:05:47.609 --> 01:05:53.549
with exercise or with saunas but we've had
been looking at sleep and pain. And when you

01:05:53.549 --> 01:05:58.920
deprive people of sleep, you get a chronic
release of these pro-inflammatory cytokines,

01:05:58.920 --> 01:06:04.900
which is not a good situation. Acute, great,
somnogenic, good for the body. But chronic

01:06:04.900 --> 01:06:11.029
long-term, we're starting to piece together
a brain-body-sleep-pain interaction, which

01:06:11.029 --> 01:06:15.099
I think has, we haven't published this yet,
but should have marked implications for the

01:06:15.099 --> 01:06:19.220
hospital environment. Because the one place
where you do not get a good night of sleep,

01:06:19.220 --> 01:06:23.339
where it's architected against the night of
sleep, is the one place where you need sleep

01:06:23.339 --> 01:06:27.729
the most, and it's usually the one place where
you are in pain the most.

01:06:27.729 --> 01:06:32.809
And I want a revolution to happen regarding
sleep in hospitals. And I'm desperately trying

01:06:32.809 --> 01:06:38.390
to work with folks. For example, the NHS in
the United Kingdom, National Healthcare System

01:06:38.390 --> 01:06:43.849
there. I would love to work with any hospital
system in the U.S. to solve this crisis, I

01:06:43.849 --> 01:06:45.749
think, of sleep in the hospital environment.

01:06:45.749 --> 01:06:52.369
But, to come back to your point, this is a
