01:09:21.609 --> 01:09:22.620
[Matt]: Somnogenic.

01:09:22.620 --> 01:09:27.330
[Rhonda]: Somnogenic, yes. How it's somnogenic.
So interesting. I had no idea that the cytokines

01:09:27.330 --> 01:09:34.000
were responsible for that, and it makes perfect
sense. So, anyway. But also, so the opposite

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:37.450
is true where sleep also affects the immune
system, or a lack of sleep also, right?

01:09:37.450 --> 01:09:38.450
[Matt]: It does, yeah.

01:09:38.450 --> 01:09:42.630
[Rhonda]: And that is something, you know...Your
immune system is the first line of defense

01:09:42.630 --> 01:09:45.920
against, even pretty much everything, right:
cancer, viruses, bacteria.

01:09:45.920 --> 01:09:46.920
[Matt]: Yeah.

01:09:46.920 --> 01:09:51.800
[Rhonda]: And I think in your book, you were
talking about the effects on, some studies,

01:09:51.800 --> 01:09:55.790
on natural killer T cells. I mean, I was just,
like, blown away by some of the numbers.

01:09:55.790 --> 01:10:00.890
[Matt]: This is a frightening study. So it's
done by my colleague Mike Erwin. You take

01:10:00.890 --> 01:10:04.620
a group of individuals, and you're not going
to deprive them of sleep for an entire night.

01:10:04.620 --> 01:10:09.910
You're simply going to limit them, restrict
them to four hours of sleep for one single

01:10:09.910 --> 01:10:15.020
night. And then we're going to measure the
amount of reduction in natural killer cell

01:10:15.020 --> 01:10:16.020
activity.

01:10:16.020 --> 01:10:20.500
So just to take a step back, natural killer
cells are a critical part of your immune defense

01:10:20.500 --> 01:10:28.050
arsenal. And today, both you and I and everyone
listening to this podcast, we all have cancer

01:10:28.050 --> 01:10:33.120
cells that have emerged in our bodies. But
typically, what prevents those cells from

01:10:33.120 --> 01:10:38.580
becoming this disease that we call cancer
is, in part, these natural killer cells. So

01:10:38.580 --> 01:10:44.870
what you wish for is a virile set of these
sort of immune assassins, these sort of James-Bond-like,

01:10:44.870 --> 01:10:49.580
you know, that they will annihilate these
foreign organisms. You want a virile of those

01:10:49.580 --> 01:10:51.530
at all times.

01:10:51.530 --> 01:10:57.840
So take a group of healthy people, limit them
to four hours of sleep for one night, and

01:10:57.840 --> 01:11:03.690
what you see is a 70% reduction in natural
killer cell activity, seven zero. That is

01:11:03.690 --> 01:11:08.690
an alarming state of immune-deficiency. And
it happens quickly essentially after one bad

01:11:08.690 --> 01:11:13.580
night of sleep. So you can imagine, you know,
the state of your immune system after weeks,

01:11:13.580 --> 01:11:19.020
if not years, of insufficient sleep. And it's
now the reason I think that we probably are

01:11:19.020 --> 01:11:24.640
finding, at the epidemiological level, significant
links between short sleep duration, not getting

01:11:24.640 --> 01:11:28.700
enough sleep, defined as six hours or less,
and your risk for the development of numerous

01:11:28.700 --> 01:11:33.310
forms of cancer. Currently, that list includes
cancer of the bowel, cancer of the prostate,

01:11:33.310 --> 01:11:35.420
cancer of the breast.

01:11:35.420 --> 01:11:40.030
And the link between the lack of sleep and
cancer is now so strong that, recently, the

01:11:40.030 --> 01:11:45.780
World Health Organization decided to classify
any form of nighttime shift work as a probable

01:11:45.780 --> 01:11:51.510
carcinogen. So in other words jobs, that could
induce cancer because of a disruption of your

01:11:51.510 --> 01:11:52.510
sleep-wake rhythms.

01:11:52.510 --> 01:12:00.120
So, you know, that's the immune system in
cancer. But it doesn't stop there as well.

01:12:00.120 --> 01:12:03.861
Another great study that was done by Aric
Prather [SP], who is over at UCSF, another

01:12:03.861 --> 01:12:09.670
good colleague of mine, he did this brilliant
study that I write about in the book. He basically

01:12:09.670 --> 01:12:14.470
measured the sleep of a group of healthy people
for a week before using these wristwatches

01:12:14.470 --> 01:12:21.100
that are accurate. And then he quarantined
them in a hotel, in a set of hotel rooms.

01:12:21.100 --> 01:12:26.880
And then he proceeded to stuff up their nose,
squirt up their nose, rhinovirus, essentially,

01:12:26.880 --> 01:12:32.140
a flu virus. And then he quarantined them
for a week. And he measured how many of them

01:12:32.140 --> 01:12:38.010
became infected. And he was measuring all
sorts of stuff. He collected every ounce of

01:12:38.010 --> 01:12:42.600
snot that they blew out of their nose, all
of the mucus, everything.

01:12:42.600 --> 01:12:48.990
And what he found was that those people who
were getting five hours of sleep or less in

01:12:48.990 --> 01:12:54.540
the week before they came in and were infected
relative to those who are getting seven hours

01:12:54.540 --> 01:12:58.900
of sleep or more, those people who were getting
five hours of sleep in the week before they

01:12:58.900 --> 01:13:05.120
got infected were four times more likely to
end up developing the flu than those people

01:13:05.120 --> 01:13:07.460
who are getting seven hours or more.

01:13:07.460 --> 01:13:12.500
The final nail in that sort of immune coffin
for me is a study that was done by Eve Van

01:13:12.500 --> 01:13:17.120
Cauter, who's a wonderful endocrinologist.
And I'd love, by the way, to speak about sleeping

01:13:17.120 --> 01:13:22.150
diabetes and glucose regulation, too. She's
doing some great work there. But she did a

01:13:22.150 --> 01:13:28.001
great study. She looked at the amount of sleep
that you were getting in the week before you

01:13:28.001 --> 01:13:30.480
get your flu shot.

01:13:30.480 --> 01:13:35.500
And what she found is that if you're getting
sort of less than five or six hours of sleep

01:13:35.500 --> 01:13:41.260
in the week before you get your flu shot,
you only produce half of the normal antibody

01:13:41.260 --> 01:13:47.620
response, rendering that flu shot largely
useless, which stuns me that, you know...And

01:13:47.620 --> 01:13:54.890
here's his work technology could revolutionize
healthcare. You know, what if Kaiser, you

01:13:54.890 --> 01:13:59.030
know, had access to a sleep tracker or had
its own sleep tracker. And Kaiser, for those

01:13:59.030 --> 01:14:02.530
not familiar, is a health care provider here
in the United States.

01:14:02.530 --> 01:14:07.940
But what if, you know, any healthcare provider
or system in any country had access to your

01:14:07.940 --> 01:14:14.000
sleep in a non-Big-Brother way. And it was
tracking your sleep. And through an app, it

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:19.830
would say, "Hey, you've had a great week of
sleep this weekend in December," or "this

01:14:19.830 --> 01:14:24.680
week in November. Now is the time to come
and get your flu shot. I've listed out three

01:14:24.680 --> 01:14:26.640
appointments. Just tap on the one that you
want."

01:14:26.640 --> 01:14:31.330
Or it says, "Look, I know that you scheduled
yourself for a flu shot. You haven't quite

01:14:31.330 --> 01:14:37.080
got the good sleep that you need this past
week. Let's try again next week." And if you

01:14:37.080 --> 01:14:41.890
get the sleep next week, then you give them
access to getting the flu shot. Because otherwise,

01:14:41.890 --> 01:14:48.190
we're wasting money. And the flu, you know,
cost the United States, the flu season cost

01:14:48.190 --> 01:14:53.940
the United States about $10 billion directly
in terms of healthcare burden. Even if I could

01:14:53.940 --> 01:15:00.120
nudge that by just 1% or 2% by understanding
people's sleep and helping architect a system

01:15:00.120 --> 01:15:05.860
that co-opts around sleep time and management,
we could save hundreds of millions of dollars

01:15:05.860 --> 01:15:07.270
to the U.S. economy.

