01:17:35.270 --> 01:17:40.480
And I'm just starting to write up a theory
paper about this, which is an encompassing

01:17:40.480 --> 01:17:45.130
theory about sleep deprivation within the
human brain and the body. And I think there

01:17:45.130 --> 01:17:50.890
is a common, central dictating governing pathway,
which is the autonomic nervous system through

01:17:50.890 --> 01:17:55.310
which there is a manipulation of many of the
hormone systems, which then give rise to the

01:17:55.310 --> 01:18:00.090
whole host of deficits that we see by way
of a lack of sleep, which then ultimately,

01:18:00.090 --> 01:18:04.860
through chronic exposure of sleep loss, give
rise to all of the diseases that we know are

01:18:04.860 --> 01:18:10.230
associated with a lack of sleep. And every
single disease that is killing us in the developed

01:18:10.230 --> 01:18:14.120
world has causal and significant links to
a lack of sleep.

01:18:14.120 --> 01:18:20.850
[Rhonda]: One that I'm particularly interested
in is Alzheimer's disease. It's something

01:18:20.850 --> 01:18:25.470
that I've been researching for a while. I'm
about to get published thankfully soon.

01:18:25.470 --> 01:18:26.470
[Matt]: Congratulations.

01:18:26.470 --> 01:18:27.470
[Rhonda]: Thank you.

01:18:27.470 --> 01:18:28.470
[Matt]: Was this a review paper?

01:18:28.470 --> 01:18:29.470
[Rhonda]: Yeah.

01:18:29.470 --> 01:18:30.470
[Matt]: Oh, please send it to me.

01:18:30.470 --> 01:18:35.251
[Rhonda]: And it happens to do with a gene
called apoe4. And I found out that I have

01:18:35.251 --> 01:18:40.250
one copy of this of this allele. And when
I found that out years ago, I was like...it's

01:18:40.250 --> 01:18:45.110
probably the biggest risk factor for late-onset
on Alzheimer's disease besides age.

01:18:45.110 --> 01:18:50.450
[Matt]: Yes. So I think one of those alleles,
it's about sorts of two to threefold risk.

01:18:50.450 --> 01:18:51.450
[Rhonda]: Two to threefold.

01:18:51.450 --> 01:18:52.810
[Matt]: If you have two of them, it's like
an 8 to 12.

01:18:52.810 --> 01:18:57.700
[Rhonda]: Yeah, it's, like, pretty bad. And
25% of the population in the United States

01:18:57.700 --> 01:19:02.540
has at least one allele. So it's definitely...And
just because you have it doesn't mean you're

01:19:02.540 --> 01:19:03.860
necessarily gonna get Alzheimer's disease.

01:19:03.860 --> 01:19:04.860
[Matt]: That's right.

01:19:04.860 --> 01:19:09.430
[Rhonda]: Not everyone has it. But there's
a huge interaction with, you know, diet and

01:19:09.430 --> 01:19:15.980
lifestyle. Probably the biggest lifestyle
interaction with this gene is sleep. And so

01:19:15.980 --> 01:19:22.020
that was that was where I became very interested
in how sleep affects the brain, and how it

01:19:22.020 --> 01:19:26.060
affects, you know, Alzheimer's disease, and
all that. So I'd love to kind of talk a little

01:19:26.060 --> 01:19:27.060
bit about that.

01:19:27.060 --> 01:19:32.490
[Matt]: Yeah, so we've been doing a lot of
this work. We have a large research program

01:19:32.490 --> 01:19:37.440
here at UC Berkeley at the Sleep Center that
is devoted to aging and Alzheimer's disease.

01:19:37.440 --> 01:19:45.250
And we've been very fortunate to get many
grants from the NIH here to study this. I

01:19:45.250 --> 01:19:51.720
think that the story is fascinating because
it's a bi-directional relationship between

01:19:51.720 --> 01:19:57.270
sleep. And the pathology that we know is associated
with Alzheimer's disease.

01:19:57.270 --> 01:20:03.380
So in Alzheimer's disease, there are at least
two protein culprits that we believe are underlying

01:20:03.380 --> 01:20:08.120
of the brain pathology that seems to create
this thing called Alzheimer's. One of them

01:20:08.120 --> 01:20:14.060
is a sticky toxic protein called beta amyloid
that accumulates in these clumps outside of

01:20:14.060 --> 01:20:20.850
brain cells. And that creates these amyloid
plaques that seem to be correlated with your

01:20:20.850 --> 01:20:24.830
disease risk and disease severity.

01:20:24.830 --> 01:20:29.760
The other is a protein that we know probably
less about, which is a protein called tau

01:20:29.760 --> 01:20:36.630
protein. And that sits inside of cells. And
it creates a support structure for communicating

01:20:36.630 --> 01:20:41.420
and funneling many of the critical ingredients
up and down your nerve cells to keep them

01:20:41.420 --> 01:20:48.170
in rude health. And during Alzheimer's disease,
that protein starts to sort of fall apart

01:20:48.170 --> 01:20:55.960
and dismantle. And you get these sort of tau
tangles. And the structure of the nerve cell

01:20:55.960 --> 01:21:01.420
and its ability to transport all of the ingredients
that it needs to operate starts to collapse

01:21:01.420 --> 01:21:05.760
and fails like a tunnel collapsing down.

01:21:05.760 --> 01:21:15.380
So one of the discoveries that we made back
in 2013 was that I was looking at the distribution

01:21:15.380 --> 01:21:20.050
of this sticky toxic protein called amyloid
in the human brain. And what's fascinating

01:21:20.050 --> 01:21:25.820
is that it doesn't build up in the brain in
homogeneously. Amyloid builds up in some parts

01:21:25.820 --> 01:21:31.370
of the brain far more severely and early in
the course of Alzheimer's disease. And other

01:21:31.370 --> 01:21:38.500
parts actually remain completely uninvaded
by this thing called amyloid. In fact, parts

01:21:38.500 --> 01:21:43.780
of the motor cortex, for example, or parts
of the visual cortex, you see almost no amyloid

01:21:43.780 --> 01:21:48.360
in our Alzheimer's patients. And that's probably
the reason why their motor functions and their

01:21:48.360 --> 01:21:51.140
vision is unchanged.

01:21:51.140 --> 01:21:57.080
But one of the earliest places were beta amyloid
builds up and then built up most severely

01:21:57.080 --> 01:22:02.740
in late stages is back, again, in that medial
prefrontal cortex that sits right there in

01:22:02.740 --> 01:22:08.390
between the eyes. Why was I interested in
that? I was interested because when we were

01:22:08.390 --> 01:22:13.370
doing studies where we would map, with all
of these electrodes over your head, we would

01:22:13.370 --> 01:22:16.670
map the deep sleep that you were having.

01:22:16.670 --> 01:22:20.780
And we could do some clever mathematical modeling
of those deep sleep brain waves. And we could

01:22:20.780 --> 01:22:26.630
try to triangulate where was the electrical
epicenter of those electrical deep brain waves

01:22:26.630 --> 01:22:31.270
of deep sleep. And it seems as though they
come from all over the brain, but the principal

01:22:31.270 --> 01:22:36.270
epicenter that generates your deep sleep sits
right there in the middle part of the prefrontal

01:22:36.270 --> 01:22:42.740
cortex. It is exactly the same part of the
brain that accumulates toxic beta amyloid

01:22:42.740 --> 01:22:44.210
protein.

01:22:44.210 --> 01:22:48.800
Then we've done studies, and other people
have done studies before us, that demonstrated,

01:22:48.800 --> 01:22:54.780
as we age, our sleep gets worse. But just
any type of sleep. Especially that deep quality

01:22:54.780 --> 01:23:00.490
of sleep that we know and we spoke about is
critical for saving and learning and retaining

01:23:00.490 --> 01:23:06.350
new memories. So all of these jigsaw pieces
started to get put together in my head. I

01:23:06.350 --> 01:23:13.000
thought we need to do some studies. Is it
possible that the amount of amyloid that you

01:23:13.000 --> 01:23:19.190
have in the brain in this sleep-generating
center, it should directly predict the deficit

01:23:19.190 --> 01:23:23.700
in the amount of deep sleep that you get?
If it predicts the deficit in the amount of

01:23:23.700 --> 01:23:29.570
deep sleep, it should predict the deficit
in your ability to hold on and retain new

01:23:29.570 --> 01:23:34.750
memories, which is a hallmark cognitive feature
of Alzheimer's disease, difficulty learning,

01:23:34.750 --> 01:23:36.140
difficulty retaining.

01:23:36.140 --> 01:23:41.440
So we did the study, and it's exactly what
we found. The more beta amyloid that builds

01:23:41.440 --> 01:23:47.230
up in this central frontal part of the brain,
the less the deep sleep that you have. The

01:23:47.230 --> 01:23:53.790
less amyloid-related deep sleep that you had,
the more forgetful you were the next day rather

01:23:53.790 --> 01:23:59.080
than the more that you remembered. So this
was the first part of the Alzheimer's sleep

01:23:59.080 --> 01:24:04.650
equation, which is that Alzheimer's disease
attacks the deep-sleep-generating regions

01:24:04.650 --> 01:24:11.630
and you have a diminution of deep sleep, which,
in turn, blunts your learning and memory abilities

01:24:11.630 --> 01:24:13.330
and you become more forgetful.

01:24:13.330 --> 01:24:20.411
A far more important discovery was made by
an another group, far more important than

01:24:20.411 --> 01:24:26.540
the one we made, which was essentially the
reverse direction, which was to say, "Rather

01:24:26.540 --> 01:24:33.310
than amyloid sort of decreasing sleep, could
sleep actually decrease the amount of amyloid

01:24:33.310 --> 01:24:34.310
that you get?"

01:24:34.310 --> 01:24:41.920
And this is a discovery that was made in rats
back in 2009, I believe, was the first evidence

01:24:41.920 --> 01:24:49.660
that was published in science. A colleague,
[inaudible 01:24:09], who is out on the east

01:24:49.660 --> 01:24:56.950
coast at the University of Rochester, and
she made two wonderful discoveries. The first

01:24:56.950 --> 01:25:01.120
was that we've known for a long time the body
has a waste sewage system called the lymphatic

01:25:01.120 --> 01:25:07.430
system. But the brain doesn't have its own
lymphatic system. The lymphatic system does

01:25:07.430 --> 01:25:13.970
not penetrate the brain. So where does all
of the garbage, the metabolic garbage go that

01:25:13.970 --> 01:25:17.850
your brain cells produce? Where is the sewage
system for the brain?

01:25:17.850 --> 01:25:22.770
And she discovered it. It's actually made
up of a set of cells called glial cells, which

01:25:22.770 --> 01:25:27.710
are these supporting brain cells. And so she
called it the glymphatic system rather than

01:25:27.710 --> 01:25:32.980
the lymphatic system. So your brain does have
its sewage system, this glymphatic system,

01:25:32.980 --> 01:25:36.520
and that's the discovery that she made. Remarkable.

01:25:36.520 --> 01:25:43.370
Then, and I'm not quite sure what motivated
her to do this, she started to measure how

01:25:43.370 --> 01:25:49.730
efficient that glymphatic, that waste system
was when the rats were awake and when the

01:25:49.730 --> 01:25:58.350
rats were asleep. And what she found was that
it's during deep sleep that these brain cells

01:25:58.350 --> 01:26:03.710
actually shrink by almost 60% when we sleep.
Blows my mind.

01:26:03.710 --> 01:26:04.710
[Rhonda]: Yeah.

01:26:04.710 --> 01:26:08.090
[Matt]: It's almost like, you know, all of
the buildings in New York all of a sudden

01:26:08.090 --> 01:26:13.190
shrink, and it leaves these much greater,
large areas for the cleaning crews to come

01:26:13.190 --> 01:26:18.641
in and clean up all of the metabolic detritus
of the city's activity during the day. It's

01:26:18.641 --> 01:26:24.550
exactly what happens during sleep. And the
cleaning solution is what we call cerebrospinal

01:26:24.550 --> 01:26:32.960
fluid. And through a pulsatile mechanism during
sleep, you get a 10% to 20% increase in the

01:26:32.960 --> 01:26:40.390
bathing of cerebrospinal fluid through the
brain, which washes away all of the metabolic

01:26:40.390 --> 01:26:46.140
byproducts that have been building up. One
of those metabolic byproducts is beta amyloid.

01:26:46.140 --> 01:26:53.190
And, in fact, if you deprive those rats of
that deep sleep, you immediately get an increase

01:26:53.190 --> 01:26:56.020
in toxic beta amyloid.

01:26:56.020 --> 01:27:00.910
So now we've linked these two. I'm sorry it's
a long story. But if you're not getting

01:27:00.910 --> 01:27:06.310
Enough deep sleep at night, you're not giving
yourself the chance for the kind of good night

01:27:06.310 --> 01:27:12.190
and sleep clean process to remove the beta
amyloid. So more beta amyloid builds up. Where

01:27:12.190 --> 01:27:16.970
does it build up? Tragically, in the very
same regions of the brain that generate the

01:27:16.970 --> 01:27:22.250
deep sleep that you need to clear out the
toxic amyloid. So you start getting less deep

01:27:22.250 --> 01:27:27.590
sleep, so you get more toxic protein, more
toxic protein, less deep sleep, less deep

01:27:27.590 --> 01:27:33.550
sleep. It's a self-fulfilling prophecy, and
it's a nonlinear exponential curve.

01:27:33.550 --> 01:27:37.220
If you look at how amyloid builds up in the
brain, and if you look at the trajectory of

01:27:37.220 --> 01:27:43.880
Alzheimer's disease, it is a nonlinear exponential
curve. It fits exactly what the sleep-dependent

01:27:43.880 --> 01:27:48.571
model of amyloid clearance would predict.
If you're not getting sufficient sleep, that's

01:27:48.571 --> 01:27:53.240
the reason why now insufficient sleep seems
to be one of the most significant lifestyle

01:27:53.240 --> 01:27:55.400
factors determining that.

01:27:55.400 --> 01:27:59.950
Now you could say, by the way, those studies
were in rats, and you deprived from the sleep

01:27:59.950 --> 01:28:05.940
for one night. What about humans? Like, surely...Well,
the study has now been done. Great study done

01:28:05.940 --> 01:28:13.990
out of Wash U by a team of scientists. They're
led by David Holtzman. And they took a group

01:28:13.990 --> 01:28:18.980
of humans, and they did this very clever method
where they deprive them of deep sleep but

01:28:18.980 --> 01:28:20.950
they didn't deprive them of sleep.

01:28:20.950 --> 01:28:26.920
And you think, it sounds paradoxical. I can
play you these auditory tones. Now this is

01:28:26.920 --> 01:28:31.670
not like the memory reactivation where you
play a tone and then you leave the brain alone

01:28:31.670 --> 01:28:36.010
for a while. Here, I'm just going to keep
playing tones to your brain, really sort of

01:28:36.010 --> 01:28:41.340
annoying tones. But I can play them at a level
that doesn't wake you up, but it lifts you

01:28:41.340 --> 01:28:45.390
out of deep sleep and keeps you in shallow
sleep.

01:28:45.390 --> 01:28:50.460
So what's delightful about this method is
that I can selectively excise one type of

01:28:50.460 --> 01:28:55.940
sleep, deep sleep, but I don't wake you up.
So there's no stress of awakening. You are

01:28:55.940 --> 01:29:00.510
asleep for the same amount of time, but the
quality of sleep is decreased.

01:29:00.510 --> 01:29:01.920
[Rhonda]: Can street noise do that?

01:29:01.920 --> 01:29:07.340
[Matt]: We don't know. Although I will come
back to that when we speak about hopefully

01:29:07.340 --> 01:29:15.470
sleep appetite regulation, sleep glucose regulation,
and sleep in low socio-economic cultures...

01:29:15.470 --> 01:29:16.710
[Rhonda]: This is a little terrifying.

01:29:16.710 --> 01:29:20.190
[Matt]: And I think that it's possible. I
think there's other factors that link poor

01:29:20.190 --> 01:29:25.531
sleep in low SES, socioeconomic backgrounds.
Is noise pollution one of them? I actually

01:29:25.531 --> 01:29:32.240
think it is. Untested as yet. But what they
did with these human participants, they selectively

01:29:32.240 --> 01:29:37.540
remove deep sleep while keeping them asleep
so total sleep time has not changed. And then,

01:29:37.540 --> 01:29:41.890
in the morning, they woke them up, they rolled
them over, and they did a spinal cord puncture,

01:29:41.890 --> 01:29:48.170
a lumbar puncture, and they measured the cerebrospinal
fluid that was populated within the spinal

01:29:48.170 --> 01:29:52.420
cord, which also goes around the brain. And
you can measure the amount of beta amyloid,

01:29:52.420 --> 01:29:56.040
which is a reflection of perhaps how much
amyloid is there within the brain.

01:29:56.040 --> 01:30:02.440
After one night of essentially a loss of deep
sleep, you saw an immediate rise in the amount

01:30:02.440 --> 01:30:08.130
of beta amyloid. So it is a causal manipulation.
That insufficient sleep in rodents and in

01:30:08.130 --> 01:30:11.080
humans will lead to a rise in beta amyloid.

01:30:11.080 --> 01:30:13.570
[Rhonda]: Yeah. I think it was like 25% to
30%.

01:30:13.570 --> 01:30:14.570
[Matt]: It was.

01:30:14.570 --> 01:30:19.090
[Rhonda]: Yeah, it was definitely...So, of
course, that's all I could think about the

01:30:19.090 --> 01:30:20.620
past nine months...

01:30:20.620 --> 01:30:21.620
[Matt]: Showing that, yeah.

01:30:21.620 --> 01:30:22.620
[Rhonda]: And the buildup of amyloid.

01:30:22.620 --> 01:30:25.530
[Matt]: You know, I would tell you, that's
the last thing you should think about. You

01:30:25.530 --> 01:30:30.190
know, try not to worry too much about it,
you know, because it's not to say to diminish

01:30:30.190 --> 01:30:34.620
the loss of sleep but simply to say that worrying
about it is not gonna do you any good.

01:30:34.620 --> 01:30:35.620
[Rhonda]: Of course.

01:30:35.620 --> 01:30:41.470
[Matt]: But how do you tell that especially
to people who, you know, have one ApoE allele...apoe-4,

01:30:41.470 --> 01:30:47.030
sorry, allele. What I would also say that's
important for people, if you know your ApoE

01:30:47.030 --> 01:30:54.910
status, and if you are apoe-4, be mindful
of snoring as well. Because people who are

01:30:54.910 --> 01:31:01.900
apoe-4-positive, they also have a significantly
elevated risk of a sleep disorder that we

01:31:01.900 --> 01:31:06.640
call sleep apnea, which is sleep disorder
breathing, which is heavy snoring and a cessation

01:31:06.640 --> 01:31:11.330
of breathing entirely. And then you gasp when
you wake up again.

01:31:11.330 --> 01:31:16.870
Heavy snoring sleep apnea is a killer. It
is an outright killer. It increases your risk

01:31:16.870 --> 01:31:23.900
of basically everything you don't want: cardiovascular
disease, stroke, diabetes, and obesity. It

01:31:23.900 --> 01:31:29.350
also increases your risk of immediate death
through a higher risk of car accidents.

01:31:29.350 --> 01:31:34.690
But one of the other problems with sleep apnea
is that you don't get the amount of deep sleep

01:31:34.690 --> 01:31:39.190
that you need. And you have hypoxic damage.
Because you stopped breathing, your oxygen

01:31:39.190 --> 01:31:45.160
saturation goes down. You get hypoxia damage
particularly in a region that is most sensitive

01:31:45.160 --> 01:31:50.350
to it in the brain, which is, drumroll, the
hippocampus, the very same memory structure

01:31:50.350 --> 01:31:53.000
that is attacked in Alzheimer's disease.

01:31:53.000 --> 01:32:01.240
So now you can see why I appeal for this sensitivity
in this danger to sleep apnea. Because if

01:32:01.240 --> 01:32:05.600
you are apoe-4, you're already at high risk
of Alzheimer's disease, you need to pay attention

01:32:05.600 --> 01:32:11.330
to your sleep. If you start snoring, and you
have sleep apnea untreated, you will get less

01:32:11.330 --> 01:32:16.670
deep sleep. So you're compromising the thing
that you need to try and lower your amyloid

01:32:16.670 --> 01:32:20.080
risk to begin with, because you're going to
build up that amyloid, because you're not

01:32:20.080 --> 01:32:25.760
going to get the amyloid clearance elsewhere
in the body, for example, in the liver. And

01:32:25.760 --> 01:32:29.770
then where still the part of the brain that
is attacked severely by Alzheimer's disease

01:32:29.770 --> 01:32:34.730
and atrophies, which is the hippocampus, which
is why memory fades, is a part of the brain

01:32:34.730 --> 01:32:39.200
that is damaged when you stop breathing because
of oxygen desaturation.

01:32:39.200 --> 01:32:46.700
So, as an appeal, even if you are not apoe-4-positive,
but you are snoring, or you know someone who

01:32:46.700 --> 01:32:53.040
is snoring, go and see your doctor and get
a sleep apnea test. It is potentially life-saving.

01:32:53.040 --> 01:32:56.870
[Rhonda]: Actually, I had a sleep apnea test
because of my night awakenings. I didn't know.

01:32:56.870 --> 01:33:02.770
It was, like, maybe I have apnea and I couldn't...And
so I'm having this terror. And of course,

01:33:02.770 --> 01:33:07.260
that wasn't it. I don't have sleep apnea.
But I didn't know about the connection between

01:33:07.260 --> 01:33:09.520
apoe-4 and sleep apnea. That's terrible because...

01:33:09.520 --> 01:33:11.600
[Matt]: It's quite a dramatic...

01:33:11.600 --> 01:33:12.600
[Rhonda]: Yeah.

01:33:12.600 --> 01:33:15.050
[Matt]: I mean, you can bind those two together.
It's a real...I mean, itâ€™s gasoline on an

01:33:15.050 --> 01:33:16.050
already started fire.

01:33:16.050 --> 01:33:19.490
[Rhonda]: People with apoe-4 also don't repair
damage and their brain as well as people with

01:33:19.490 --> 01:33:20.490
apoe-3.

01:33:20.490 --> 01:33:21.490
[Matt]: They don't.

01:33:21.490 --> 01:33:23.730
[Rhonda]: So you're talking about hypoxic
damage in addition, you know, there's sort

01:33:23.730 --> 01:33:25.930
of just this potentially compounding effect.

01:33:25.930 --> 01:33:31.220
[Matt]: And I think that's, you know, that's
part of the reason...I mean, so I have some

01:33:31.220 --> 01:33:36.090
family members that have been associated with
Alzheimer's disease, one recently passed away.

01:33:36.090 --> 01:33:41.500
And it's been a big motivation for me personally.
I started, you know, 20 years ago. My PhD

01:33:41.500 --> 01:33:45.500
was looking at people with degenerative dementia.
That's how I actually got into sleep, because

01:33:45.500 --> 01:33:47.660
I was seeing these sleep abnormalities.

01:33:47.660 --> 01:33:55.180
And, you know, I'm so desperately trying to
find ways to help and to combat that incredible

01:33:55.180 --> 01:34:00.670
epidemic of dementia. And that's why we've
started to try and develop things like electrical

01:34:00.670 --> 01:34:06.650
brain stimulation methods, to try and help
actually augment human sleep, an electrically-supercharged

01:34:06.650 --> 01:34:11.480
sleep, as it were, to see if we could give
back some healthy quality of deep sleep to

01:34:11.480 --> 01:34:17.600
patients who are aging or those with dementia.
Can we essentially, you know, amplify the

01:34:17.600 --> 01:34:21.760
amount of deep sleep? And in doing so, can
we salvage aspects of learning and memory?

01:34:21.760 --> 01:34:26.960
But better still, could we actually start
to increase, you know, the amount of glymphatic

01:34:26.960 --> 01:34:29.150
clearance of beta amyloid?

01:34:29.150 --> 01:34:33.700
Now I suspect that when the disease is in
play and you've been diagnosed in those late

01:34:33.700 --> 01:34:40.410
stages, I don't know how much sleep is electrically
charged even as it maybe could help. What

01:34:40.410 --> 01:34:46.290
we're now trying to do in our studies is actually
retrospectively find out, is there a particular

01:34:46.290 --> 01:34:53.590
decade of life or decades of life when a decline
in sleep makes you most susceptible to then

01:34:53.590 --> 01:34:59.010
developing a lot more amyloid later in life?
In other words, we're trying to now identify

01:34:59.010 --> 01:35:02.600
these vulnerability windows during the lifespan.

01:35:02.600 --> 01:35:07.310
The reason I want to do that is, if I can
scientifically convince myself of a knowledge

01:35:07.310 --> 01:35:12.330
base of vulnerability sensitivity to insufficient
sleep, my guess is that it's just across the

01:35:12.330 --> 01:35:19.070
lifespan, it gives me a chance to know where
is the inflection point of not late-stage

01:35:19.070 --> 01:35:25.120
life treatment but early-life prevention.
Because that's what medicine has to do right

01:35:25.120 --> 01:35:30.470
now, I think. We've done a good job at extending
lifespan but a miserable job at extending

01:35:30.470 --> 01:35:37.200
health span. Lifespan is probably about treatment.
Health span is probably about prevention.

01:35:37.200 --> 01:35:42.110
Sleep needs to be part of that discussion.
And sleep is usually absent in many of these

01:35:42.110 --> 01:35:45.950
conversations for either lifespan or health
span despite it having a demonstrable impact

01:35:45.950 --> 01:35:50.880
on both. But my hope is that to be able to
find that sensitive time when your risk for

01:35:50.880 --> 01:35:55.820
Alzheimer's development by way of insufficient
sleep is present. That's where I go in and

01:35:55.820 --> 01:35:59.830
start augmenting your sleep with electrical
brain stimulation or other methods that we're

01:35:59.830 --> 01:36:01.050
trying to develop as well.

01:36:01.050 --> 01:36:07.370
[Rhonda]: I think, at least for the apoe-4-positive
individuals, by the age of 40, the amyloid

01:36:07.370 --> 01:36:08.550
plaques start to really...

01:36:08.550 --> 01:36:09.550
[Matt]: That's right, yup.

01:36:09.550 --> 01:36:14.750
[Rhonda]: ...you know. So, to me, it would
seem that, you know, before 40, and certainly

01:36:14.750 --> 01:36:16.801
when you hit 40, you better have your sleep
optimized.

01:36:16.801 --> 01:36:20.390
[Matt]: I would say before. I mean, we can
see the decline of deep sleep occurring in

01:36:20.390 --> 01:36:23.540
people in their 20s. That's when your deep
sleep starts to decline.

01:36:23.540 --> 01:36:24.540
[Rhonda]: Wow.

01:36:24.540 --> 01:36:28.180
[Matt]: Which is, you know, frightening, isn't
it? It's sad. And at that point, it's in the

01:36:28.180 --> 01:36:33.040
mail. You know, by the time you're 50 years
old, you've lost about 50% of the deep sleep

01:36:33.040 --> 01:36:38.150
that you are having when you are a young teenager.
By the time you're 70%, there's only about

01:36:38.150 --> 01:36:43.610
5%...sorry, by the time you're 70 years old,
there's only about 5% of your deep sleep left

01:36:43.610 --> 01:36:48.920
that you had when you were young and healthy.
By the time you're 80, we almost can't detect

01:36:48.920 --> 01:36:50.630
any of these deep sleep brain waves anymore.

01:36:50.630 --> 01:36:56.050
[Rhonda]: Do you know if there is changes
in the way your core body temperature regulates

01:36:56.050 --> 01:36:57.050
with age as well?

01:36:57.050 --> 01:37:00.400
[Matt]: There is. So what happens with age
is that your circadian rhythm that we've spoke

01:37:00.400 --> 01:37:04.950
about before...I'm just going to...So your
circadian rhythm that we spoke about before,

01:37:04.950 --> 01:37:10.360
which in healthy people is nice and high and
peaking during the day, lots of activity,

01:37:10.360 --> 01:37:16.380
and then drops down at night, lots of inactivity,
lots of deep sleep, that sinusoidal wave starts

01:37:16.380 --> 01:37:21.611
to flatten out as if someone has compressed
it as we get older. So our circadian rhythm

01:37:21.611 --> 01:37:28.010
gets weaker. So we get we feel sleepier during
the day and not as alert as we used to do,

01:37:28.010 --> 01:37:33.990
but we don't feel as though we are as sleepy
at night. We're more awake at night because

01:37:33.990 --> 01:37:36.530
our circadian rhythm is blunted.

01:37:36.530 --> 01:37:42.130
And so I think that's another area for aging
intervention, is how can we modulate the circadian

01:37:42.130 --> 01:37:47.530
rhythm. And it turns out that it comes back
to light. So one of my colleagues in the Netherlands,

01:37:47.530 --> 01:37:53.630
Eus Van Someren, did a great study where he
installed circadian-regulating light in an

01:37:53.630 --> 01:37:59.530
elderly care home, you know, in a home where
you care for the elderly. And many of them

01:37:59.530 --> 01:38:04.450
had cognitive decline. And he's now done some
of these studies with people in with Alzheimer's

01:38:04.450 --> 01:38:06.890
disease in some of these care homes.

01:38:06.890 --> 01:38:12.800
And when you start to create appropriate lighting
in the internal environment in these homes,

01:38:12.800 --> 01:38:17.530
which if you go into them, and I used to go
into them all the time during my PhD, these

01:38:17.530 --> 01:38:21.530
sort of care homes, and I would be testing
my patience and seeing my patients there,

01:38:21.530 --> 01:38:26.350
they were grim environments with dim light.
And these patients never got outside. They

01:38:26.350 --> 01:38:30.810
rarely had a window. And Eus Van Someren,
the scientist in the Netherlands, he was able

01:38:30.810 --> 01:38:37.300
to really produce this strong bout of light
during the day inside the care home and then

01:38:37.300 --> 01:38:42.920
drop out that light in the evening. And he
regularized their light. And he improved the

01:38:42.920 --> 01:38:46.590
circadian rhythm. And he improved cognitive
outcome measures.

01:38:46.590 --> 01:38:47.590
[Rhonda]: Wow.

01:38:47.590 --> 01:38:50.330
[Matt]: Cognition got better in these Alzheimer's
patients.

01:38:50.330 --> 01:38:51.330
[Rhonda]: That's cool.

01:38:51.330 --> 01:38:55.350
[Matt]: Now you can look at that same manipulation,
that same lighting hack, at the beginning

01:38:55.350 --> 01:39:01.490
of life. So in the neonatal intensive care
unit, what we used to have when we go in there,

01:39:01.490 --> 01:39:08.390
you just have constant light on all of the
time, dim light on 24 hours a day, which prevented

01:39:08.390 --> 01:39:14.090
those infants getting the signal of a regulating
24-hour light-dark cycle.

01:39:14.090 --> 01:39:20.310
If you regularized light in the neonatal intensive
care unit, so light during the day, darkness

01:39:20.310 --> 01:39:27.530
at night, in these studies, what you see is
basically almost a 50% to 60% increase in

01:39:27.530 --> 01:39:32.171
oxygen saturation within the blood of these
neonates in the intensive care unit. Weight

01:39:32.171 --> 01:39:36.400
gain increases dramatically. And they end
up exiting the neonatal intensive care unit

01:39:36.400 --> 01:39:40.410
at about five weeks earlier than they would
otherwise.

01:39:40.410 --> 01:39:45.510
Circadian regulation of sleep leads to better
health outcomes. It does so in neonates. It

01:39:45.510 --> 01:39:51.010
does so in the elderly. So I think there is
all manner of sleep possible interventions

01:39:51.010 --> 01:39:55.550
that we can think about across the lifespan
when it comes to modifying disease risk at

01:39:55.550 --> 01:39:56.840
any stage of life.

01:39:56.840 --> 01:40:02.660
[Rhonda]: Yeah. And I think, at least as far
as I've, you know, understood from our conversation

01:40:02.660 --> 01:40:09.010
thus far, some of the main things for prevention
in optimizing your sleep really are preventing

01:40:09.010 --> 01:40:13.940
that emotional stimulation, that anxiety,
and getting particularly a few hours before

01:40:13.940 --> 01:40:18.510
bed, the bright LED exposure early in the
morning, and then not having the bright light

01:40:18.510 --> 01:40:23.980
exposure, you know, about four hours before
bedtime. And then the cold, like, having your

01:40:23.980 --> 01:40:28.220
body temperature go down. So, you know, whether
that's through something like, you know, having

01:40:28.220 --> 01:40:32.890
a hot bath or a hot shower or even possibly
the chili pad, which I'm gonna actually experiment

01:40:32.890 --> 01:40:33.890
with...

01:40:33.890 --> 01:40:34.890
[Matt]: Yeah.

01:40:34.890 --> 01:40:38.100
[Rhonda]: Because now I've been using this
Oura ring that I've been tracking my sleep.

01:40:38.100 --> 01:40:45.820
By the way, do you know how accurate, like...So
it tells me, in my app, the light sleep, the

01:40:45.820 --> 01:40:51.470
REM sleep, and deep sleep. And I know there's
nothing going in my brain measuring any sort

01:40:51.470 --> 01:40:54.490
of brainwaves. So it must be movement, right,
that...

01:40:54.490 --> 01:41:01.190
[Matt]: Yeah, I won't say specifically even
though I know the folks at Oura and I know

01:41:01.190 --> 01:41:08.670
the folks at almost all of the sleep-tracking
companies, most of them right now use a combination

01:41:08.670 --> 01:41:14.250
of your heart rate, which you can pick up
through the pulse waveform either on the wrist

01:41:14.250 --> 01:41:20.760
or on the finger, or if it's a bed sensor,
through the heartbeat, as well as respiration.

01:41:20.760 --> 01:41:25.620
And they'll use a combination of those things
together with movement to try and stage your

01:41:25.620 --> 01:41:26.620
sleep.

01:41:26.620 --> 01:41:30.440
Right now, without naming, you know, I don't
think there's anyone that is necessarily better

01:41:30.440 --> 01:41:35.310
than the other, at least none of them have
published scientific evidence. We sleep scientists

01:41:35.310 --> 01:41:40.440
have actually looked at these devices relative
to gold standard, what we call polysomnography,

01:41:40.440 --> 01:41:44.340
which is essentially like doing a sleep study.
If you were to, here at my sleep center, we've

01:41:44.340 --> 01:41:47.192
got all of this equipment. You look like a
spaghetti monster with electrodes on your

01:41:47.192 --> 01:41:48.192
head.

01:41:48.192 --> 01:41:49.320
[Rhonda]: I don't know who can sleep with
that on.

01:41:49.320 --> 01:41:52.909
[Matt]: Yeah, I know. But we can measure that
sleep with high precision, high fidelity.

01:41:52.909 --> 01:41:56.291
That's the gold standard. And when you compare
these sleep trackers, unfortunately, they're

01:41:56.291 --> 01:42:00.730
not quite accurate. They either overestimate
or underestimate sleep onset latency, how

01:42:00.730 --> 01:42:04.360
long it takes you to fall asleep. They either
overestimate or underestimate the amount of

01:42:04.360 --> 01:42:09.250
time that you've been awake. Sleep duration
may not be bad with some of them, total sleep

01:42:09.250 --> 01:42:15.240
duration, but once you get into the sleep
stages, that's where things become more inaccurate.

01:42:15.240 --> 01:42:20.340
Their ability to separate non-REM from REM,
it is getting better. It could be in the region

01:42:20.340 --> 01:42:27.400
of sort of 60% accuracy, possibly lower. But
right now, we're not there yet. Will we be

01:42:27.400 --> 01:42:31.540
there in about four years' time? I actually
think we will be.

01:42:31.540 --> 01:42:34.780
[Rhonda]: Because that's what...I'm really
interested in the deep. Obviously...

01:42:34.780 --> 01:42:39.420
[Matt]: But also I would say REM sleep, too,
you know, I think REM sleep takes a backseat.

01:42:39.420 --> 01:42:44.640
At sort of, you know, a bit of a neglected
stepsister in the sort of sleep conversation.

01:42:44.640 --> 01:42:48.380
REM sleep, we found all manner of different
functions, one of which is emotional first-aid.

01:42:48.380 --> 01:42:55.910
It's incredible for palliative emotional benefit.
It's not time that heals all wounds, but it's

01:42:55.910 --> 01:42:58.930
time during REM sleep that provides emotional
convalescence.

01:42:58.930 --> 01:43:02.630
[Rhonda]: I guess that would also then be
important to help you sleep better, because

01:43:02.630 --> 01:43:07.870
if you are managing your emotions better,
you probably have less anxiety...

01:43:07.870 --> 01:43:11.810
[Matt]: Correct. Exactly. But also REM is
for the body, too, you know. It seems to regulate

01:43:11.810 --> 01:43:15.610
cardiovascular function. So REM sleep is critical
too.

01:43:15.610 --> 01:43:18.110
[Rhonda]: Oh, really? Is REM what's important
for lowering the blood pressure?

01:43:18.110 --> 01:43:21.950
[Matt]: No. Well, it's during deep sleep that
you get this lowering of blood pressure, and

01:43:21.950 --> 01:43:28.350
we've got some data right now that we're about
to publish that deep sleep provides actually

01:43:28.350 --> 01:43:30.460
a homeostatic recalibration of blood pressure.

01:43:30.460 --> 01:43:34.040
What do I mean by that? If I measure your
blood pressure before sleep and then after

01:43:34.040 --> 01:43:38.600
sleep at a matched circadian time, so we remove
the circadian fluctuation of which there is

01:43:38.600 --> 01:43:43.870
a large one to your systolic blood pressure,
but we match it, and so the only thing that's

01:43:43.870 --> 01:43:47.790
different is the quality of your sleep, what
we've discovered firstly is that the amount

01:43:47.790 --> 01:43:53.860
of deep sleep that you have measured in these
big delta slow waves during deep non-REM sleep,

01:43:53.860 --> 01:43:59.830
that predicts how much of a drop in your systolic
blood pressure you will have in the morning

01:43:59.830 --> 01:44:05.330
relative to the evening as if deep sleep provides
a recalibration of the cardiovascular system.

01:44:05.330 --> 01:44:06.330
[Rhonda]: Wow.

01:44:06.330 --> 01:44:11.290
[Matt]: If you're having higher frequency
brainwaves that are not like the deep sleep,

01:44:11.290 --> 01:44:18.470
that's what we call unrestorative sleep, if
you have a ratio of very little deep brainwave

01:44:18.470 --> 01:44:26.340
activity and a lot of high-frequency wake-like
brain activity, what we call delta-beta ratio

01:44:26.340 --> 01:44:30.780
that predicts very bad cardiovascular outcomes,
that if anything, your systolic blood pressure

01:44:30.780 --> 01:44:33.860
is even worse after sleep than it is the night
before.

01:44:33.860 --> 01:44:38.240
And what we found is that during aging, now
we looked at this and healthy people, then

01:44:38.240 --> 01:44:42.880
we replicated in older adults, and we found
that the older that you get, the less deep

01:44:42.880 --> 01:44:47.690
sleep that you get, the more sort of wake-like
or faster-frequency brainwave activity, which

01:44:47.690 --> 01:44:53.090
isn't good during deep sleep. And that accurately
predicts the cardiovascular dysfunction that

01:44:53.090 --> 01:44:59.550
we see in aging. So we now think we understand
in part why poor sleep is linked into poor

01:44:59.550 --> 01:45:01.280
cardiovascular outcomes.

01:45:01.280 --> 01:45:08.530
One of the benefits of sleep is that it resets
cardiovascular tone and particularly systolic

01:45:08.530 --> 01:45:13.220
tone. It doesn't stop there. There's lots
of other benefits, heart rate drops, etc.

01:45:13.220 --> 01:45:18.070
But REM sleep also seems to have this strange
function where you go through these cycles

01:45:18.070 --> 01:45:21.860
where you get a massive activation of the
cardiovascular system, and then it falls silent,

01:45:21.860 --> 01:45:27.960
and then a massive escalation again. And you
get this really remarkable increase in heart

01:45:27.960 --> 01:45:29.150
rate variability.

01:45:29.150 --> 01:45:34.480
And heart rate variability has been used as
a metric of health outcome, that if you have

01:45:34.480 --> 01:45:39.050
high current rate variability, it's very good.
It predicts lots of health outcomes. That's

01:45:39.050 --> 01:45:43.060
what you get during REM sleep. So we should
be careful not to think of everything being

01:45:43.060 --> 01:45:49.050
all about deep sleep. It's about all stages.
Every stage of sleep that we have, we have

01:45:49.050 --> 01:45:55.510
ascribed a function to. Which makes sense,
you know, during sleep...Sleep is the most

01:45:55.510 --> 01:46:01.950
idiotic of all things in terms of a creation
from Mother Nature. You know, you're not finding

01:46:01.950 --> 01:46:06.400
a mate. You're not reproducing. You're not
eating. You're not caring for your young.

01:46:06.400 --> 01:46:12.490
And worse of all, you're vulnerable to predation.
So on any one of those grounds, sleep should

01:46:12.490 --> 01:46:16.480
have been strongly selected against in the
course of evolution.

01:46:16.480 --> 01:46:22.280
The exact opposite is true. Every species
that we've studied to date sleeps. What that

01:46:22.280 --> 01:46:27.670
means is that sleepers fought its way through
heroically every step along the evolutionary

01:46:27.670 --> 01:46:32.770
pathway, which must mean that if sleep doesn't
serve an absolutely vital function, it is

01:46:32.770 --> 01:46:37.970
the biggest mistake that the evolutionary
process has ever made. And if any one of those

01:46:37.970 --> 01:46:42.180
stages of sleep could be removed, because
it was not important, because I want to, you

01:46:42.180 --> 01:46:47.490
know, emphasize this type of sleep because
that other sleep must not be important, I

01:46:47.490 --> 01:46:52.570
promise you, mother nature would have thought,
I'm gonna excise that stage of sleep out because

01:46:52.570 --> 01:46:55.160
you're just too vulnerable.

01:46:55.160 --> 01:47:01.550
But I think, in your position, of course I
would be concerned about my deep sleep, thinking

01:47:01.550 --> 01:47:07.350
about things like apoe-4 Alzheimer's risk,
too. But I think the bottom line is that no

01:47:07.350 --> 01:47:12.300
matter which way you slice the sleep pie,
you just can't shortchange sleep.

01:47:12.300 --> 01:47:17.740
[Rhonda]: I just want to figure out, it'd
be nice to know what environmental factors

01:47:17.740 --> 01:47:23.651
are affecting, you know, different stages
of sleep, you know. So it's like, you know,

01:47:23.651 --> 01:47:28.190
if I do X, then that's gonna, you know, affect
my deep sleep or it's gonna affect my REM

01:47:28.190 --> 01:47:29.751
or it's gonna make me miss, you know.

01:47:29.751 --> 01:47:34.120
For example, if I were to go to bed, let's
say I usually go to bed at 9 or 9:30, and

01:47:34.120 --> 01:47:40.700
if I were to go to bed instead at 11:30 or
midnight, because I had a social event or

01:47:40.700 --> 01:47:44.820
something, and my circadian rhythm, usually,
well, my circadian rhythm these days is my

01:47:44.820 --> 01:47:51.632
son. Wakes me up at 6 a.m. But let's just
say I could sleep longer if I...let's say

01:47:51.632 --> 01:47:56.430
I wake up at 6 a.m., but then I'm like, "Oh,
I went to bed at midnight instead of 9:30.

01:47:56.430 --> 01:48:02.260
I'll try to go back to sleep." Would that
be okay? Would I be able to, like, recover

01:48:02.260 --> 01:48:07.070
something that I'm missing from the 9:30 to
midnight? Do you see what I'm saying? Like...

01:48:07.070 --> 01:48:08.070
[Matt]: Yeah. So...

01:48:08.070 --> 01:48:10.460
[Rhonda]: Should I go back to sleep? Should
I try to go back or...?

01:48:10.460 --> 01:48:12.761
[Matt]: You should try to go back to sleep.
So you should try to get the sleep that you

01:48:12.761 --> 01:48:13.761
need.

01:48:13.761 --> 01:48:14.761
[Rhonda]: The duration, yeah.

01:48:14.761 --> 01:48:19.010
[Matt]: Yeah, the duration. So there are essentially
four ingredients, and this is probably going

01:48:19.010 --> 01:48:26.550
to be my next book, which is essentially the
four pillars of sleep: depth, duration, continuity,

01:48:26.550 --> 01:48:32.470
regularity. If you shortchange sleep on any
one of those, you get a compromised deficit

01:48:32.470 --> 01:48:38.300
in brain and body. So depth is what we were
speaking about. It really should be depth/quality

01:48:38.300 --> 01:48:44.010
of sleep. You need both the depth of those
deep sleep brainwaves but you also need all

01:48:44.010 --> 01:48:47.591
of these different brainwave oscillations,
these things called sleep spindles, and slow

01:48:47.591 --> 01:48:51.830
waves, and the coordination between those
two. It's all about the electrical quality

01:48:51.830 --> 01:48:52.830
of your sleep.

01:48:52.830 --> 01:48:56.920
So you can have the duration of sleep, you
can have eight hours of sleep, but if it's

01:48:56.920 --> 01:49:03.940
not of the right electrical quality or depth,
you get deficits. But you can get lots of

01:49:03.940 --> 01:49:08.310
high quality sleep, but if you're only getting
four hours of it, it's not going to be enough.

01:49:08.310 --> 01:49:11.660
So it's duration. Depth, duration.

01:49:11.660 --> 01:49:15.910
Then it's also about continuity. This has
been probably, in the past five years, one

01:49:15.910 --> 01:49:21.610
of the explosions in the sleep field. If you
were to get eight hours of sleep but across

01:49:21.610 --> 01:49:27.400
a nine-hour period because you are awake for,
you know, 5 minutes here, 10 minutes here,

01:49:27.400 --> 01:49:32.430
30 minutes here, 15 minutes here, that's very
fragmented sleep, which, by the way, alcohol

01:49:32.430 --> 01:49:38.690
is another thing that will fragment your sleep
very much like that. So the continuity of

01:49:38.690 --> 01:49:43.920
your sleep is poor. It's not continuous. It's
fragmented.

01:49:43.920 --> 01:49:49.530
And even if you get eight hours of sleep in
a nine-hour period but it's fragmented versus

01:49:49.530 --> 01:49:55.680
you get eight hours of sleep all in a nice
one bout within eight hours, so in both of

01:49:55.680 --> 01:50:00.350
those scenarios, it's the same duration of
sleep, maybe it's even the same electrical

01:50:00.350 --> 01:50:05.970
quality of sleep, but if it's fragmented and
littered and punctured with many awakenings,

01:50:05.970 --> 01:50:09.510
the continuity of sleep is poor. And that's
not good either.

01:50:09.510 --> 01:50:14.760
And then, finally, the part is regularity.
This means going to bed and waking up at the

01:50:14.760 --> 01:50:19.150
same time no matter whether it's the weekend
or the weekday. Go to bed at the same time,

01:50:19.150 --> 01:50:25.380
wake up at the same time. Those are the four
key pillars that we know of for sleep. And

01:50:25.380 --> 01:50:32.230
you can hold any three constant and manipulate
one of them and you get a deficit.

01:50:32.230 --> 01:50:37.990
Now we can't quite weigh the complete, you
know, is it, you know, this one is worth,

01:50:37.990 --> 01:50:43.950
you know, 40%. This one is worth sort of 20%.
We can't yet do that. But it's very clear

01:50:43.950 --> 01:50:47.040
that those are the four pillars of good sleep.

01:50:47.040 --> 01:50:55.650
So I mentioned that just coming back to the
quality of sleep, when you position of the

01:50:55.650 --> 01:51:01.420
quantity of sleep on the clock face, on the
24-hour clock face, at an inappropriate time

01:51:01.420 --> 01:51:06.780
according to your natural innate preference,
and I say that specifically rather than a

01:51:06.780 --> 01:51:12.300
particular time, you will not get the same
quality of your sleep. So an extreme version

01:51:12.300 --> 01:51:18.490
of this is a night shift worker, where they
may get eight hours of sleep in bed but they

01:51:18.490 --> 01:51:23.780
are sleeping during the day, not during the
night. So it's a complete reversal. The quality

01:51:23.780 --> 01:51:28.050
of their sleep is not good. They don't get
the same amount of deep sleep nor do they

01:51:28.050 --> 01:51:30.240
get the same amount of REM sleep.

01:51:30.240 --> 01:51:35.860
But let's kind of walk that back a little
bit to your scenario, which is much more subtle.

01:51:35.860 --> 01:51:41.120
Let's say that my chronotype, and your chronotype
simply determines whether you're a morning

01:51:41.120 --> 01:51:47.050
person, an evening person, or somewhere in
the middle, about 30% of the population is

01:51:47.050 --> 01:51:54.250
an extreme morning type or a morning type,
about sort of 40% percent is sort of neither

01:51:54.250 --> 01:52:00.790
strongly morning or evening, and about the
remaining 30% is an evening type, we call

01:52:00.790 --> 01:52:04.180
them owls and larks.

01:52:04.180 --> 01:52:08.590
So if you're a morning type, you like to go
to bed, let's say, like, 9 p.m. And wake up

01:52:08.590 --> 01:52:13.670
at 5 or 6. If you're an evening type, you
may want to go to bed at 1 a.m. And wake up

01:52:13.670 --> 01:52:20.860
at 9 a.m. The next morning. So when I'm saying
the optimal position of sleep, I'm saying

01:52:20.860 --> 01:52:25.091
with the optimal for your chronotype, this
is your chronotype...And by the way, it's

01:52:25.091 --> 01:52:30.010
genetic. You don't get to decide whether you're
a morning type or an evening type. It's hardwired

01:52:30.010 --> 01:52:34.300
into your genes. We know the genes. It's not
your fault. If you're an evening type and

01:52:34.300 --> 01:52:40.780
you're listening to this, and society, which
is strongly architected against your chronotype,

01:52:40.780 --> 01:52:46.420
we reward and we favor the morning types,
it is not your fault. It's not a choice. And

01:52:46.420 --> 01:52:49.610
there's not too much you can do about it.
You can push and pull the system by about

01:52:49.610 --> 01:52:53.720
30 minutes, 45 minutes, but not much more.

01:52:53.720 --> 01:52:59.010
So coming back to it, when we position that
sleep on that eight-hour period, whatever

01:52:59.010 --> 01:53:03.860
is optimal for you, you will get a nice distribution.
You'll get all of the deep sleep that you

01:53:03.860 --> 01:53:08.420
want and all of the REM sleep that you want.
And earlier in the conversation, I said that

01:53:08.420 --> 01:53:11.650
we go through these 90-minute cycles, we,
human beings, it's different for different

01:53:11.650 --> 01:53:16.900
animals, you always go into deep non-REM sleep
first and then you always have REM sleep second.

01:53:16.900 --> 01:53:20.780
And that repeats every 90 minutes throughout
the night.

01:53:20.780 --> 01:53:26.970
What changes, however, is the ratio of non-REM
to REM within those 90-minute cycles as you

01:53:26.970 --> 01:53:32.470
move across the night such that in the first
half of the night, the majority of those 90-minute

01:53:32.470 --> 01:53:37.720
cycles are comprised of lots of deep non-REM
sleep and very little REM sleep. In the second

01:53:37.720 --> 01:53:42.630
half of the night, that balance shifts, and
now you get much more REM sleep in the late

01:53:42.630 --> 01:53:45.990
morning hours and very little deep sleep.

01:53:45.990 --> 01:53:50.260
The reason I'm saying this is because let's
take someone who goes to bed at a substandard

01:53:50.260 --> 01:53:53.300
amount of time. Let's say that they go to
bed at midnight, and they're going to wake

01:53:53.300 --> 01:53:58.470
up at 8. But instead they have to wake up,
because they've got an early morning meeting,

01:53:58.470 --> 01:54:02.660
so they go to bed at midnight and they wake
up at 6. And my question is how much sleep

01:54:02.660 --> 01:54:07.410
have they lost? And your response is, well,
they've lost two hours out of the eight hours,

01:54:07.410 --> 01:54:12.740
which means they've lost 25% of their sleep.
And your answer would be right in a way, but

01:54:12.740 --> 01:54:17.820
it would be wrong as well, which is that they've
lost 25% of their total sleep but they may

01:54:17.820 --> 01:54:24.350
have lost almost 80% of their REM sleep because
that's the REM rich phase of the night.

01:54:24.350 --> 01:54:30.320
And it also works the other way around, too,
that if you go to bed too late, you will...So

01:54:30.320 --> 01:54:34.750
what happens is, because of the circadian
rhythm, the brain has a different appetite

01:54:34.750 --> 01:54:41.420
for different stages of sleep on the 24-hour
clock face. In the late evening and the early

01:54:41.420 --> 01:54:49.170
morning hours, the brain has a dietary preference
for deep sleep. And it doesn't very much have

01:54:49.170 --> 01:54:53.360
an appetite taste for REM sleep. Through to
the second half of the night, that's when

01:54:53.360 --> 01:54:55.620
it gets its appetite for REM sleep.

01:54:55.620 --> 01:55:02.550
So if you start sleeping at 4:00 in the morning
and you wake up it in the middle of the day,

01:55:02.550 --> 01:55:07.440
your brain has lost its appetite for deep
sleep. And so it won't get much. Now you will

01:55:07.440 --> 01:55:12.691
probably get much more REM sleep as a consequence.
So you've got to be really careful. That why...

01:55:12.691 --> 01:55:15.940
[Rhonda]: So it's almost like your chronotype
may even dictate in a way how much deep sleep

01:55:15.940 --> 01:55:16.940
you may get.

01:55:16.940 --> 01:55:21.970
[Matt]: The chronotype will...If you sleep
naturally and you get the amount of sleep

01:55:21.970 --> 01:55:25.900
that you want, your chronotype will probably
mean that...your circadian rhythm is actually

01:55:25.900 --> 01:55:30.970
shifted as your chronotype, too. So you will
still get, as an owl, if you get your eight

01:55:30.970 --> 01:55:36.820
hours when you want it, you will probably
get a similar sleep architecture as a lark,

01:55:36.820 --> 01:55:42.330
who has gone to bed five or six hours earlier,
because your circadian rhythms are five to

01:55:42.330 --> 01:55:43.800
six hours different.

01:55:43.800 --> 01:55:50.220
But you're right in the sense that owls typically
try to go to bed early. But because they are

01:55:50.220 --> 01:55:54.720
designed not to fall asleep at that time,
they're just gonna lie in bed. Many owls think

01:55:54.720 --> 01:55:58.930
that they have insomnia. They don't. They're
just not going to bed at the right time. Because

01:55:58.930 --> 01:56:03.490
they get into bed, and it's like a teenager,
whose rhythm is also shifted late, you tell

01:56:03.490 --> 01:56:07.080
them to go to bed because you've got to wake
up for early school start times, but there's

01:56:07.080 --> 01:56:10.440
nothing they can do because their circadian
rhythm has shifted forward in time. And it's

01:56:10.440 --> 01:56:11.990
the same for owls.

01:56:11.990 --> 01:56:17.340
So what will happen is that they will probably
stay awake for a while, then they'll get into

01:56:17.340 --> 01:56:21.400
deep sleep. But then they have to wake up
at an earlier time, and they will lose a lot

01:56:21.400 --> 01:56:26.650
of REM sleep. REM sleep, for emotional well-being,
what the owls typically experience: depression,

01:56:26.650 --> 01:56:31.420
low mood, anxiety. So I think we're really
starting to put the pieces together on that

01:56:31.420 --> 01:56:32.420
component.

01:56:32.420 --> 01:56:39.550
[Rhonda]: And so for someone like me, I'm
somewhere in the middle, like, when I don't...pre-baby.

01:56:39.550 --> 01:56:45.150
Now I'm I guess you would call a lark because
I'm going to bed at, like, 9. My optimal time,

01:56:45.150 --> 01:56:49.080
if I can go to bed when my son does, and it's
like, you know, if I go to bed, like, at 8,

01:56:49.080 --> 01:56:53.720
then I get the longer duration. That way,
if I'm a little more fragmented, then I, like,

01:56:53.720 --> 01:56:57.990
at least can make up for it somewhat. But
I'm up at 6 a.m. Now if it were up to me,

01:56:57.990 --> 01:57:00.350
I'd like to sleep...I usually would wake up,
like, 8 a.m.

01:57:00.350 --> 01:57:01.350
[Matt]: Yes, 8 a.m.

01:57:01.350 --> 01:57:02.350
[Rhonda]: Like, that's my natural time.

01:57:02.350 --> 01:57:06.440
[Matt]: And the reason that you can probably
go to sleep sort of, you know, 9 p.m. Or even

01:57:06.440 --> 01:57:11.450
8 p.m. Now is because you're chronically sleep-deprived.
And as a consequence, you've built up such

01:57:11.450 --> 01:57:16.870
as sleep debt that, you know, there is a lingering
what we call sleep pressure in your system.

01:57:16.870 --> 01:57:22.780
But, yeah, I think fighting your chronotype,
we found, it comes with deleterious health

01:57:22.780 --> 01:57:27.691
consequences. Increased risk for poor cardio
metabolic outcomes. Things like, you know,

01:57:27.691 --> 01:57:33.960
C-reactive protein is higher. If you look
at, you know, A1C in terms of sort of a raw

01:57:33.960 --> 01:57:40.090
shot review of blood glucose, your blood sugar,
not good. If you look at your propensity for

01:57:40.090 --> 01:57:47.660
being obese or being overweight, also not
great if you're an owl and you're not sleeping

01:57:47.660 --> 01:57:48.660
according to your schedule.

01:57:48.660 --> 01:57:49.660
[Rhonda]: Telomeres are shorter.

01:57:49.660 --> 01:57:50.780
[Matt]: Telomeres are shorter as well.

01:57:50.780 --> 01:57:53.980
[Rhonda]: So let's talk about your, because
a lot of interesting researchers come out

01:57:53.980 --> 01:58:01.670
of your lab on the blood glucose regulation
front and, well, I guess more on the eating

01:58:01.670 --> 01:58:02.670
preferences...

01:58:02.670 --> 01:58:03.670
[Matt]: And appetite and eating.

01:58:03.670 --> 01:58:04.670
[Rhonda]: ...and appetite. Yeah.

01:58:04.670 --> 01:58:09.770
[Matt]: I mean, the way I see it, it's all
part of the energy intake expenditure system.

01:58:09.770 --> 01:58:14.470
And sleep, you know, if you think about like
a weighing scale between sort of energy expenditure

01:58:14.470 --> 01:58:20.840
and energy consumption, sleep, if you're not
getting it, just annihilates that balance.

01:58:20.840 --> 01:58:23.020
And we can speak about any one of those things.

01:58:23.020 --> 01:58:31.630
But, you know, I think the blood glucose story
and sleep is very very well-worked out now.

01:58:31.630 --> 01:58:36.460
It started with epidemiological studies, where
we started to see that people who were sleeping

01:58:36.460 --> 01:58:42.130
less than seven hours were at significantly
higher likelihood of either being diabetic

01:58:42.130 --> 01:58:48.000
or going on to develop diabetes. Many of them
were already, you know, what we call a pre-diabetic

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:55.200
state, or they had what we now call sort of
metabolic disorder.

01:58:55.200 --> 01:58:59.890
And then the question became, well, is that
associational or is it causal? So the next

01:58:59.890 --> 01:59:04.530
studies that happened in this was work back
in...starts in the 1990s by Evan Carter at

01:59:04.530 --> 01:59:08.820
the University of Chicago. Wonderful studies.
It took a group of healthy people, started

01:59:08.820 --> 01:59:12.840
to limit them to different doses of sleep
for a week, you know, five hours of sleep,

01:59:12.840 --> 01:59:16.660
six hours of sleep, four hours of sleep, and
what she showed was that, essentially, after

01:59:16.660 --> 01:59:22.030
one week of short sleep, your blood sugar
levels are disrupted so significantly that

01:59:22.030 --> 01:59:27.300
your doctor would classify you at that point
as being pre-diabetic after one week of short

01:59:27.300 --> 01:59:28.780
sleep.

01:59:28.780 --> 01:59:34.830
And the way that they do this is what's called
a glucose tolerance test, where you are fasted,

01:59:34.830 --> 01:59:39.840
and then you are given this sickly-sweet drink
of glucose, and then they are measuring from

01:59:39.840 --> 01:59:48.070
your blood in the next three or four hours
how quickly is your body able to dispose of

01:59:48.070 --> 01:59:49.630
that blood glucose.

01:59:49.630 --> 01:59:54.470
So what happens when you drink or when you
eat a meal is that your blood sugar spikes.

01:59:54.470 --> 01:59:59.550
And you don't want that spike to stick around
very long. If your body is healthy, it deals

01:59:59.550 --> 02:00:04.670
with that raised level of blood glucose very
quickly, and it brings it back down very quickly.

02:00:04.670 --> 02:00:10.300
That's a healthy profile. That's what we call
good glucose management. So how good is your

02:00:10.300 --> 02:00:15.530
body at disposing essentially of that glucose?
And the way it disposes it is that cells in

02:00:15.530 --> 02:00:21.680
the body, including muscle cells, will suck
up that glucose. And it's called your disposal

02:00:21.680 --> 02:00:26.280
index, or your disposition index, it turns
out.

02:00:26.280 --> 02:00:32.580
So what she found, Evan Carter, with her studies,
was that, firstly, the way that your body

02:00:32.580 --> 02:00:38.480
knows how to absorb glucose and suck in that
glucose is that there is another chemical

02:00:38.480 --> 02:00:44.500
called insulin, which is released by the pancreas,
beta cells of the pancreas, and that insulin

02:00:44.500 --> 02:00:49.550
will instruct the cells of the body to open
up special glucose channels to absorb the

02:00:49.550 --> 02:00:53.600
glucose and your blood sugar drops, which
is good and healthy.

02:00:53.600 --> 02:00:58.330
Firstly, what she found was that when you
are not getting sufficient sleep, the beta

02:00:58.330 --> 02:01:06.810
cells in your pancreas stop being sensitive
to the signal of high glucose. So the beta

02:01:06.810 --> 02:01:11.200
cells, which normally are listening for this
spike in glucose, and as soon as they sort

02:01:11.200 --> 02:01:14.240
of, you know, hear...no, they're not hearing
it. They're sensing it. But as soon as they

02:01:14.240 --> 02:01:20.540
sense the spike in glucose, they release insulin.
And that insulin will drop your blood glucose.

02:01:20.540 --> 02:01:28.860
But those cells had become insensitive to
glucose, what we call sort of glucose insensitivity.

02:01:28.860 --> 02:01:35.490
And so the beta cells of the pancreas stopped
releasing as much insulin. It didn't release

02:01:35.490 --> 02:01:42.130
enough insulin to drop blood glucose, so blood
glucose remained high. If that wasn't bad

02:01:42.130 --> 02:01:47.130
enough, we've since gone on to demonstrate,
and you can do this with really clever studies,

02:01:47.130 --> 02:01:56.150
taking tissue biopsies, the cells of the body
including muscle cells and fat cells, their

02:01:56.150 --> 02:01:59.720
receptors stopped being as sensitive to insulin.

02:01:59.720 --> 02:02:04.860
So, firstly, you're releasing less insulin
when you're sleep-deprived. But what little

02:02:04.860 --> 02:02:11.070
insulin you do release is not instructing
those cells to open up the channels to take

02:02:11.070 --> 02:02:17.090
away the monsoon of the glucose that's flowing
in the channels of the body. So on both sides

02:02:17.090 --> 02:02:23.670
of the glucose regulation, on the release
of insulin, to instruct cells to absorb glucose,

02:02:23.670 --> 02:02:31.070
and on those cells themselves to be sort of
instructed by insulin, those cells became

02:02:31.070 --> 02:02:37.740
less sensitive to the insulin signal. And
so, as a consequence, your overall ability

02:02:37.740 --> 02:02:43.990
to deal with glucose became far more degraded,
and blood glucose remained higher, which sets

02:02:43.990 --> 02:02:46.280
you on a profile of looking pre-diabetic.

02:02:46.280 --> 02:02:49.100
[Rhonda]: Couple that with the standard American
diet, and, you know...

02:02:49.100 --> 02:02:50.560
[Matt]: And you're off to the races in terms
with...

02:02:50.560 --> 02:02:54.520
[Rhonda]: Yeah, and eating late at night.
So, actually, are you familiar with the studies,

02:02:54.520 --> 02:03:00.520
I know Dr. Satchin Panda actually is the one
who told me about this, melatonin is actually

02:03:00.520 --> 02:03:04.850
what is responsible for shutting down the
pancreatic beta cells from producing insulin.

02:03:04.850 --> 02:03:09.660
So I wonder how much of the sleep deprivation
the melatonin system is involved in that.

02:03:09.660 --> 02:03:13.220
[Matt]: Yeah. So in those studies, what was
good is that they held constant circadian

02:03:13.220 --> 02:03:17.240
rhythms, they held constant ambient light,
and they even held constant physical activity.

02:03:17.240 --> 02:03:23.910
The control group was sort of they were in
bed for eight hours, but the people who are

02:03:23.910 --> 02:03:28.360
sleep deprived, limited to four or five hours,
during the eight-hour window where the other

02:03:28.360 --> 02:03:33.290
people were actually sleeping, they had to
lie recumbent in bed with no physical movement.

02:03:33.290 --> 02:03:34.290
[Rhonda]: Oh, man.

02:03:34.290 --> 02:03:36.720
[Matt]: So you controlled, but it was a great
study because you control for physical activity

02:03:36.720 --> 02:03:43.330
as well. So we now really understand the link
between a lack of sleep and poor glucose management,

02:03:43.330 --> 02:03:48.120
and very very well indeed. And we also know
the stage of sleep that's important. It's,

02:03:48.120 --> 02:03:51.790
again, deep slow-wave sleep. The study that
I described before, where you're playing those

02:03:51.790 --> 02:03:58.700
annoying tones just below the level of awakening
so I can remove your deep quality of sleep,

02:03:58.700 --> 02:04:03.390
you can do that same thing again, and you
essentially produce that same diabetic-like

02:04:03.390 --> 02:04:08.050
consequence just by removing or excising deep
slow-wave sleep.

02:04:08.050 --> 02:04:12.270
[Rhonda]: So you're doing that, and then on
top of that, some of your work has shown that

02:04:12.270 --> 02:04:18.170
you're now also gonna have a preference to
eat the very food that raises your blood sugar,

02:04:18.170 --> 02:04:19.170
right?

02:04:19.170 --> 02:04:20.170
[Matt]: Yup, yup.

02:04:20.170 --> 02:04:21.170
[Rhonda]: And it's something I've definitely
experienced...

02:04:21.170 --> 02:04:22.170
[Matt]: High glycemic food...

02:04:22.170 --> 02:04:23.170
[Rhonda]: Yeah, yeah.

02:04:23.170 --> 02:04:27.740
[Matt]: So this is a whole...So it all fits
in, I think, to this energy balance. So, you

02:04:27.740 --> 02:04:34.010
know, firstly, what we know is that your regulation
of blood sugar, of blood glucose is profoundly

02:04:34.010 --> 02:04:41.910
impaired by a lack of sleep. But what about
your calorie intake? What about your obesogenic

02:04:41.910 --> 02:04:47.120
profile, setting aside your glycemic profile?

02:04:47.120 --> 02:04:53.140
So what we've discovered is that when you're
not getting enough sleep, two appetite-regulating

02:04:53.140 --> 02:04:58.710
hormones go in opposite directions. These
two hormones are called leptin and ghrelin.

02:04:58.710 --> 02:05:04.310
And I often, you know, think of them as, you
know, they sound like hobbits to me, at least,

02:05:04.310 --> 02:05:05.310
you know.

02:05:05.310 --> 02:05:06.310
[Rhonda]: That's hilarious.

02:05:06.310 --> 02:05:10.001
[Matt]: Leptin and ghrelin that, you know,
J. R. Tolkien would have written about them.

02:05:10.001 --> 02:05:15.490
But they're not. They're real hormones. Leptin
is a hormone that signals satiety. What I

02:05:15.490 --> 02:05:20.890
mean by that is, when you have high amounts
of leptin, it tells your brain you're full.

02:05:20.890 --> 02:05:26.450
You're satisfied with your food. You don't
want to eat anymore. Ghrelin is the other

02:05:26.450 --> 02:05:33.520
hunger hormone. When ghrelin is increased,
you feel unsatisfied by your food. You feel

02:05:33.520 --> 02:05:36.740
hungry. And you want to eat more.

02:05:36.740 --> 02:05:42.340
So after you eat a meal, normally, what happens
is that levels of leptin increase and levels

02:05:42.340 --> 02:05:47.170
of ghrelin, the hunger hormone, you can think
about ghrelin as like a grumbling tummy, ghrelin

02:05:47.170 --> 02:05:52.260
goes down. And this means that you stop eating,
you don't want to eat anymore, and you're

02:05:52.260 --> 02:05:57.801
full for a duration of time period. When you
are sleep-deprived, levels of leptin, which

02:05:57.801 --> 02:06:02.530
normally signal to your brain you're full
and you're satisfied with food, that hormone

02:06:02.530 --> 02:06:09.540
is impaired by a lack of sleep. So you lose
the fullness satiety signal in your brain.

02:06:09.540 --> 02:06:15.921
If that wasn't bad enough, the hunger hormone,
ghrelin, actually increases. So it's a double

02:06:15.921 --> 02:06:23.120
whammy effect here. What does that lead to?
It leads to a strong obesogenic profile of

02:06:23.120 --> 02:06:29.250
energy consumption, of food consumption. So
what we, and Evan Carter, in fact, has done

02:06:29.250 --> 02:06:33.700
all of these pioneering studies, and we've
done some of them now, too, typically, you

02:06:33.700 --> 02:06:39.500
tend to over eat during main meals. So you
will typically eat somewhere between about

02:06:39.500 --> 02:06:45.000
200 to 300 extra calories. If we give you
a meal, and we measure all of the food on

02:06:45.000 --> 02:06:49.070
your plate, and we ask how much did you eat
at that one sitting, you tend to overeat by

02:06:49.070 --> 02:06:53.490
about 200 or 300 calories per main meal sitting.

02:06:53.490 --> 02:06:54.830
[Rhonda]: Wow.

02:06:54.830 --> 02:06:57.550
[Matt]: Now you could say...Well, actually...

02:06:57.550 --> 02:06:59.990
[Rhonda]: That's after a full night of sleep?

02:06:59.990 --> 02:07:04.910
[Matt]: Well, that's when you've been limited
to maybe four hours of sleep for a week. Now

02:07:04.910 --> 02:07:09.430
someone, and the reviewers of these papers,
you know, in the early days, said, "Well,

02:07:09.430 --> 02:07:15.480
that's because when you're awake longer, being
awake is more metabolically demanding, and

02:07:15.480 --> 02:07:20.220
you're probably moving around more." Not true.
It turns out sleep, firstly, is a remarkably

02:07:20.220 --> 02:07:25.430
metabolically active state. You're very active
metabolically when you're asleep. In fact,

02:07:25.430 --> 02:07:30.830
the difference between being asleep versus
being awake is only about, for a whole night

02:07:30.830 --> 02:07:32.830
of sleep, the difference of about 140 calories.

02:07:32.830 --> 02:07:33.830
[Rhonda]: Wow.

02:07:33.830 --> 02:07:40.070
[Matt]: Just like a small cookie, essentially.
So, yes, when you're awake longer, you do

02:07:40.070 --> 02:07:47.860
burn more calories. But the amount of calories
that you increase in your intake far exceeds

02:07:47.860 --> 02:07:53.540
anything that you expend by way of being awake
a little bit longer. If that wasn't bad enough,

02:07:53.540 --> 02:07:58.630
though, it's not the main meal where the trouble
lies with sleep. That's some of the problem.

02:07:58.630 --> 02:08:04.340
The other studies that are even more sort
of devilish are where you give these sleep-deprived

02:08:04.340 --> 02:08:12.310
subjects the same meal but then you give them
a snack bar. And it's an ad-lib food buffet,

02:08:12.310 --> 02:08:17.970
essentially. And you can eat as much as you
want. And they allow you to eat in a room

02:08:17.970 --> 02:08:22.830
by yourself, so there's no social pressure,
so you don't restrict your eating or...it's

02:08:22.830 --> 02:08:23.900
true eating.

02:08:23.900 --> 02:08:30.370
And of course, we measure everything that
you eat. And it's snacking that is the dead

02:08:30.370 --> 02:08:36.651
giveaway here. You end up eating 300 to 400
additional calories by way of snacks. This

02:08:36.651 --> 02:08:43.120
is after they've eaten a 2,000-calorie meal
in one sitting. They will then go away, and

02:08:43.120 --> 02:08:46.610
they will eat an additional 400 calories at
the snack bar.

02:08:46.610 --> 02:08:47.860
[Rhonda]: Wow.

02:08:47.860 --> 02:08:53.590
[Matt]: So, as a consequence, what you're
doing is you're increasing the total caloric

02:08:53.590 --> 02:08:59.980
intake, which sets you on a path towards being
overweight and obese. Then the discovery came

02:08:59.980 --> 02:09:05.130
that it's not just what you eat...sorry, it's
not just how much you eat but it's what you

02:09:05.130 --> 02:09:11.430
eat. And what Evan Carter discovered in her
early studies was that if you give one of

02:09:11.430 --> 02:09:18.450
these sort of food buffets...and you can eat
anything. It goes from, you know, sugary treats

02:09:18.450 --> 02:09:26.190
to salty treats like pretzels or potato chips
to heavy-hitting starchy carbohydrates, breads,

02:09:26.190 --> 02:09:33.200
pasta, pizza all the way to salad, what you
find is that you eat more of all of the food

02:09:33.200 --> 02:09:40.310
groups. But you eat mostly in terms of an
increase the starchy, heavy-hitting carbohydrates

02:09:40.310 --> 02:09:42.290
as well as the sugary foods.

02:09:42.290 --> 02:09:46.920
And if we know anything from the recent movement
in food, particularly from people like Gary

02:09:46.920 --> 02:09:51.520
Taubes, who has written wonderfully about
this type of stuff, that's the food that sets

02:09:51.520 --> 02:09:59.541
you on a path, again, down an obesogenic and
also a poor glycemic control profile. If you

02:09:59.541 --> 02:10:05.850
look at all of the cardio metabolic markers
of health when you're eating excessive carbohydrate-heavy

02:10:05.850 --> 02:10:14.380
rich or and particularly simplified sugars,
they're bad for your health profile in general.

02:10:14.380 --> 02:10:17.660
It's exactly the foods that you eat when you
are underslept.

02:10:17.660 --> 02:10:21.950
[Rhonda]: Is there a feedback loop on those
foods affecting your sleep?

02:10:21.950 --> 02:10:22.950
[Matt]: There is.

02:10:22.950 --> 02:10:23.950
[Rhonda]: There is.

02:10:23.950 --> 02:10:28.530
[Matt]: So I would say this is probably, apart
from maybe the gut microbiome of which there

02:10:28.530 --> 02:10:33.850
is now some evidence, and we're starting to
look at this, too, at the sleep center, it's

02:10:33.850 --> 02:10:38.470
probably the least well understood. But the
bottom line is that if you're eating a diet

02:10:38.470 --> 02:10:45.240
that's high in carbohydrate, especially high
in processed simple sugars and low in fiber,

02:10:45.240 --> 02:10:50.780
you tend to have worse sleep, you take longer
time to fall asleep, the amount of deep sleep

02:10:50.780 --> 02:10:56.420
that you get is less, and you have more fragmented
awakenings throughout the night.

02:10:56.420 --> 02:11:01.110
Now I don't think there's enough evidence
right now for me to hang my hat on any dietary

02:11:01.110 --> 02:11:06.000
prescription for sleep. In five years' time,
I think we'll have a very different conversation.

02:11:06.000 --> 02:11:10.320
I think, you know, absence of evidence is
not evidence of absence. I think we'll get

02:11:10.320 --> 02:11:13.580
there. And I think food is going to be a big
part of that equation. I think we have gut

02:11:13.580 --> 02:11:18.450
microbiome, too. I think that's what we've
seen when you, in a few of the studies where

02:11:18.450 --> 02:11:22.460
you limit people, you sleep deprive them or
you put them on a jet lag routine, you see

02:11:22.460 --> 02:11:30.310
the balance between the sort of bacteriodetes
sort of class of the microbiome versus the

02:11:30.310 --> 02:11:34.960
firmicutes. That ratio goes in a balance that
you don't want.

02:11:34.960 --> 02:11:39.950
So, typically, in sort of obese people or
people with diabetes, you get a higher ratio

02:11:39.950 --> 02:11:47.940
of the firmicutes relative to the bacteriodetes.
When you modulate sleep and you shortchange

02:11:47.940 --> 02:11:54.260
sleep or you put sleep on a jet like profile,
that's exactly the same gut microbiome sort

02:11:54.260 --> 02:11:58.880
of dysregulation profile that you see. So
I think it's gonna be a great...And I think

02:11:58.880 --> 02:11:59.880
part of...

02:11:59.880 --> 02:12:01.560
[Rhonda]: Because they're on their own circadian
rhythm as well, the...

02:12:01.560 --> 02:12:02.600
[Matt]: They are. Yeah.

02:12:02.600 --> 02:12:05.110
[Rhonda]: So is that why? Because their ratio
is changing and then...?

02:12:05.110 --> 02:12:11.460
[Matt]: I think it's possible that it could
be a circadian rhythm. I think it's also possible

02:12:11.460 --> 02:12:15.360
that it could be down to what we described
before, which is the fight-or-flight branch

02:12:15.360 --> 02:12:21.180
of the nervous system, that when you are under
slept, it's, like, revving a car but in neutral.

02:12:21.180 --> 02:12:25.090
It's desperately bad for the engine. That's
what happens when you're sleep-deprived. You

02:12:25.090 --> 02:12:28.890
get this ramping up of your fight-or-flight
system, and it just stays there with chronic

02:12:28.890 --> 02:12:33.900
sleep deprivation for as long as you're chronically
sleep-deprived. And one out of every two adults

02:12:33.900 --> 02:12:36.510
in first world nations is chronically sleep-deprived.

02:12:36.510 --> 02:12:42.810
I think it leads to a release of stress chemistry,
particularly cortisol. Cortisol is known in

02:12:42.810 --> 02:12:48.500
the gut microbiome to produce this imbalance.
What's the pathway? I think it's probably

02:12:48.500 --> 02:12:53.020
a bunch of nerve fibers from the brain into
the body called the vagus nerve. And we're

02:12:53.020 --> 02:12:58.170
starting to do a lot of work on this now.
I think the vagus nerve we know has a direct

02:12:58.170 --> 02:13:03.160
mainline pathway or provides a mainline pathway
from your brain to your gut. And that's why

02:13:03.160 --> 02:13:07.240
there is a very powerful brain-gut relationship.

02:13:07.240 --> 02:13:12.150
I think that's one of the mechanisms by which
the gut is affected by sleep. Which gets me

02:13:12.150 --> 02:13:23.310
excited, because if that's true, flip the
equation, could the gut microbiome be a path

02:13:23.310 --> 02:13:28.481
through which we can reverse-engineer a signal
for better sleep in the brain? I think that

02:13:28.481 --> 02:13:32.520
now becomes a parsimonious hypothesis, and
it's one that I'd like to test as well.

02:13:32.520 --> 02:13:38.010
[Rhonda]: There was a really interesting study
looking at the effects of a particular strain.

02:13:38.010 --> 02:13:42.630
I think it was the rhamnosus strain that...they
produce GABA in the gut.

02:13:42.630 --> 02:13:43.630
[Matt]: Yes.

02:13:43.630 --> 02:13:49.450
[Rhonda]: But GABA doesn't cross the blood-brain
barrier as far as...I think most evidence

02:13:49.450 --> 02:13:50.680
suggests it does not.

02:13:50.680 --> 02:13:54.240
[Matt]: No. So the brain has GABA, but it's
not coming from the...

02:13:54.240 --> 02:13:55.370
[Rhonda]: Right, right.

02:13:55.370 --> 02:13:56.370
[Matt]: Yeah.

02:13:56.370 --> 02:14:00.760
[Rhonda]: But there was some studies that
were speculating that there's, through the

02:14:00.760 --> 02:14:05.880
vagal nerve, because some of the efferent
neurons in the gut were stimulating it, and

02:14:05.880 --> 02:14:10.010
they were more, like, relaxed or something.
They were producing GABA in the brain through

02:14:10.010 --> 02:14:13.190
the vagal nerve. And GABA affects sleep, right?

02:14:13.190 --> 02:14:14.190
[Matt]: Yeah.

02:14:14.190 --> 02:14:15.800
[Rhonda]: So it sounds like there could definitely
be some sort of interesting...

02:14:15.800 --> 02:14:20.530
[Matt]: You know, that's one of...I think
the things in anxiety that we see is that

02:14:20.530 --> 02:14:25.280
it's a failure of the brain to dampen down
and basically invoke inhibition throughout

02:14:25.280 --> 02:14:27.730
the brain to quiet down these regions.

02:14:27.730 --> 02:14:32.370
[Rhonda]: That particular strain of probiotics
was shown to help with anxiety. Small trials,

02:14:32.370 --> 02:14:38.290
clinical trials in humans. Of course, the
initial studies were preclinical in animals,

02:14:38.290 --> 02:14:40.710
but it has been shown to actually help improve...

02:14:40.710 --> 02:14:41.710
[Matt]: It does?

02:14:41.710 --> 02:14:42.710
[Rhonda]: Yeah. [inaudible 02:14:04]...

02:14:42.710 --> 02:14:47.100
[Matt]: My guess is that, if that's true,
if you were to look at sleep, I would be surprised

02:14:47.100 --> 02:14:53.020
not to see a sleep benefit by way of an anxiety
reduction. I think, I mean, in my lab, that's

02:14:53.020 --> 02:14:57.030
probably one of the most reliable things that
we see when we deprive people of sleep, of

02:14:57.030 --> 02:14:58.030
any dose.

02:14:58.030 --> 02:14:59.250
[Rhonda]: That anxiety goes up?

02:14:59.250 --> 02:15:03.730
[Matt]: Anxiety goes up. We've done the dose
response curve. We've looked, you know, hour

02:15:03.730 --> 02:15:10.190
by hour by hour. And as soon as you get past
probably about 14 or 15 hours of wakefulness,

02:15:10.190 --> 02:15:14.740
anxiety starts to increase. The further you
go into that sleep deprivation period, the

02:15:14.740 --> 02:15:19.180
more anxious that you get. It's a very robust,
reliable effect.

02:15:19.180 --> 02:15:22.420
[Rhonda]: So what do you think...It sounds
like if you were to give people, like, some

02:15:22.420 --> 02:15:28.860
of the main things, you know, the main interventions
they can do to help improve their sleep, a

02:15:28.860 --> 02:15:32.780
lot of people are interested in prevention,
a lot of people listening and watching are

02:15:32.780 --> 02:15:36.840
really interested, including myself, in prevention.
And it sounds like things that lower anxiety

02:15:36.840 --> 02:15:40.000
are obviously important for...

02:15:40.000 --> 02:15:41.000
[Matt]: Critical.

02:15:41.000 --> 02:15:43.480
[Rhonda]: Yeah, for improving sleep.

02:15:43.480 --> 02:15:48.680
[Matt]: Yeah. I think the prescription I would
have...Well, firstly, I think it's good to

02:15:48.680 --> 02:15:56.400
recognize the sort of those four pillars of
sleep that, you know, depth, duration, continuity,

02:15:56.400 --> 02:16:02.740
regularity, but I think there are five actionable
things that people could do tonight to start

02:16:02.740 --> 02:16:09.110
getting better sleep. And we've mentioned
many of them. The first is darkness. You really

02:16:09.110 --> 02:16:14.390
do need some degree of darkness at night to
release that hormone melatonin, which helps

02:16:14.390 --> 02:16:16.820
trigger the timing of the healthy onset of
sleep.

02:16:16.820 --> 02:16:20.010
[Rhonda]: And you would say about maybe four
hours before your bedtime, or what would you

02:16:20.010 --> 02:16:21.010
say...?

02:16:21.010 --> 02:16:23.820
[Matt]: Yeah, I would say three to four hours
is the time to start thinking about your light

02:16:23.820 --> 02:16:28.540
saturation exposure, certainly in the last
hour before bed. And there are ways that you

02:16:28.540 --> 02:16:33.599
can do that you can install software on your
computer if you really have to look at it,

02:16:33.599 --> 02:16:37.590
but I would advise against that because I
think computers cause and trigger anxiety.

02:16:37.590 --> 02:16:42.380
I think, in fact, if anything, my estimation
right now is that the blue light from those

02:16:42.380 --> 02:16:48.399
screens is detrimental. I think the evidence
is favoring a blockade of melatonin and a

02:16:48.399 --> 02:16:49.399
reduction in REM sleep.

02:16:49.399 --> 02:16:53.179
They did this great study. They took people
with an iPad, one hour of iPad reading versus

02:16:53.179 --> 02:16:59.610
one hour of book reading. iPad reading dropped
or blunted melatonin by over 20%. The peak

02:16:59.610 --> 02:17:05.570
of melatonin didn't arrive until three hours
later. This is one hour of iPad reading. They

02:17:05.570 --> 02:17:06.750
had less REM sleep, and they...

02:17:06.750 --> 02:17:07.979
[Rhonda]: They were reading, like...?

02:17:07.979 --> 02:17:11.960
[Matt]: They were reading just a book under
dim light versus reading the same book on

02:17:11.960 --> 02:17:18.550
an iPad. When they woke up the next morning,
the people who read the iPad felt more unrefreshed.

02:17:18.550 --> 02:17:22.489
They subjectively knew that they had not slept
as well. What was interesting is that when

02:17:22.489 --> 02:17:27.550
they stopped the iPad reading, there was a
washout effect that was a blast radius of

02:17:27.550 --> 02:17:31.849
reading the iPad. And it's continued into
subsequent nights even though they'd stopped

02:17:31.849 --> 02:17:33.149
reading the iPad.

02:17:33.149 --> 02:17:38.880
So I think light is a feature, but I also
think part of the problem with computers and

02:17:38.880 --> 02:17:45.380
iPads and iPhones...and I don't mean to sound
like a prude about this, but they do trigger

02:17:45.380 --> 02:17:53.199
anxiety. They are what I would describe as
anxiogenic pieces of hardware. Unless you

02:17:53.199 --> 02:17:57.639
are, and if you can do this, please write
to me and tell me how you do this, but most

02:17:57.639 --> 02:18:03.040
people get a lot of their anxiety infusion
in part through these devices.

02:18:03.040 --> 02:18:07.540
A recent study in teenagers are actually demonstrated
that part of the reason that they were having

02:18:07.540 --> 02:18:13.740
sleep disruption by using phones was not necessarily
about the light but was because of FOMO, fear

02:18:13.740 --> 02:18:20.330
of missing out, that if you weren't online,
you would miss out on some key social communication.

02:18:20.330 --> 02:18:22.800
And they were suffering because of that, too.

02:18:22.800 --> 02:18:28.159
But I digress. My first recommendation is
watch the light saturation, watch the light

02:18:28.159 --> 02:18:32.840
pollution. And you can think about it like
that in the evening. So an hour before bed,

02:18:32.840 --> 02:18:38.019
certainly, close computers down, try not to
stare at phones, and dim half the lights down

02:18:38.019 --> 02:18:40.939
in the house. It really is powerful.

02:18:40.939 --> 02:18:47.090
The second is temperature. Try to set your
bedroom temperature to somewhere between about

02:18:47.090 --> 02:18:53.019
63 to 66 degrees for most people is optimal,
colder than most people think.

02:18:53.019 --> 02:18:54.450
[Rhonda]: Yeah, that is definitely colder
than...

02:18:54.450 --> 02:19:00.710
[Matt]: Yeah. And if you get cold feet, it's
okay to wear socks, but cold it must be. The

02:19:00.710 --> 02:19:08.269
third thing is what I would suggest is walk
it out, which is don't stay in bed awake.

02:19:08.269 --> 02:19:14.689
This is one of the mistakes that a lot of
people make. In this era, I think most people,

02:19:14.689 --> 02:19:21.979
because of anxiety, were wired and tired.
And one of the problems when you are lying

02:19:21.979 --> 02:19:27.399
in bed awake for a period of time, and I think
more than 20 minutes is not great, because

02:19:27.399 --> 02:19:32.069
what happens is that your brain very quickly
starts to learn the association between being

02:19:32.069 --> 02:19:38.029
in bed is about being awake rather than your
bed being the place of sleep. And so it learns

02:19:38.029 --> 02:19:39.159
this association.

02:19:39.159 --> 02:19:43.250
And so many of the patients that speak to,
they'll say, "Look, you know, I'm falling

02:19:43.250 --> 02:19:47.599
asleep on the couch watching television, and
then I get into bed and I'm wide awake, and

02:19:47.599 --> 02:19:52.359
I don't know why." And the answer is because
you've made the association between your bed

02:19:52.359 --> 02:19:57.649
is the place of wakefulness, not your place
of sleep. So the answer is you need to break

02:19:57.649 --> 02:20:04.819
that association. Get out of bed, go to another
room, in dim light, just read a book, no computers,

02:20:04.819 --> 02:20:08.470
and only return to bed when you feel very
sleepy.

02:20:08.470 --> 02:20:13.279
And the first night this may mean that you're
awake for two or three hours. And it sounds

02:20:13.279 --> 02:20:17.609
bad, and it sounds strange coming from someone
like me, but that's better than staying in

02:20:17.609 --> 02:20:23.220
bed awake for those two or three hours. And
over time, gradually, by only returning bed

02:20:23.220 --> 02:20:27.390
when you're sleepy, your brain will relearn
the association that it once had when you're

02:20:27.390 --> 02:20:32.390
a child, and you can relearn it, which is
that your bed is a place of deep sleep and

02:20:32.390 --> 02:20:36.499
sound sleep. So that's the next thing.

02:20:36.499 --> 02:20:43.930
I think the final two things we've touched
upon a little bit, which is alcohol and caffeine.

02:20:43.930 --> 02:20:50.050
Caffeine, many people know, keeps them awake.
It's a stimulant. It's what we call psychoactive

02:20:50.050 --> 02:20:54.130
stimulant. It's the only psychoactive stimulant,
by the way, that we readily give to our children

02:20:54.130 --> 02:21:03.499
in an unregularized free way, which I think
is a problem. Caffeine has several problems

02:21:03.499 --> 02:21:08.270
with it. Firstly, because of it being a stimulant,
it can keep you awake and it makes it harder

02:21:08.270 --> 02:21:10.699
for you to fall asleep.

02:21:10.699 --> 02:21:14.109
A lot of people, though, will say to me, "Look,
I'm one of those people who can have a cup

02:21:14.109 --> 02:21:18.680
of coffee with dinner and I fall asleep and
I stay asleep, and I'm just fine." Even if

02:21:18.680 --> 02:21:22.899
that's true, we and others have done these
studies, if you give someone a standard dose

02:21:22.899 --> 02:21:28.039
of one cup of coffee in the evening, 200 milligrams
of caffeine, the amount of deep sleep that

02:21:28.039 --> 02:21:34.949
they have is reduced by 20%. You would normally
have to age an individual by 10 or 15 years

02:21:34.949 --> 02:21:40.949
to drop your deep sleep quality by 20%, or
you can do it simply by having a cup of caffeinated

02:21:40.949 --> 02:21:47.819
drink or coffee in the evening. So caffeine
is a problem.

02:21:47.819 --> 02:21:52.729
The other problem with caffeine is its duration
of action. Caffeine has a half-life of about

02:21:52.729 --> 02:21:57.830
six or seven hours. And a half-life simply
means the amount of time it takes for a 50%

02:21:57.830 --> 02:22:03.680
of the drug to still be in your system or
50% of it to be cleared. Caffeine has a quarter

02:22:03.680 --> 02:22:08.270
life of about 12 hours. In other words, if
you have a cup of coffee at noon, a quarter

02:22:08.270 --> 02:22:12.149
of that caffeine is still circulating in your
brain at midnight.

02:22:12.149 --> 02:22:15.989
So if you have a cup of coffee at noon, it's
the equivalent of getting into bed at midnight.

02:22:15.989 --> 02:22:20.390
And just before you turn out the lights, you
snick a quarter of a cup of Starbucks, and

02:22:20.390 --> 02:22:24.249
you hope for a good night of sleep, you know,
it's probably not gonna happen.

02:22:24.249 --> 02:22:30.630
So the advice would be try to cut caffeine
off around about midday if you can. And even

02:22:30.630 --> 02:22:35.560
if you're someone who, you know, can fall
asleep fine, stay asleep, you should just

02:22:35.560 --> 02:22:38.880
know that caffeine can still impact your sleep.

02:22:38.880 --> 02:22:43.420
It's what usually creates the vicious cycle,
by the way, that those people will wake up

02:22:43.420 --> 02:22:47.460
the next day, they feel unrefreshed and unrestored
by their sleep, they don't remember waking

02:22:47.460 --> 02:22:51.420
up, so they don't think it's the cup of coffee,
but now they start reaching for two cups of

02:22:51.420 --> 02:22:55.979
coffee in the morning rather than one. They've
got now more caffeine in the system. The next

02:22:55.979 --> 02:23:00.160
night, they have even less deep sleep. The
next morning, they wake up even less refreshed.

02:23:00.160 --> 02:23:03.510
And now they drink more caffeine. Self-fulfilling
prophecy.

02:23:03.510 --> 02:23:10.521
Final one is alcohol. Alcohol is probably
the most misunderstood sleep aid or sleep

02:23:10.521 --> 02:23:15.979
drug. It's what most people usually reach
for when over-the-counter medications have

02:23:15.979 --> 02:23:22.149
failed. Alcohol is a sedative. It's a class
of drugs that we call the sedatives. And sedation

02:23:22.149 --> 02:23:27.340
is not sleep. So when you drink alcohol, what
you're doing is sedating your cortex. You're

02:23:27.340 --> 02:23:32.540
just knocking yourself out. And that's why
you think that you fall asleep faster.

02:23:32.540 --> 02:23:37.130
There are two other problems with alcohol.
Firstly, alcohol will litter your sleep with

02:23:37.130 --> 02:23:41.159
many more awakenings throughout the night.
And in fact, some people can even see this

02:23:41.159 --> 02:23:46.290
on their sleep trackers even though they're
not necessarily as accurate as my sleep laboratory

02:23:46.290 --> 02:23:52.439
would be. Even with that less accurate measure,
you can still see the impact of alcohol in

02:23:52.439 --> 02:23:57.770
sleep. So it litters your sleep with awakenings,
fragmenting your sleep. So this comes back

02:23:57.770 --> 02:24:04.069
to the third of the four pillars of good sleep,
which is continuity. It takes away your continuous

02:24:04.069 --> 02:24:06.430
asleep, and it makes it fragmented.

02:24:06.430 --> 02:24:11.239
The final part of alcohol is that it's one
of the best chemicals that we know for suppressing

02:24:11.239 --> 02:24:18.130
REM sleep alongside marijuana. Now, by the
way, I should say that's THC-specific. If

02:24:18.130 --> 02:24:24.260
you look at CBD, the evidence seems to be
less clear. CBD actually doesn't seem to be

02:24:24.260 --> 02:24:28.270
as detrimental to your sleep as THC. If anything...

02:24:28.270 --> 02:24:33.369
[Rhonda]: Yeah, because a lot of people, I
mean, again, this is just anecdotal, talk

02:24:33.369 --> 02:24:37.020
about how marijuana improve their sleep.

02:24:37.020 --> 02:24:42.499
[Matt]: Yes, yeah. So marijuana...We have
two separate sort of the active from the inactive

02:24:42.499 --> 02:24:50.220
component. THC, tetrahydrocannabinol, is the
active component. And CBD is the sort of the

02:24:50.220 --> 02:24:51.810
non-hallucinogenic component of that.

02:24:51.810 --> 02:24:54.050
[Rhonda]: They're both in if people are taking
a whole plant here.

02:24:54.050 --> 02:24:58.840
[Matt]: Typically, yeah. Yeah, exactly. Now
with strains and drops that you can buy, you

02:24:58.840 --> 02:25:02.630
can separate those out, you can play around
with the ratios, and you can get very low

02:25:02.630 --> 02:25:10.840
THC to very high CBD. THC does tend to decrease
the time it takes you to fall asleep, but

02:25:10.840 --> 02:25:14.660
it tends to make you sometimes wake up more
throughout the night, but it certainly does

02:25:14.660 --> 02:25:16.489
seem to block REM sleep.

02:25:16.489 --> 02:25:22.279
One of the other problems with THC dosing
of sleep is that you become dependent on that

02:25:22.279 --> 02:25:29.720
for sleep. And when you stop using THC for
sleep, you have quite bad rebound insomnia,

02:25:29.720 --> 02:25:33.790
which leads to then a perpetuating cycle of
dependency. And I think, you know, I'm never

02:25:33.790 --> 02:25:39.739
keen for dependency on anything, be it dependency
on, you know, any, you know, food substance

02:25:39.739 --> 02:25:45.569
or anything. I think you should, you know,
be able to generate all of the physiological

02:25:45.569 --> 02:25:49.449
pathways and processes that you need, you
know, naturally without dependency.

02:25:49.449 --> 02:25:54.999
CBD is interesting, though. There is nowhere
near enough data for someone like me to make

02:25:54.999 --> 02:25:58.850
any recommendation. So all I can do is tell
you the very limited data that there is right

02:25:58.850 --> 02:26:05.489
now. CBD does not seem to produce the degree
of REM sleep impairment that we've seen with

02:26:05.489 --> 02:26:13.710
THC. What's interesting is that low-dose CBD
actually seems to be wake-promoting. So you

02:26:13.710 --> 02:26:20.850
actually are sort of forcing yourself more
awake. High-dose CBD seems to help people

02:26:20.850 --> 02:26:23.920
sleep more consistently.

02:26:23.920 --> 02:26:28.729
I would have thought it would it be the opposite,
that low-dose would have been better than

02:26:28.729 --> 02:26:32.449
high-dose, but the opposite seems to be true.
Now we don't know about the dependency. We

02:26:32.449 --> 02:26:37.779
don't know about the long-term effects. So
I am not going to sit here and give any recommendations

02:26:37.779 --> 02:26:44.949
regarding THC use or CBD use. If you're using
any compound, be it alcohol, be it a sleeping

02:26:44.949 --> 02:26:49.210
pill, which are...sleeping pills, by the way,
come with deathly consequences and higher

02:26:49.210 --> 02:26:51.560
risk of cancer. Or you're using...

02:26:51.560 --> 02:26:52.560
[Rhonda]: Really?

02:26:52.560 --> 02:26:53.560
[Matt]: Yeah, markedly increased risk.

02:26:53.560 --> 02:26:56.490
[Rhonda]: Is that because there's something
directly the sleeping pills are doing, or

02:26:56.490 --> 02:27:00.860
because the way it affects your...? What does
it do to your sleep, sleeping pills? A lot

02:27:00.860 --> 02:27:02.199
of people take Ambien.

02:27:02.199 --> 02:27:09.890
[Matt]: So in the past month, 10 million Americans
have swallowed some kind of sleeping aid,

02:27:09.890 --> 02:27:16.199
either a prescription or over-the-counter,
monumental amounts. You know, I often joke

02:27:16.199 --> 02:27:22.239
that I think, it's not really a joking topic,
but, you know, it took George Lucas about

02:27:22.239 --> 02:27:29.500
40 years to amass $4 billion in profit from
the Star Wars franchise. It took Ambien less

02:27:29.500 --> 02:27:35.310
than 20 months to amass $4 billion in profit.
That tells me everything about the insufficiency

02:27:35.310 --> 02:27:42.109
of sleep and the desperate need for sleep
in this modern 21st-century era.

02:27:42.109 --> 02:27:47.130
But the problem is Ambien isn't part of that
same class of drugs that alcohol is. It's

02:27:47.130 --> 02:27:51.869
what we call a sedative hypnotic. It works
on the same receptor, which is the GABA receptor.

02:27:51.869 --> 02:27:57.290
Now it tickles the GABA receptor in a different
way to that which alcohol does. But what we

02:27:57.290 --> 02:28:03.029
found is that sleeping pills, and I won't
name any names but including the one that

02:28:03.029 --> 02:28:08.140
you described, they are sedating the brain.
You're not going into naturalistic sleep.

02:28:08.140 --> 02:28:12.159
If I look at the electrical signature of your
sleep when you're on a sleeping pill versus

02:28:12.159 --> 02:28:16.000
natural sleep, it's not the same.

02:28:16.000 --> 02:28:21.439
Secondly, what we found is that those sleeping
pills can often come with a grogginess in

02:28:21.439 --> 02:28:27.949
the morning and some forgetfulness. Third,
what we've found is that in animal models,

02:28:27.949 --> 02:28:32.291
and this is work that was done by Markus Frank,
who's a wonderful friend and colleague, he

02:28:32.291 --> 02:28:37.210
was looking at how the brain rewires itself
during sleep. And the brain does, particularly

02:28:37.210 --> 02:28:39.680
during the development.

02:28:39.680 --> 02:28:45.569
And he has a model in animals, where, if you
sort of put a patch on one of the eyes when

02:28:45.569 --> 02:28:50.770
the visual cortex is developing, the visual
cortex shifts over to developing more wiring

02:28:50.770 --> 02:28:56.569
to the eye that remains open. And it's called
the monocular deprivation paradigm of brain

02:28:56.569 --> 02:29:01.850
plasticity, and it's a very well worked out
model of brain plasticity. If you give those

02:29:01.850 --> 02:29:07.859
animals some exposure once you patch the eye
to the eye that remains, you drive learning

02:29:07.859 --> 02:29:15.189
and plasticity, and then you allow it to sleep,
sleep will strengthen the synaptic connections

02:29:15.189 --> 02:29:17.680
that have been made during the day by about
100%.

02:29:17.680 --> 02:29:18.680
[Rhonda]: Wow.

02:29:18.680 --> 02:29:23.760
[Matt]: So sleep is almost as powerful as
experience during the day. That's how sort

02:29:23.760 --> 02:29:31.350
of strong and powerful it is. But what he
then did was a study where he dosed those

02:29:31.350 --> 02:29:38.010
animals with Ambien. Now it turns out that
those animals slept even longer, if you look

02:29:38.010 --> 02:29:42.220
at the data, than the animals who weren't
dosed on Ambien. And the prediction would

02:29:42.220 --> 02:29:47.730
be, surely, they would have as much if not
more of that wonderful brain plasticity. The

02:29:47.730 --> 02:29:55.550
opposite was true. Ambien-induced sleep resulted
in a 50% unwiring of the connections that

02:29:55.550 --> 02:29:59.910
have been made during day rather than potentiating
them.

02:29:59.910 --> 02:30:04.380
That frightens me. Because if you look at
the prescription age of sleeping medications

02:30:04.380 --> 02:30:09.619
over the past decade, it's coming down and
down. I don't know how long it's going to

02:30:09.619 --> 02:30:15.040
be before prescription medication comes in
to a pediatric realm. And if those data hold

02:30:15.040 --> 02:30:22.609
up, it makes me worried. So I'm coming off
topic a little bit, but we know that sleeping

02:30:22.609 --> 02:30:27.369
pills are associated with a markedly higher
risk of death, as well as cancer, as well

02:30:27.369 --> 02:30:34.669
as your susceptibility to infection, particularly
in pneumonia.

02:30:34.669 --> 02:30:41.380
But returning to alcohol, it is definitely
one of the most, I think, misunderstood drugs.

02:30:41.380 --> 02:30:49.189
But what I was saying regarding THC, alcohol,
sleeping pills, if you are using anything

02:30:49.189 --> 02:30:55.479
to help you sleep, I think you have to ask
yourself, are you just really treating, you

02:30:55.479 --> 02:31:02.569
know, an open wound and not really actually
trying to stitch it up? Because what that

02:31:02.569 --> 02:31:08.260
is simply doing is masking a problem that
you're not dealing with, you know. Why is

02:31:08.260 --> 02:31:09.510
it, like...?

02:31:09.510 --> 02:31:13.560
And this is not a criticism, I'm sorry if
my voice sounds like that, and it's not, you

02:31:13.560 --> 02:31:17.820
know, I'm so sympathetic to people who have
sleep problems. We see them all of the time

02:31:17.820 --> 02:31:23.750
here. But you have to ask why. Why is it that
you're struggling with sleep? Is it because

02:31:23.750 --> 02:31:28.490
you're of a certain chronotype and you don't
understand your chronotype and you're sleeping

02:31:28.490 --> 02:31:34.989
at the wrong phase of the 24-hour period and
it's masquerading as insomnia. Or do you have

02:31:34.989 --> 02:31:42.199
too much anxiety in your life and you're blunting
that anxiety with things like alcohol or THC

02:31:42.199 --> 02:31:46.520
or sleeping pills? You know, you're just kicking
the can down the road. You're just hitting

02:31:46.520 --> 02:31:52.279
the mute button. But the movie is still playing
of damage. Whatever is causing that sleep

02:31:52.279 --> 02:31:56.979
disruption, you know, is still there. You're
just sedating your brain and trying to mask

02:31:56.979 --> 02:31:58.119
it.

02:31:58.119 --> 02:32:02.739
So I think people who are using those things,
if they're having sleep difficulties, you

02:32:02.739 --> 02:32:07.949
should ask yourself, could I examine my life
and really think more about what it is that

02:32:07.949 --> 02:32:13.979
is preventing me from sleeping. What's good
is that you don't have to turn to any of those

02:32:13.979 --> 02:32:18.510
because there is a non-pharmacological treatment
but is just as effective as sleeping pills

02:32:18.510 --> 02:32:23.739
in the short-term. It is completely safe.
And it is more efficacious in the long-term.

02:32:23.739 --> 02:32:30.499
And it's called cognitive behavioral therapy
for insomnia or CBTI.

02:32:30.499 --> 02:32:34.540
Based on its efficacious nature, and they've
been done lots of randomized clinical control

02:32:34.540 --> 02:32:41.160
trials, it is just as powerful as sleeping
pills in the short-term. But when you stop

02:32:41.160 --> 02:32:44.729
working with your therapist, and you work
with a therapist for several sessions across

02:32:44.729 --> 02:32:51.770
several weeks, when you stop working with
a therapist, you don't go back to the bad

02:32:51.770 --> 02:32:55.970
sleep that you have. You continue on with
your good sleep. Unlike sleeping pills, which

02:32:55.970 --> 02:33:00.479
is when you stop them, you have what we call
rebound insomnia, which is that you tend to

02:33:00.479 --> 02:33:04.739
go back to the bad sleep that you are having,
if not worse sleep that you are having before

02:33:04.739 --> 02:33:07.030
you started taking sleeping pills.

02:33:07.030 --> 02:33:12.600
And the danger surround sleeping pills and
their lack of true benefit above and beyond

02:33:12.600 --> 02:33:21.949
placebo, which is, if you look at these meta
analyses, in 2015 or 2016, the American College

02:33:21.949 --> 02:33:27.439
of Physicians made a landmark recommendation.
They said that sleeping pills must no longer

02:33:27.439 --> 02:33:32.319
be the first line recommended treatment for
insomnia. It must be cognitive behavioral

02:33:32.319 --> 02:33:39.420
therapy for insomnia because of both the deleterious,
deathly, and carcinogenic consequences of...or

02:33:39.420 --> 02:33:43.350
association with...I shouldn't say cause because
we don't yet know cause. But certainly they

02:33:43.350 --> 02:33:49.399
are associated with higher mortality risk
and higher cancer rates. CBTI, this cognitive

02:33:49.399 --> 02:33:53.220
behavioral therapy, must be the first-line
recommendation treatment.

02:33:53.220 --> 02:33:58.420
The problem is most doctors don't know about
it because most doctors get a less than two

02:33:58.420 --> 02:34:03.029
hours of sleep education during the medical
curriculum. And this is another crusade that

02:34:03.029 --> 02:34:07.170
I am on. I am desperately trying to reach
out to all medical curriculum, not just here

02:34:07.170 --> 02:34:12.100
in the United States but in all nations where
you have medical programs. We need a greater

02:34:12.100 --> 02:34:17.819
degree of medical education. Our doctors are
not at fault at, you know, not understanding

02:34:17.819 --> 02:34:22.130
sleep. They have not been educated about sleep,
you know.

02:34:22.130 --> 02:34:26.450
So I teach a class here at University of California
Berkeley. It's usually around 500 or 600 kids.

02:34:26.450 --> 02:34:31.529
It's the Science of Sleep. And they get 25,
hopefully, meaningful lectures about sleep

02:34:31.529 --> 02:34:39.109
across the semester. They will have had somewhere
between 10 to 15 times more sleep education

02:34:39.109 --> 02:34:42.970
than the standard doctor that you will go
and see. You know, most doctors don't ask

02:34:42.970 --> 02:34:47.979
how much sleep that you're getting despite
it being this fundamental, you know...Sleep

02:34:47.979 --> 02:34:55.010
is a life support system, and it is mother
nature's best effort yet at immortality. And

02:34:55.010 --> 02:35:00.851
it's a key to disease, and it's a key to potentially
helping treat or even prevent disease. Most

02:35:00.851 --> 02:35:03.939
doctors don't ask because most doctors aren't
educated.

02:35:03.939 --> 02:35:06.840
[Rhonda]: Right. Nutrition is another one
of those areas.

02:35:06.840 --> 02:35:08.789
[Matt]: It's right up that, you know...

02:35:08.789 --> 02:35:12.270
[Rhonda]: But thankfully, we have people like
you who are doing phenomenal research and

02:35:12.270 --> 02:35:18.779
also communicating that research quite nicely.
I read your book. It was a really great book.

02:35:18.779 --> 02:35:19.859
It's "Why We Sleep."

02:35:19.859 --> 02:35:20.859
[Matt]: Thank you.

02:35:20.859 --> 02:35:25.899
[Rhonda]: So if people do want to learn more
about your research, about sleep, about anything

02:35:25.899 --> 02:35:29.350
related to sleep or what you do, they can
